<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Nightmare,' `Betrayed' Lead Box Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summer Movies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Nightmare on Elm Street'' made a killing at
the nation's movie theaters for the third-consecutive weekend as
summer box-office revenues reached about $1.7 billion, the highest
ever.
   With Labor Day weekend receipts of more than $43 million, this
year's summer movie season surpassed 1987's record of $1.59
billion. The season runs from late May to Labor Day.
   The top eight spots in the box-office list were mostly unchanged
from a week ago, with ``Betrayed'' emerging as something of a
late-summer hit.
   ``A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master'' took in $6.4
million last weekend. ``Betrayed,'' a movie about white
supremacists, finished second with $5.5 million.
   Finishing third was ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' with $5.1 million,
followed by ``Die Hard'' in fourth with $4.8 million and ``Who
Framed Roger Rabbit'' in fifth place, with $4.4 million.
   ``Cocktail'' finished sixth with $4.4 million, just $60,000 less
than ``Roger Rabbit,'' ``Young Guns'' was seventh with $4.1
million, ``Married to the Mob'' was eighth with $3.4 million,
``Big'' ninth with $2.5 million and ``Tucker'' 10th with $2.3
million.
   Here are the top films for the long holiday weekend as tallied
by Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of
theater screens, average per screen, total gross and number of
weeks in release.
   1. ``Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' New Line,
$6.4 million, 1,758 screens, $3,660 per screen, $34.2 million,
three weeks.
   2. ``Betrayed,'' United Artists, $5.5 million, 1,099 screens,
$5,001 per screen, $12.8 million, two weeks.
   3. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM, $5.1 million, 1,187 screens,
$4,294 per screen, $37.8 million, eight weeks.
   4. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $4.8 million, 1,461 screens,
$3,262 per screen, $58.5 million, eight weeks.
   5. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $4.43 million, 1,588
screens, $2,792 per screen, $130.1 million, 11 weeks.
   6. ``Cocktail,'' Disney, $4.37 million, 1,404 screens, $3,115
per screen, $57.3 million, six weeks.
   7. ``Young Guns,'' 20th Century Fox, $4.1 million, 1,399
screens, $2,386 per screen, $28.9 million, four weeks.
   8. ``Married to the Mob,'' Orion, $3.4 million, 828 screens,
$4,113 per screen, $12 million, three weeks.
   9. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.5 million, 1,177 screens,
$1,671 per screen, $97.8 million, 14 weeks.
   10. ``Tucker,'' Paramount, $2.3 million, 706 screens, $3,299 per
screen, $14.4 million, four weeks.
</TEXT>
