<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Iran-Stock Exchange,0134</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran's First Stock Exchange Opens</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's first stock exchange has opened
and is offering shares of big industrial establishments to the
public, the country's official Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, on Tuesday quoted Morteza
Arami, Managing Director of the Bank of Industry and Mines as
saying shares will be offered at determined ceiling and base prices.
   They will be sold to the highest bidder within the pre-set
limits, he said.
   Aramai was quoted as saying the establishments, affiliated to
the bank, have annual sales of 150 billion riyals ($2 billion) and
include factories producing 92 percent of the glass needed in the
country, five cement plants, two chinaware factories, a tile
factory, 33 textile mills and dozens of other enterprises.
</TEXT>
