<1ST_LINE>d a PM-Perry'sComeback     09-07 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Perry's Comeback,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Lottery Host Convicted In Rigging Scandal Makes Comeback</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former host of the Pennsylvania Lottery's
TV drawing who was convicted in a scheme to rig the game is making
a television comeback: as host of a bowling show.
   ``I was apprehensive. You could say I still am,'' Nick Perry
said. ``There's bound to be somebody out there dissatisfied with my
coming back.''
   Perry, 71, returned to television Tuesday night on ``BPA Jackpot
Bowling,'' a twice-nightly show on cable television in the
Pittsburgh area.
   Perry has taped 30 of 64 programs scheduled for an initial
13-week run.
   Perry was host of the nightly lottery telecast and an announcer
on a Pittsburgh TV station when the daily lottery number came up
666 on April 24, 1980. Perry and several other people were
convicted of rigging the drawing by putting weights in the pingpong
balls used to select the number.
   Perry served two years in prison and a year at a halfway house.
He now supervises couriers for a medical testing company in
suburban Ross Township.
   Perry still insists he is innocent.
   ``No one in my family and none of my close friends ever hit the
three sixes,'' he said. ``Why wouldn't I give it to them _ my
family, who could have used the money?''
</TEXT>
