<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-07 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rice Remains `Symbol of Japanese Protectionism'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The recent U.S. agreement with Japan on beef
and citrus was hailed as a major step toward improved trade
relations, but an Agriculture Department economist says rice
remains ``a symbol of Japanese protectionism.''
   Although the United States continues to press Japan to open its
rice market to imports, only a small quantity can come in for use
in alcohol or confectionery products, says Lois A. Caplan of the
department's Economic Research Service. Returning travelers also
are allowed to bring in small amounts.
   The United States for years has been after Japan to liberalize
its import policies so more American products can flow into the
Japanese market. Japan is the U.S. farmer's largest foreign market,
but officials say freer trade would open the door even wider.
   After months of negotiations, the United States and Japan signed
a pact on July 5 which gradually widens access to the Japanese
market by 1991. However, Japan adamantly refused to budge on the
question of rice.
   Although Japanese consumers pay more than twice as much for rice
as Americans do, sentiment is strong in Japan to protect the
nation's rice farmers.
   In September 1986, the Rice Millers' Association, a private U.S.
trade group, filed a complaint against Japan under section 301 of
the 1974 Trade Act, charging that Japan's virtual ban on rice
imports constituted unfair trade practices.
   ``The U.S. government decided not to pursue the 301 action
against Japan but urged Japan to discuss its rice policy in the
current round of global trade negotiations,'' Caplan said. ``Japan
has agreed to consultations under the new round but has repeatedly
refused to have bilateral discussions with the United States.''
   Caplan, whose analysis is in a report about U.S. trade with
Pacific Rim countries, said rice is a ``very sensitive issue'' in
Japan because it is a staple food and is important in many Japanese
traditions.
   ``Many older Japanese have bitter memories of hunger during and
immediately after the Second World War, and still have ties to the
farming community,'' she said. ``The Japanese government and the
LDP (Liberal Democratic Party), which derives much of its support
from farmers, have steadfastly rejected demands to liberalize the
rice market and have promised to maintain the present policy of
self-sufficiency in rice.''
   In most of the last two decades, Japan has produced more rice
than it has consumed, leading to periods of burdensome surpluses.
The unneeded rice inventories were reduced by subsidizing exports,
using rice in livestock feed, or by limiting production.
   The criticism of Japan's restrictive rice policies and strong
pressure by its foreign trading partners have started
``unprecedented debate in Japan over its agricultural policy,
including import restrictions,'' Caplan said.
   Consequently, he said, the discussion and social changes taking
place in Japan ``are likely to make it politically feasible for
Japan to move toward freer market access for agricultural imports''
down the road.
   ``Changes include an aging population with fading memories of
World War II food shortages, a decline in the political influence
of farm groups, and an increasing awareness of the high cost of
domestic agricultural products compared with overseas prices,''
Caplan said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grants totaling $2 million are being awarded
by the Agriculture Department to 18 predominantly black land-grant
colleges and universities.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said Tuesday the grants will
help the schools upgrade instructional programs in agriculture,
strengthen faculty, and recruit and retain minority students in the
fields of agriculture and food sciences.
   The grants will be administered by the department's Office of
Minority Research and Teaching Programs, which primarily serves the
interests of colleges and universities authorized under an 1890
federal law, the Second Morrill Act.
   Officials said the grants, minus administrative costs, will
provide each of the recipients a total of $102,496.
   The schools are:
   Alabama A&M University, Huntsville.
   Alcorn State University, Lorman, Miss.
   University of Arkansas-Pine Bluff.
   Delaware State College, Dover.
   Florida A&M University, Tallahassee.
   Fort Valley State College, Fort Valley, Ga.
   Kentucky State University, Frankfort.
   Southern University, Baton Rouge, La.
   University of Maryland-Eastern Shore, Princess Anne.
   Lincoln University, Jefferson City, Mo.
   North Carolina A&T State University, Greensboro.
   Tuskegee University, Tuskegee, Ala.
   Langston University, Langston, Okla.
   South Carolina State College, Orangeburg.
   Tennessee State University, Nashville.
   Prairie View A&M University, Texas.
   University of the District of Columbia, Washington, D.C.
   Virginia State University, Petersburg.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought more U.S. corn for
delivery during the current marketing year, the Agriculture
Department says.
   Officials said Tuesday that an additional 802,400 metric tons of
U.S. corn have been sold by private exporters for delivery during
the 1988-89 marketing year which began on Sept. 1.
   More than 1.7 million tons of corn have been sold to the Soviets
in the last week, according to USDA announcements.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 802,400 tons of
corn would be about 31.6 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.68 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the new sale
could have a farm value of around $84.7 million.
   No indication was given whether the recent new corn sales would
count under the current long-term grain supply agreement with the
Soviet Union or be carried forward separately in case a new pact is
forthcoming.
   The current five-year pact is set to expire Sept. 30 and
negotiators are trying to work out a new one, or at least an
extension of the current agreement, to take effect on Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
