<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0211EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ForestFireFunds     09-07 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Forest Fire Funds,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Forest Service May Have To Raid Trust Fund To Pay For Firefighting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Forest Service says it may be forced
for the second straight year to raid a reforestation trust fund to
pay its fast-mounting firefighting bill.
   The Forest Service already has spent $190 million this year on
firefighting, and the Western fire season is just entering its
traditional peak month.
   An Interior Department appropriations bill now pending in
Congress includes $125 million for firefighting and Rep. Peter
DeFazio, D-Ore., said Tuesday that most of it will be used to repay
the Knutsen-Vanderberg trust fund from last year's borrowings.
   The Forest Service spent $265 million in 1987 to fight Western
fires, most of which struck in late August and September.
   While Congress has traditionally bailed out the Forest Service,
DeFazio said ``smoke and mirrors'' budgeting could eventually leave
the trust fund short of money.
   A Forest Service budget official said no decision has been made
on whether to borrow from the Knutsen-Vanderberg trust fund.
   ``It's a possibility,'' said Robert Gordon, an assistant
director of the agency.
   He said the fund typically has about $400 million in it and the
programs it finances generally cost about $200 million a year.
Money from the fund comes from fees timber operators pay when they
log national forests and is earmarked for reforestation projects.
   ``It will eventually catch up with you if you don't replenish
it, but I think we will be all right this year,'' Gordon said.
</TEXT>
