<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Dukakis     09-07 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Dukakis,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Denies Anger Over Being Excluded From Illinois Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson says he is eager to get on with
his role in the fall Democratic campaign although he was excluded
from a meeting between presidential nominee Michael Dukakis and
Democratic leaders in his home state of Illinois.
   Dukakis met in Illinois on Tuesday with elected leaders and
fund-raisers, including Sen. Paul Simon, Rep. Dan Rostenkowski,
other members of Congress and other elected officials. Though at
home in Chicago, Jackson was not invited.
   Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach said the reason was that Jackson
is a national leader and the meeting in Illinois was focusing on
the Dukakis state strategy and organization.
   ``I didn't know anything about it other than the press
inquiries,'' Jackson said in a telephone interview from Chicago.
``So I have no comment to make.''
   Sources said Jackson was angered by the exclusion, and one
associate, speaking on condition of anonymity, described him as
``seething.'' But Jackson said he was neither hurt nor angry.
   ``I just hate for people to be allowed to put words in my mouth
or give some adjective description of what my emotions are,'' he
said. ``I'm working. I'm hopeful. I'm registering voters.''
   He said he had spoken Monday night and Tuesday morning to
Dukakis vice chairman John Sasso. The two are to meet Thursday to
discuss the future of the campaign.
   Jackson said that ``areas dealing with campaign direction and
priorities still have to be worked out.'' He said he hoped to
discuss his ongoing voter registration efforts with the campaign.
And he said he hoped to discuss targeting the message of the
Democratic ticket to Teamsters, working women, family farmers and
others who ``need to be Democrats.''
   Asked if he would get a schedule of campaign appearances at this
meeting, Jackson said, ``I certainly hope so.''
   Asked if he feels Dukakis has been slow to involve him in the
campaign, Jackson said, ``There are some decisions the campaign has
to make about how it will employ its volunteers,'' including people
like New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, Sen. Edward Kennedy of
Massachusetts and himself.
   ``I assume that's the kind of thing Sasso will be doing,'' he
said referring to Dukakis' close confidant, who has just returned
to the campaign.
   ``The plans are incomplete,'' he said. ``I hope they will be
complete soon ... I hope before this week is out that all of the
remaining areas will be resolved and we'll be on our way.''
   Dach said the meeting with Sasso will include discussion of
``how we can best work together, places, details, themes.'' But he
also indicated the campaign sees the meeting as involving
``evolving issues that need to be addressed and refined.''
   Jackson has declined to criticize Dukakis, despite some
incidents that some Jackson supporters have perceived as slights.
   The most recent involved reports that the Dukakis camp had
conducted polling that found Jackson had high negatives in some
states where he beat Dukakis in the primaries and that the Dukakis
officials said they did not want Jackson campaigning in those
states.
   While these reports came from sources close to Jackson and the
national Democratic Party, Jackson himself said he had received no
such direction.
   ``I don't have anything in writing on that,'' he said.
</TEXT>
