<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan     09-07 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Criticizes Carter, Media in Political Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is campaigning against the
Carter administration and the news media as he attempts to convince
voters that he has put America's defense policy on the right track
and the Democrats would derail it.
   The president jumped into the post-Labor Day election fray
Tuesday as he ended a three-week California vacation and returned
to the White House, where he planned a meeting with Republican
congressional leaders today.
   ``It will be a meeting to map strategy and to get reports from
the leaders on what they found out from their constituents during
the recess,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters
aboard Air Force One.
   The congressional recess coincided with Reagan's vacation, which
was spent mainly at his ranch north of Santa Barbara, with a
five-day interval in Los Angeles.
   On his way back to Washington, Reagan stopped in Louisville,
Ky., to address the American Legion's 70th national convention,
asking, ``After eight hard years of rebuilding America's strength,
do we really want to return to a Disneyland defense policy?''
   Deriding the policies of the president from whom he wrested the
White House in 1980, Reagan said: ``An administration from the
party of Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and John Kennedy had,
incredibly, lost faith in the place of America, the role for good
that America played, the moral mission of America in the world.''
   Reagan also reminded the Legionnaires of something he said when
he addressed their convention during his 1980 campaign: ``Once we
have the (military) programs to reverse the trends now in favor of
the Soviet Union, we must strive for arms limitation agreements
that will further that security _ including significant arms
reductions _ so long as they are equitable and based on strict
reciprocity.
   ``Actually, I didn't read that for your benefit, but for the
benefit of my gang on the (press) platform back there,'' he told
the audience at Louisville's Commonwealth Convention Center.
   ``They keep saying that the INF agreement I signed with Mr.
Gorbachev _ the first significant, equitable and reciprocal
reduction of U.S. and Soviet nuclear missiles in history shows how
I've grown in my job. But I'm waiting for them to acknowledge the
simple truth of what I've been saying for eight years about
strength being the only road to peace.''
   Reagan also touched on some of the legislative issues facing him
as he headed back to Washington with 4{ months remaining in his
term.
   ``Earlier this year, the majority in Congress turned a deaf ear
to our pleas, and to those in Central America who hunger for the
freedoms we in the United States take for granted,'' he said. ``We
hope that with your help we might still convince this Congress to
do what's right.''
   The Senate has passed a bill, which the administration describes
as minimally acceptable, to resume assistance to rebels fighting
the leftist government of Nicaragua. The House has not acted.
   The president also said that ``before I leave office I want to
be sure that we have a Cabinet-level Department of Veterans
Affairs.'' A bill to upgrade the status of the Veterans
Administration has passed the Senate and awaits House action.
   Much of the speech was devoted to denunciation of the previous
Democratic administration and of the Democrats now seeking to
regain the White House.
   Reagan at one point claimed that Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis wants to scrap the Trident missile and the Stealth bomber.
Dukakis actually favors both.
</TEXT>
