<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Bangladesh     09-07 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Bangladesh,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Sends $3.6 Million To Aid Bangladesh Victims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has committed $3.6 million in
emergency assistance for flood-plagued Bangladesh, and a private
U.S. group says it will provide another $4 million for medicine and
food.
   The Agency for International Development's office of foreign
disaster assistance said Tuesday that the government assistance
will include 10,000 tons of food and more than 2,000 tons of corn
and wheat seed. U.S. disaster management experts also will be sent
to Dhaka to help assess the situation and advise on further
assistance, the agency said.
   Oxfam America, a private humanitarian organization, also
announced its relief program on Tuesday.
   ``Of the 500 deaths that have been reported officially, many
were caused by consuming contaminated food and drinking water, and
as a result of snakebites,'' Oxfam said in a statement from its
Boston headquarters.
   ``The greatest medical need is for water purification tablets,
which we are attempting to secure in large quantities and deliver
as quickly as humanly possible.''
   The organization said experts fear that ``because most roads and
highways have been out ... thousands of families will starve to
death unless supplies reach them soon.''
   Oxfam blamed the second consecutive year of major floods in
Bangladesh on massive destruction of trees in northern India and
China, allowing water to pour unchecked into the deltas of
Bangladesh.
   ``The deforestation of the region has stripped away many of the
natural barriers that protect against the waters of the Ganges
River and the melted snows of the Himalayas,'' the organization
said.
   Oxfam said it is concerned that ``many more deaths will occur in
Bangladesh in the years to come with continued inattention to this
problem.''
</TEXT>
