<DOCNO> AP880907-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TreasuryBills     09-07 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rates Mixed On T-bills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities were mixed in the latest auction with rates on
three-month bills unchanged while rates on six-month bills fell to
the lowest level in a month.
   The Treasury Department sold $7 billion in three-month bills
Tuesday at an average discount rate of 7.26 percent, the same as
last week. Another $7 billion was sold in six-month bills at an
average discount rate of 7.4 percent, down from 7.5 percent last
week.
   The rates on three-month bills this week and last were the
highest since they sold for 7.3 percent on Aug. 5, 1985. The
decline in six-month bills put them at their lowest level since
they averaged 7.26 percent on Aug. 8.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.5 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,816.50 and and 7.79 percent for six-month bills selling for
$9,625.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Tuesday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate home mortgages, fell to 8.24
percent last week after averaging 8.28 percent the week before.
</TEXT>
