<1ST_LINE>r i PM-AmnestyConcert     09-07 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amnesty Concert,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Human Rights Concert Draws Big Crowd In Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock music fans traveled from
throughout the Soviet bloc to hear Bruce Springsteen, Peter Gabriel
and other stars sing for human rights on the third stop of Amnesty
International's global rock tour.
   The concert Tuesday opened to a sell-out crowd of 80,000,
including senior communist officials.
   It was a rare event in Eastern Europe.
   Individual Western rock groups have been allowed to play in
Communist European capitals, but this was believed to be the first
such group performance in the Soviet bloc.
   The Budapest concert also was unusual because it was sponsored
by a Western human rights organization. The West has often accused
East bloc countries of violating human rights commitments.
   The state news agency MTI reported that ``chief patron'' of the
concert was Hungarian top ideologist Janos Berecz, a Politburo
member. It said Soviet government spokesman Gennady Gerasimov also
was present, as was Interior Minister Istvan Horvath.
   One source said Premier and Communist leader Karoly Grosz was
also seen at the Nep Stadium, as were Soviet diplomats.
   The tour, which began in London Friday, then took the stars to
Paris, is marking the 40th anniversary of the U.N. Universal
Declaration on Human Rights. It will include 20 cities on five
continents.
   The performers include Britain's Sting, American folk singer
Tracy Chapman and Senegal's Youssou N'dour.
   Gabriel told reporters that negotiations still were under way to
take the tour to Moscow and that the performers hoped it could be
arranged.
   During a break in the concert, Berecz was quoted by MTI as
saying that ``there is no need to be afraid of human rights issues,
but persistent efforts are needed for them to be accomplished and
to prevail to the full extent.''
   Berecz was also reported as saying that there was ``no
obstacle'' to cooperation with Amnesty International since the
organization is assessing countries not according to their social
systems but on the basis of their human rights record.
   Hungary has taken the unprecedented step recently of accusing an
allied country of human rights abuses. Budapest maintains that
neighboring Romania is pursuing discriminatory policies that harm
the culture and tradition of about 1.7 million ethnic Hungarians
who live there.
   Ian Martin, secretary-general of Amnesty International, visited
Budapest last week for brief talks with Horvath and with Gyula
Horn, the state secretary for foreign affairs.
   Thousands of Austrians went by special train to Budapest for
Tuesday's event with a special package deal costing $45. Fans from
Czechoslovakia, East Germany and Poland were also in town for the
performance.
   Hungarians paid a maximum $6 for tickets.
   Audiences at each stop on the tour receive a personal ``passport
to human rights,'' a pocket-size replica of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
