<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yeats-Grave     09-07 0544</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yeats-Grave,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bones In Grave Aren't Those Of Yeats, Scholar Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grave of William Butler Yeats in western
Ireland, where the great Irish poet was buried in a state funeral
in 1948, probably doesn't contain his remains, a researcher says.
   The tomb in Drumcliffe, County Sligo, says Diana Souhami, more
likely contains the remains of anonymous Frenchmen with whom Yeats
shared a pauper's grave before being brought to Ireland for
reburial.
   Ms. Souhami's conclusions, which met with disbelief among some
keepers of Yeats' memory, are based on letters of Yeats' friend,
the painter Hannah Gluck. Ms. Souhami read the letters while
writing a biography of Ms. Gluck.
   Yeats died in France in 1939 after stipulating he wanted to be
buried at Drumcliffe. He had even written his own epitaph, now
inscribed on the gravestone seen by thousands of visitors annually:
   ``Cast a cold eye
   ``On life, on death
   ``Horseman, pass by.''
   Yeats scholar John Kelly was quoted by The Daily Telegraph on
Tuesday as saying Ms. Souhami's findings, if true, represented ``a
very cruel irony.''
   But Canon Pat Wood, president of the Yeats Society in Sligo,
said in a telephone interview: ``It's an old, old story and I don't
believe it.''
   He said Anne Saddlemyer, author of a biography of Yeats' wife
Georgie, examined the controversy and concluded the remains at
Drumcliffe were the poet's.
   Ms. Saddlemyer lives in Toronto and her telephone was not
answered Tuesday. Yeats' son Michael, who lives in Dublin, also did
not answer telephone calls.
   Ms. Souhami said in an interview that from letters she found
among Ms. Gluck's papers, it appeared that Georgie had Yeats buried
in a cemetery in Roquebrune, southern France, believing the grave
would be left intact for 10 years.
   In fact, perhaps unwittingly, she had bought a pauper's grave in
which Yeats was buried with four or five others. This grave was
cleared in 1946 and the bones placed in a common ossuary, a
receptacle for bones of deceased people, Ms. Souhami said.
   ``Why she chose the communal grave isn't clear,'' she said.
``Perhaps she thought she had a 10-year concession. What is certain
is that she didn't, and it's certain that it was all cleared out in
1946.''
   In 1947 Ms. Gluck and the journalist Edith Heald visited the
site and were shocked to find no trace of Yeats' grave, she said.
Ms. Gluck then contacted Yeats' friend Edmund Dulac, who wrote to
the priest at the graveyard asking whether Yeats' remains could be
dug up and identified.
   Ms. Souhami said she found among Ms. Gluck's papers a letter to
Dulac from the priest, a man identified only as Biancheri, which
said: ``Is it possible to find the bones of the poet Yeats in the
ossuary? Yes! If we empty the entire contents of the ossuary, and
if we have details of distinctive characteristics which will enable
us to reconstruct the skeleton after painstaking research carried
under the direction of a medical expert...''
   Yeats' purported remains were exhumed and shipped to Ireland
just one month later _ much too soon to enable the bones to be
identified under the terms described by Biancheri, said Ms. Souhami.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
