<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Wildfires 4thLd-Writethru a0765 09-07 1097</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wildfires, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0765,1126</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Old Faithful Complex Ordered Closed; Flames Move On Two Towns</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with officials ordering
evacuation of Old Faithful complex and flames moving withing 600
yards of Silver Gate; picks up 5th graf pvs, `Hundreds of ...' SUBS
grafs 22-25 pvs, `If flames ...' with 2 grafs to conform; DELETES
final four grafs to trim</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos CKCX3, XYS2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COOKE CITY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge fire Tuesday prompted an
evacuation order for the Old Faithful tourist complex at
Yellowstone National Park, and a wall of flames moved to within 600
yards of the town of Silver Gate and threatened Cooke City.
   The 500 to 600 visitors and non-essential employees near the
park's most popular attraction would be asked to leave by 9 a.m.
MDT Wednesday for safety reasons and to allow firefighters the
access they need to protect structures, said Yellowstone
spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo.
   ``This is not a panic at all,'' she said. ``This will be a slow,
orderly closure and evacuation as (closures) have been in different
locations throughout the summer.''
   Gusts 30 mph pushed the main body of the 144,000-acre North Fork
blaze to within 1{ miles of the complex Tuesday evening and carried
embers to within three-quarters of a mile of the area, where they
sparked spot fires.
   To the north, flames surged out of the northeast corner of
Yellowstone within 600 yards of the tourist community of Silver
Gate but moving eastward on a collision course with the larger
community of Cooke City, three miles away.
   Officials said the flames passed to the north of Silver Gate
along a hillside without damaging buildings. But the community
remained endangered and the situation appeared to be worsening as
the flames moved east.
   The sheet of flame was barely 600 feet from downtown Silver Gate
as it paralleled the community, spreading one mile to the east
within an hour, officials said.
   Observers said the fire billowed hundreds of feet into the air
through a cloud of spewing embers that were doused by firefighters
as they landed on buildings.
   Earlier, the fire forced hundreds of firefighters to retreat to
new positions in what was called a last-ditch effort to keep the
flames from overrunning the community.
   Fire officials were pessimistic about holding back the
unpredictable 61,300-acre Storm Creek fire, only 1{ miles west of
Silver Gate, the first town in the fire's path.
   ``We're going to make every effort we can to save every
structure and every home in these communities,'' said Mike Warren,
branch commander of the firefighting effort.
   Hundreds of firefighters retreated Tuesday, fearing for their
safety. ``Too hot!'' yelled one. However, more experienced
firefighters remained to extinguish hot spots and wet down trees.
   Tuesday night, flames leaped from tree to tree a few hundred
yards from Silver Gate after a spot fire flared on a nearby
hillside. Firefighters splashed buildings with water in a
last-ditch effort to save the community.
   The spot fire was estimated at 20 acres and growing fast.
   Earlier Tuesday, authorities went door to door to order
evacuations of Cooke City.
   Gov. Ted Schwinden and federal authorities Tuesday imposed a ban
on all outdoor recreation outside Montana's cities and towns to
lessen the fire danger.
   ``We could face a very, very dangerous day or day and a half,''
Schwinden told reporters. ``When you count up the score, Mother
Nature is way ahead.''
   Thirteen major fires have burned roughly 1 million acres in
Yellowstone and the surrounding national forests in Wyoming,
Montana and Idaho. Inside the 2.2 million-acre park, 633,725 acres
are charred.
   Elsewhere, a fire in parched grass and pine in central
Washington exploded overnight from just 160 acres Monday to more
than 25,000 acres Tuesday, sending firefighters fleeing and
overrunning at least one bulldozer that could not move fast enough,
state officials said. It burned toward some of the state's prime
fruit orchards.
   Forests and grassland also burned in California, Oregon and Utah.
   The Boise Interagency Fire Center, the coordinating office for
firefighting in the West, says fires so far this year have charred
3.65 million acres, an area larger than Connecticut, which is 3.2
million acres. But slightly more than 2 million of the acres are in
Alaska. During the last big fire season, 1985, 2.8 million acres
burned, including Alaska.
   The fire center has called this the worst fire season in 30
years, but without giving a specific year or acreage.
   The U.S. Forest Service said Tuesday it has spent $190 million
battling this summer's blazes. Last year, the Forest Service spent
$265 million to fight fires through September.
   The National Weather Service said any relief is still five days
away. Long-range weather maps show a low pressure system dropping
into the Pacific Northwest from the Gulf of Alaska by Sunday, which
could bring rain to Montana and snow in the state's western
mountains.
   But until then, the weather service said, Montana can expect
relatively strong wind.
   Park County commissioners declared an emergency and directed
sheriff's deputies to forcibly remove people from Silver Gate and
Cooke City. Deputies remained behind to protect property from
looting.
   Silver Gate was encircled by firebreaks Monday about a half-mile
away and work continued Tuesday on strenghtening the fire break
around Cooke City.
   About 75 fire trucks were stationed in the two towns, some from
as far away as New York and California. The trucks were manned by
250 firefighters to protect buildings, in addition to 1,200
firefighters battling the fire itself.
   Inside Yellowstone, crews battled to defend the stores, lodges
and cabins around Old Faithful geyser from the North Fork fire,
which was } mile away.
   ``It's a very defensible area,'' Denny Bungarz, North Fork fire
incident commander, said before the evacuation order. ``We feel
very good that if that fire gets around Old Faithful, we'll be able
to skirt (the fire) around it with little or no loss.''
   Soldiers from Fort Lewis, Wash., worked Tuesday to place a
4,000-foot irrigation line on the western edge of the complex to
protect it from flames expected Wednesday. The soldiers also
chopped down small trees and brush.
   The northwest flank of the North Fork fire was about three miles
northeast of West Yellowstone, Mont., after jumping the Madison
River over the weekend, but Tuesday's change in wind direction
pushed the flames away from town.
   A lobe of the North Fork fire also burned back into the Targhee
National Forest in Idaho, where it originally started before
entering Yellowstone, said Troy Corn, fire information officer.
</TEXT>
