<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st item to ADD 2 grafs to UPDATE with report of Tyson
suicide attempt; a version moved on sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Tyson won't fight Frank Bruno in London as
scheduled Oct. 22, his manager said after doctors announced the
heavyweight champion suffered a concussion and amnesia when his car
hit a tree Sunday.
   ``The fight is off,'' manager Bill Cayton said. ``I don't know
when he will be able to fight again. It will have to be against
Bruno because of the contract.''
   ``When Tyson was told the fight was off, he took it pretty
well,'' Columbia-Presbyterian neurologist Carolyn Britton said
Tuesday. ``He is in good spirits. He did sustain a concussion, but
he will be able to go home in the next day or two. He is doing
quite well.''
   It will be 30 to 60 days before the 22-year-old Tyson can resume
training, said the doctor, who strongly recommended against the
fight.
   Britton said that when Tyson arrived at the hospital Sunday
night, about nine hours after the accident near the upstate town of
Catskill, the champion couldn't remember getting into the car.
   Later, doctors said, he recalled getting into it and starting
the engine, but not the single-car accident, which occurred near
his training camp.
   Meanwhile, the Daily News today quoted Tyson through
unidentified sources as having made comments regarding suicide to
his wife prior to the accident.
   The Daily News, again through unidentified sources, also said
Tyson had threatened his wife on several occasions and is under the
care of a psychiatrist.
