<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     09-07 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Says Campaign Turned Nasty Early</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Lloyd
Bentsen returns to the Senate today after a Labor Day recess spent
in campaigning that he says surprised him with its ferocity.
   ``I think this is early on, to be as aggressive as it is,'' said
Bentsen, who had to battle some jeers as he wrapped up a campaign
trip at the Virginia Polytechnic Institute in Blacksburg, Va. on
Tuesday.
   Mike Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, and Vice
President George Bush, the GOP candidate, also faced hostile
elements in their appearances on Tuesday.
   Bentsen was interrupted as he spoke at an outdoor rally at
Virginia Tech by students carrying Bush posters. Instead of
ignoring them, Bentsen spoke to them directly.
   ``I met George Bush once before,'' he told them, alluding to the
1970 Texas Senate race in which he defeated the then-congressman
Bush. ``And Quayle season is opening early this year,'' he said.
   Afterward, Bentsen visited with reporters on his campaign jet
and said he enjoyed the challenge. ``It gets my adrenaline up,'' he
said.
   Bentsen told reporters he felt the Republicans were running on
``phony issues'' such as Dukakis' veto of a bill requiring the
pledge of allegiance in schools, a decision the Massachusetts
governor made based on a Supreme Court opinion.
   The Texas senator has been responding by sharpening his own
attacks. On Tuesday at Virginia Tech, he said the Republicans have
tried to ``trash educational opportunity across the country.''
   ``We can't make quality education available only to the
privileged few,'' he said, as part of the Democrats' charge that
the Republicans are unfair to working people.
   Bentsen planned to spend today in the Senate, including a
procedural vote on a politically-sensitive textile trade bill. He
was scheduled to leave the Capitol again this evening for a
$1,000-per-person reception in Connecticut to raise money for his
Senate campaign.
   Under an unusual Texas law, Bentsen is running for both the vice
presidency and re-election to his Senate seat, since he cannot drop
out of the latter without handing the spot to the GOP for six
years. If he were to win both races, he could then resign from the
Senate and a special election would be held.
   Bentsen's late-summer campaigning has been concentrated in
Texas, the South, and border states. But he planned to begin a more
wide-ranging schedule Thursday. After campaigning in New York on
Thursday, he was heading for Iowa and then California.
</TEXT>
