<DOCNO> AP880907-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     09-07 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Tells Solidarity Activists To Join Official Unions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers who boycotted official unions
after Solidarity was outlawed should now join those unions instead
of agitating for their own, says government spokesman Jerzy Urban.
   Lech Walesa called the comment irresponsible and said such
government utterances could jeopardize ``roundtable'' talks at
which communist authorities have promised to discuss reinstating
the Solidarity independent labor federation, which he chairs.
   Urban, in his first news conference since a 19-day strike wave
ended Saturday, also said Tuesday that the talks between government
officials and worker representatives would be held sometime this
month.
   He said government officials want the meetings to begin as soon
as possible, but that they would be canceled automatically if any
more ``political'' strikes occur.
   The last of the strikes ended after Walesa won government
assurances that the legalization of Solidarity would be discussed
in the round-table talks.
   Urban said the round table with Walesa and other worker
delegates will include several dozen people and cover speeding
economic recovery, reaching a national consensus, improving living
standards and democratizing Poland.
   Asked about the strikers' demand for reinstatement of
Solidarity, Urban said allowing two trade unions in one plant was
unacceptable.
   ``If followers of some tendency connected in the past with
Solidarity are a majority in a given plant, then they can either
join the (official) trade union, outnumbering it and directing it
where they wish, or form a coalition, a compromise body'' with the
official union, he said.
   ``The existing legal rules offer a broad scope of
possibilities,'' he said, and Solidarity activists made a
``historical mistake'' in boycotting the new government unions
created in 1982 after Solidarity was outlawed.
   Urban said a pro-Solidarity union could be formed in a plant
where no union existed, but it would not be permitted to use the
name Solidarity ``in the present legal situation.''
   Reached at home in Gdansk after Urban's news conference, Walesa
said: ``Let them talk. But they should remember that they could
destroy the round table by such irresponsible statements. This is
all I can say.''
   Solidarity activists say they want their own unions not
membership in the unions established by the government under the
1981 martial-law crackdown.
   The official union federation, called OPZZ, said it would oppose
allowing new unions into plants where it is established.
   An OPZZ resolution also said Premier Zbigniew Messner's
government should resign. Its leaders have said government
officials should be held personally accountable for economic
problems that led to last month's strikes, which affected 20
enterprises employing 100,000 people.
   Numerous signs in the official press and in speeches at a party
conference last month have pointed to changes in the government at
the next parliament session, which is expected this month. Such a
shake-up would not affect the Communist Party leadership, which
holds the real power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
