<DOCNO> AP880907-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0346EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Guerrillas     09-07 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Guerrillas,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrilla Endorses Election Participation, But Promises Military
Action</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A guerrilla leader has endorsed
plans by the rebels' political allies to participate in national
elections in March, but still vows military action to ``complicate
the election.''
   Leonel Gonzalez, one of five commanders of the leftist Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, said Tuesday that the rebels
approve of the plans by the Democratic Revolutionary Front to take
part in the elections.
   ``That they have decided to participate is an autonomous
decision that in no way damages the (military-political) alliance
but rather strengthens it in light of the current situation,'' he
said on the rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos.
   The Democratic Revolutionary Front, an umbrella organization of
leftist political organizations linked to the guerrilla army,
announced last month that they would take part in the elections.
   The rebels and the leftists have boycotted elections here for
the past decade, contending the balloting was part of a
U.S.-designed counterinsurgency effort and that democracy did not
exist in El Salvador.
   The rebels have been battling the U.S.-backed government since
1979. An estimated 65,000 people have died during the civil war.
   The election likely will be a close contest between El
Salvador's two dominant parties, the incumbent Christian Democrats
and the conservative Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   The rightist alliance, known as Arena, gained control of the
legislature and two-thirds of the country's municipal governments
in elections held in March.
   Incumbent President Jose Napoleon Duarte, barred by the
constitution from another term as president, has been diagnosed as
having terminal liver cancer. Gonzalez said on Radio Venceremos
that the left's participation is intended ``to prepare all forces
for the politically negotiated solution (to the war). It is a
correct decision.''
   But he said ``We must make the entire electoral process a
political and military battleground.
   ``Our military action will deepen the political crisis and
complicate the electoral scheme,'' he said.
   The guerrillas demand a share of power in what they say would be
a transition government ``of broad popular participation.'' The
government has repeatedly rejected the demand, insisting the rebels
lay down their arms and compete for power through elections.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0353EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WellsFargoTrial     09-07 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wells Fargo Trial,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Plead Guilty In Wells Fargo Robbery Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense lawyers appeared grim, but
insisted the trials of remaining defendants in the $7 million Wells
Fargo robbery would not be harmed by the guilty pleas of two others.
   Luz Berrios Berrios and Paul S. Weinberg accepted plea bargains
in federal court Tuesday and pleaded to reduced charges stemming
from the 1983 heist, the second-largest in U.S. history.
   Ms. Berrios pleaded guilty to conspiring to use some of the
stolen cash to pay for a toy giveaway in Hartford in 1985. Weinberg
pleaded guilty to a reduced charge of transporting some of the
stolen money in 1984.
   ``It's not going to hurt us,'' said attorney Leonard Weinglass,
who represents Juan Segarra Palmer, a Harvard-educated lawyer
accused of being the ringleader of a Puerto Rican terrorist group
that claimed responsibility for the robbery. Prosecutors declined
comment while the cases of other defendants are pending.
   The pleas were made as jury selection began in the trial of
Weinberg; Ms. Berrios; her husband, Segarra Palmer; and four
others. Questioning of 165 prospective jurors was expected to begin
Thursday.
   Authorities say the group, Los Macheteros, planned to use the
money to finance terrorist acts aimed at ending the U.S.
government's control of Puerto Rico.
   Ms. Berrios told U.S. District Judge T. Emmet Clarie that she
conspired with others in Puerto Rico to send between $5,000 and
$12,000 to Hartford to pay for toys given away on Jan. 6, 1985,
Three Kings Day, the day when people in many Latin American
countries exchange gifts.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Albert S. Dabrowski said that
racketeering and other felony charges against Ms. Berrios would be
dropped at sentencing. She faces a maximum penalty of five years in
prison and a $10,000 fine. No sentencing date was set.
   Ms. Berrios will not testify at the trial of any other Wells
Fargo defendants, said her attorney, Jacob Wieselman.
   Weinberg, a Springfield, Mass., attorney, pleaded guilty to a
misdemeanor charge of aiding and abetting in the transport and
receipt of less than $100 in stolen money from the heist at a Wells
Fargo depot in West Hartford on Sept. 12, 1983. He had been charged
with four felonies.
   Weinberg admitted to transporting some of the stolen cash from
Pennsylvania through Connecticut to Springfield. But his attorney,
F. Mac Buckley, said Weinberg had been ``duped'' into his role by
Segarra Palmer, to whom he loaned his truck and trailer.
   Weinberg faces a maximum penalty of one year in prison and a
$1,000 fine. He will testify for the government in other cases.
   Nine other defendants are awaiting trial at a later date after
the government appeals a ruling by Clarie throwing out some
tape-recorded evidence obtained through wiretaps.
   Three defendants are at large, including Victor Gerena, the
Wells Fargo security guard who authorities say was recruited by Los
Macheteros to carry out the robbery. He allegedly fled to Cuba with
$4 million.
   The government contends that all of the defendants except
Weinberg are salaried members of Los Macheteros.
   Authorities believe some of the money is buried in Puerto Rico.
The only money recovered was the torn halves of a $10 bill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
