<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-07 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Sharply, Share Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply against the Japanese yen,
while share prices moderately rebounded on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
today.
   The foreign exchange market began trading the dollar at 134.55
yen, with a 1.05-yen drop from Tuesday's close of 135.60 yen. The
currency ranged within 134.30 yen and 134.72 yen in a spot trading
estimated at $8 billion, closing at 134.30 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
21.07 points Tuesday, recouped 183.50 points, or 0.67 percent from
the previous day's close of 27,320.51. After the index earned 87.30
points to open at 27,407.81, share prices went higher to finish the
day's session at 27,504.01 in moderate trading with estimated 750
million shares.
   ``The stock market now has less factors to make investors
cautious, and their participation finally began to be active
again,'' said an analyst with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   ``Although the volume is not that much yet, it has been at least
inceasing,'' he said, adding that the market was regaining its
strength.
   Among the issues attracting investors were steels, shipbuilding
and resort-related stocks.
   The dollar's decline was widely attributed to the Bank of
Japan's short term economy forecast Tuesday that reported the
Japanese economy has been and will be growing without inflation.
   ``Although some securities companies once sold the yen to buy
the dollar for their profit-taking purposes, the dollar-buying
drive in the market was not strong any more,'' said Hiroyuki
Sekine, exchange dealer with the Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
