<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0451EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     09-07 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0395</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Cardenas Petition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Cuauhtemoc Cardenas
suffered another setback in his quest for the presidency when the
Supreme Court refused to investigate alleged electoral fraud.
   In a unanimous opinion, the court said Tuesday it could
intervene in a congressional certification of the election results
only if irregularities jeopardized the entire vote count.
   Cardenas, the candidate of the leftist National Democratic
Front, claims the July 6 election was rigged to favor Carlos
Salinas de Gortari of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI.
   Official results gave Salinas 50.36 percent of the vote,
Cardenas 31.12 percent and Clouthier 17.07 percent. The PRI has won
every presidential race since it was formed in 1929, but never by
such a narrow margin.
   On Friday, the Chamber of Deputies begins what are expected to
be tense sessions to confirm Salinas' victory.
   In a letter to Cardenas, Supreme Court president Carlos del Rio
Rodriguez said the court was empowered to investigate only those
fraud cases that ``could place in doubt the legality of the entire
election process.''
   His ruling was carried by the Excelsior news service.
   The decision followed a vigorous defense of Salinas' victory by
the PRI's two highest officials.
   ``This has been the most watched-over election in Mexico's
history,'' said PRI secretary-general Manuel Camacho Solis. He
rejected the Front's arguments that another vote count would show
Cardenas won.
   Camacho Solis said that ``even applying the political criteria
of the (Front), there exists no basis for saying that Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas won the election. Cuauhtemoc Cardenas loses in the urban
areas; he loses in the rural areas.''
   PRI president Jorge de la Vega Dominguez accused Cardenas and
National Action Party candidate Manuel Clouthier of pressing their
fraud protests to upset the presidential transition.
   Salinas is scheduled to be inaugurated Dec. 1.
   ``The opposition parties, in an immoral and perverse attitude,
have been speaking since long before the elections of electoral
fraud,'' de la Vega Dominguez said Monday. ``They never proved it
because it never occurred.''
   ``Their objective is simplistic and puerile: the conquest of
public power through provocation. Confusion, disorder and
destabilization,'' de la Vega Dominguez said.
   His statements were among the strongest by the PRI on the
opposition since the election.
</TEXT>
