<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SniperShootings     09-07 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sniper Shootings,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sniper, Two Children Killed After Standoff With Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An immigrant apparently distraught over money
and family problems killed his two children and wounded 14 police
officers before he was shot dead during a day-long standoff,
authorities said.
   A gunbattle between police and Cho Mun Chu, 45, closed
Manhattan's FDR Drive during Tuesday morning's rush hour, tying up
thousands of motorists as negotiators tried to coax Chu into laying
down his birdshot-loaded 12-gauge shotgun.
   Helen Chu, 8, and her 9-year-old brother, Warren Chu, were
apparently both shot in the head by Chu during the nine-hour siege,
police said. The standoff ended when police shot Chu twice in the
chest; he died later that night at Bellevue Hospital.
   The 14 officers were treated at hospitals for minor injuries
involving wounds from shotgun pellets and released.
   Chu, who came to the United States from Taiwan 13 years ago, was
described by neighbors as extremely bad-tempered. He had
``financial problems and family problems'' that set him off, said
First Deputy Police Commissioner Richard Condon.
   ``He was constantly hitting on his wife, his kids,'' said Pedro
Morales, 26, whose girlfriend, Vicky Bello, lives in the apartment
above the Chus and has filed several complaints against the family.
   ``The guy was a psycho, he used to bang on the walls and the
ceiling,'' Morales said.
   ``He chased my ex-husband with a samurai sword when he
complained to him a few years ago,'' Ms. Bello said.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said authorities believe the
boy may have been killed before police arrived; Helen was last seen
alive at noon by a police camera that had been lowered to a living
room window to monitor Chu's movements.
   The girl's death was believed to be the first time since the
elite Hostage Negotiating Team began in 1973 that a hostage was
killed during negotiations, said Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell, a police
spokesman.
   The shootings began at 6 a.m., when Chu wounded three officers
called to investigate complaints of shots being fired on the Lower
East Side, police said.
   Hundreds of officers were brought into the area, and police
removed the door to Chu's 11th-floor apartment from its hinges in
an attempt to bring the girl to safety, Ward said.
   Negotiations were in its fifth hour when the gunman suddenly
fired two shotgun blasts at police, including several hostage
negotiators who were talking with him from behind a barricade
outside the doorway. Neither of the children was then visible, Ward
said.
   ``We waited until he fired point-blank _ one captain was hit,
four lieutenants were hit, and one police officer was hit by
pellets, and he was now firing point blank at the door,'' the
commissioner said.
   The officers returned two shots, hitting Chu twice in the chest,
Ward said.
   Chu had made no threats against his family and in the course of
negotiations had made no demands, said First Deputy Police
Commissioner Richard Condon.
   He was believed to be unemployed, police said. His $280-a-month
apartment is rent-subsidized by the city, according to Devorah L.
Fong, a spokeswoman for Grenadier Realty Corp., which manages the
building.
   Chu's wife, Hui Choy Chu, 37, was thought to be visiting Taiwan,
O'Donnell said.
</TEXT>
