<1ST_LINE>r p PM-FloridaPrimary     09-07 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Florida Primary,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mack Wins GOP Senate Nomination; Two Democratic Veterans In Runoff</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservative Rep. Connie Mack III handily won the
GOP nomination in the race to succeed retiring Sen. Lawton Chiles,
and he awaits the outcome of a runoff between two longstanding
Democratic rivals.
   State Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter, in a Senate runoff for
the third time, goes one-on-one in the Oct. 4 runoff with Rep.
Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay, who ran second to Gunter in Tuesday's
bitterly fought six-way Democratic primary.
   Chiles, 58, is retiring after three terms.
   Voters in Nevada, meanwhile, nominated Republican Sen. Chic
Hecht and Democratic Gov. Dick Bryan to face eachother in November
for Hecht's U.S. Senate. And Vietnam war hero James ``Bo'' Gritz,
who has made forays into Southeast Asia looking for POWs, lost his
bid in a congressional race.
   Mack, grandson of the baseball Hall of Fame manager, said he
could beat either of his rivals. ``Whoever it is, it will be
someone who wants more taxes, more spending, more government, and
less freedom,'' he said.
   Mack, 47, who got campaign help from President Reagan and
indicted former National Security Council aide Oliver North, said
his campaign will prove that ``the conservative movement isn't
over.''
   With 99 percent of the vote reporting unofficial returns, Mack
had 392,342 votes, or 62 percent, to 243,039 votes, or 38 percent,
for his only challenger, aggressive former federal prosecutor
Robert Merkle.
   Merkle, 44, said his campaign, shunned by the GOP hierarchy, had
``sent shock waves through this state. ... We have proved without a
doubt that the U.S. Senate slot is not for sale in this state.''
   Mack planned a four-city swing beginning in Key West today and
will soon air new television commercials in an effort to build
support while Gunter and MacKay are sniping at each other.
   Gunter, 54, said he won the election even though MacKay, 55,
``ran against my record. ... The people of Florida don't like that
type of campaigning.''
   With 99 percent of precincts reporting, Gunter had 360,831 votes
or 37 percent, followed by MacKay with 251,968 votes or 26 percent.
U.S. Rep. Dan Mica, 44, was third with 178,138 votes or 18 percent.
State Sen. Patricia ``Pat'' Frank had 115,187 votes, or 12 percent.
   Former Republican Gov. Claude R. Kirk, 62, was fifth with 48,797
votes or 5 percent, and former Senate postal clerk Fred Rader, 41,
had 11,222 votes for 1 percent.
   MacKay had accused Gunter of conflict of interest for accepting
contributions from the industry he regulates. MacKay's campaign
manager, Greg Farmer, called Gunter's 12 years as insurance
commissioner ``a saga of sleaze.''
   Gunter retorted that MacKay was hypocritical for accepting funds
from political action committees that Gunter said wanted to
influence his votes.
   Ms. Frank, praised for running a clean campaign but badly
outspent by the Democratic leaders, said the Senate race was an
``M&M campaign _ money and mudslinging.''
   MacKay ran third in a bitter 1980 primary in which Gunter ran
second, then defeated incumbent Richard Stone in a runoff. Gunter
lost to Republican Paula Hawkins, but Democrat Bob Graham won that
seat back by defeating Mrs. Hawkins in 1986.
   Elsewhere in Florida, 10-term Democratic Rep. William Chappell
of Ormond Beach captured 70 percent of the vote against primary
challenger Charley Roberts, a retired Army veteran. Chappell's name
has been mentioned in published reports about the defense
procurement probe, but he denied wrongdoing.
   ``Any time we can get this type of response on this kind of
(rainy) day, we know we are doing a good job,'' said Chappell, 66,
who described his Democratic opponent and three Republican
challengers as ``four vultures waiting to see the demise of ol'
Bill Chappell.''
</TEXT>
