<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0536EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Bombs     09-07 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Bombs,0266</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Bombs Explode in Four Cities in Northwestern Galicia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO DE COMPOSTELA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven bombs exploded today
outside offices in this northwestern regional capital and in three
other cities, causing extensive damage but no injuries, police said.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, but police said
they suspected the radical nationalist group, the Guerrilla Army of
the Free Galician People.
   The small group seeks independence from Spain for the
four-province northwestern region of Galicia and claimed
responsibilty for a series of bombings in the area in April, police
said.
   The first three explosions occurred just after 3:30 a.m. in
downtown Santiago de Compostela, the capital of the region of
Galicia.
   The blasts ripped through offices of Barclay's Bank, the utility
company Union Electrica Fenosa and Banco de Galicia, police said.
   The blasts shattered windows of buildings adjacent to the
offices and wrecked at least seven cars, police said.
   At nearly the same time in La Coruna, the capital of La Coruna
province, a bomb exploded in the doorway of a centrally located
office of the Banco de Bilbao, heavily damaging the office and
seven cars parked nearby, according to police.
   An hour later in Vigo, a port city on Galicia's eastern coast,
bombs exploded outside offices of Banco Atlantico and the Banco
Pastor, partially destroying the offices but causing no injuries,
police said.
   The seventh bomb exploded in the northern Galician port city of
El Ferrol outside an office of Banco de Bilbao, destroying the
office and heavily damaging several cars parked nearby, police said.
</TEXT>
