<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Shamir     09-07 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Shamir,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Kicks Off Campaign, Vows to Block Palestinian State</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir vowed to foil
Palestinian dreams of an independent state but called for a
dialogue with leaders in the occupied territories as he launched
his campaign against the rival Labor Party.
   Shamir, leader of the right-wing Likud bloc, said Tuesday that a
victory for his party in the Nov. 1 national elections ``would put
an end to the delusions regarding an independent Palestinian state
or a provisional (Palestinian) government.''
   He said a Likud victory also would send a message to ``all Arab
rioters ... and the terrorist organizations controlling them, that
they do not stand a chance of fulfilling their goals and plots.''
   Palestinians have been rioting in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip since Dec. 8. More than 250 Palestinians have been
killed. Four Israelis have died.
   Israel captured the Gaza Strip from Egypt and the West Bank from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization, under pressure to fill
the vacuum left by Jordan's King Hussein when he dropped claims to
the West Bank in July, has said it may declare a Palestinian state
in the occupied lands or a government in exile.
   About 3,000 right-wing supporters, some waving Israeli flags,
cheered as Shamir criticized the left-of-center Labor Party, which
advocates trading land for peace with Palestinians.
   In a bid for crucial support from religious voters, the
non-observant Shamir donned a skullcap at the end of his speech and
read a special prayer recited before the Jewish New Year, which
begins next week. Skullcaps are worn by observant Jews.
   If elected, Shamir said, he would immediately ``invite the
leaders of Egypt and Jordan and Palestinians in Judea and Samaria
(the biblical names for the occupied West Bank) and Gaza to
negotiate directly for peace on the basis of the Camp David
agreements,'' which call for limited Palestinian autonomy.
   ``Each side will be able to raise any issue as long as we don't
stop talking until all possibilities for peace have been
exhausted,'' he said.
   He said the Palestinian uprising had not changed his mind about
the need to negotiate autonomy.
   ``We know many (Palestinians) are taking part in the acts of
hostility and hatred against Israel,'' Shamir said. ``But we also
know many understand that the path of violence will only heap
tragedy and suffering upon them.''
   Shamir said Likud would step up the construction of Jewish
settlements in the occupied territories ``until there is absolutely
no doubt in anyone's mind that we have returned to our ancestral
homeland.''
   Jewish settlement slowed under the current Labor-Likud coalition
government because Labor opposes Jewish settlements in densely
populated Arab areas of the occupied territories.
   Shamir said his government would strengthen ties between Israel
and the United States, and he scorned Labor for saying that his
hard-line policies would create a rift with Washington.
   ``Our relations have never been better or closer than during the
Likud era,'' said Shamir.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
