<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaPrimary     09-07 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada Primary,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Against Incumbent in Nevada U.S. Senate Race</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Dick Bryan crushed three
Democratic rivals for the right to challenge Sen. Chic Hecht in
November as the Republican senator easily won his party's primary.
   Vietnam war hero James ``Bo'' Gritz, who has made forays into
Southeast Asia in search of POWs, lost his bid for a seat in the
U.S. House of Representatives to Republican Party activist Lucille
Lusk.
   With all precincts reporting in Tuesday's Democratic primary,
Bryan, 51, garnered 61,987 votes or 80 percent. ``None,'' an option
listed on the ballot, came in second with 6,991 votes or 9 percent.
   Trailing the 51-year-old governor and ``None'' were Patrick
Fitzpatrick with 4,691 votes or 6 percent, Manford ``Cave Rock
Manny'' Beals with 2,651 votes or 3 percent, and Larry Kepler with
1,650 votes or 2 percent.
   Hecht, 59, defeated Larry Scheffler, owner of a graphics
business in Henderson who said he would press for reprocessing
nuclear waste brought to Nevada so that only low-level, less
radioactive waste would remain.
   Hecht had 55,352 votes or 82 percent, Scheffler had 5,617 votes
or 8 percent, and 6,454 voters or 10 percent favored ``None.''
   ``Now the primary is over and we're gearing up for this race,''
said Hecht, who is seeking a second term. ``You're going to see the
most exciting race Nevada has ever had.''
   Bryan, who is serving his second term, said he looked forward
``to the challenge that lies ahead ... We feel that we've generated
some momentum but as we've said from the very beginning this is
going to be a very tough race.''
   In the GOP House primary, Lusk received 12,075 votes or 48
percent to 10,715 votes or 42 percent for Gritz and 2,562 votes or
10 percent for retiree John Kraft. The Democratic incumbent, Jim
Bilbray, had no opposition.
   ``We needed a larger voter turnout,'' said Gritz.
   Gritz said of his main opponent, ``Lucille would be much better
in the home than in the House _ of Representatives, that is.''
   Ms. Lusk said she was ``ready to take on Mr. Bilbray. As for
Gritz, she said, ``I think what I believe is more believable than
what he believes.''
   In the Senate race, Hecht has become known for verbal miscues,
once referring to a ``nuclear suppository'' when he meant
``repository'' and on another occasion saying he had debated
``diametric materialism'' with a Soviet official, when he meant
``dialectic.''
   A recent survey of Senate administrative assistants ranked him
as the least effective senator in Washington.
   Hecht has attacked Bryan as being too pro-labor and said: ``I
brought out what this campaign is about. The out-of-state labor
bosses want to control the Senate.''
   Bryan responded that Hecht has resorted to inaccuracies and
cliches instead of specifics. He also said only about 10 percent of
his contributions come from labor and Hecht was incorrect to say 42
percent of all contributions came from labor groups.
   Bryan said he has received about $189,000 from labor out of $1.8
million in contributions and ``I don't care if you're using the old
math or new math ... that works out to 10.4 percent.''
</TEXT>
