<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HurricaneUleki     09-07 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane Uleki,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Uleki Threatens Midway Island, Kure Atoll</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy personnel and civilian workers on tiny
Midway Island 1,300 miles northwest of here have made preparations
to ride out Hurricane Uleki, the commanding officer said.
   ``We've secured all the equipment and made the preparations we
need to make, and we're ready it ride it out,'' said Lt. Cmdr.
Gibson McMillan, officer in charge of the Navy base on the
two-square-mile island where the highest elevation is about 30 feet.
   ``We anticipate the possibility of hurricane force winds in 24
to 36 hours,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   Midway is home for about 300 sailors and contracted civilian
employees who share the island with thousands of gooney birds. Navy
dependents no longer live on the island.
   Hurricane Uleki's strong winds could hit the northern-most
islands in the Hawaiian Chain today. The islands include Midway and
Kure Atoll, where the 22 Coast Guard personnel maintain a
navigation station.
   At 8 p.m. Tuesday, the hurricane was 1,000 miles west of
Honolulu, moving west-northwest at 14 mph with winds at 75 mph and
gusts 90 mph, the National Weather Service said.
   The storm was forecast to maintain hurricane strength during the
next 12 to 24 hours and to gradually turn north within 18 to 24
hours.
   The weather service said some of the stronger fringe winds on
the north side of Uleki might reach Lisianski Island early today
and Midway and Kure Atoll later in the day.
   Uleki, at one time packing winds gusting to 150 mph, approached
to about 300 miles of the major Hawaiian Islands of Oahu, Kauai and
Niihau during the Labor Day weekend, before veering away to the
west and then moving northwest, parallel to the 1,500-mile-long
chain.
</TEXT>
