<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmericanLegion-Fonda     09-07 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Legion-Fonda,0227</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legionnaires Rebuff Fonda Apology</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Legion says it's too soon to
forgive or forget Jane Fonda's visit to Hanoi during the Vietnam
War despite her recent apology to veterans on national television.
   Legionnaires ``do not believe her apology was in any way sincere
and was only stated on the TV program as a ruse to further enhance
her many commercial undertakings,'' said a resolution adopted
Tuesday at the veterans group's 70th annual convention.
   Many ``of America's fighting men and women lost their lives,
were wounded, tortured and suffered in many other ways because of
Jane Fonda's dealing with the enemy,'' the resolution.
   Ms. Fonda, who has made a career both as a film actress and
physical fitness enthusiast, offered the apology for her excesses
as a 1960s anti-war activist on ABC-TV's ``20-20'' news program
this summer.
   During the Vietnam War, she made a much-publicized trip to North
Vietnam, where she called on U.S. servicemen to quit fighting.
   The Legion's resolution, presented by the organization's
Americanism Commission, was approved on the convention floor on a
voice vote without discussion, but with apparent enthusiasm.
   Last month, the Veterans of Foreign Wars also rejected Ms.
Fonda's apology at the group's convention in Chicago, and adopted a
resolution calling on Congress to try her for treason.
</TEXT>
