<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     09-07 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Dips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in thin early European
trading today. Gold prices fell.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell sharply to close at 134.30 yen, down 1.30 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.90 yen.
   The dollar's decline in Tokyo was widely attributed to the Bank
of Japan's short-term economic forecast that reported the Japanese
economy has been and will be growing without inflation.
   Foreign currency dealers said trading in Frankfurt, West
Germany, was also dominated by dollar-yen movements. After the
dollar rose to peaks of 1.8480 marks and 134.70 yen in the Far
East, Japanese investors began unloading it and pushed the U.S.
currency back, dealers said.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8418 West German marks, down from 1.8425
   _1.5540 Swiss francs, up from 1.5525
   _6.2725 French francs, up from 6.2715
   _2.0796 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820
   _1,375.50 Italian lire, down from 1,377.65
   _1.2370 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2340
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound.
One pound cost $1.7050, compared with $1.7035 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $428.00 a troy ounce,
down from $428.10 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $427.
   Bullion dealers said the precious metal was trapped in tight
ranges, amid a lack of investor interest and the offsetting
influences of a weaker dollar and weaker oil prices.
   The bid price for gold in Zurich was also $427, down from $428
bid late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.04 to close at a bid $430.19.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.49 a troy
ounce, down from Tuesday's $6.56.
</TEXT>
