<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-07 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stationary Front Continues to Drench Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A stationary front continued to hit Florida with strong winds
and heavy rain today, causing widespread flooding of lowland areas
and minor beach erosion along the state's central Gulf Coast.
   Cool air, meanwhile, spread over part of the nation's
midsection, breaking temperature records as far south as Arkansas.
   The stationary front has been drenching Florida since Sunday,
with some west-central areas getting 5 to 10 inches and Yankeetown
on the Gulf Coast receiving more than 13 inches.
   ``All the rivers around here are over their banks,'' said Coast
Guard Petty Officer Eric Hermann in the Yankeetown station.
``There's a lot of street flooding and stuff. We're just waiting
for high tide tonight.''
   The rains flooded roads in the Tampa-St. Petersburg area and
curbed voter turnout in the state's primary elections. A flood
warning was issued for the St. Mary's River in northeast Florida,
which is expected to crest Thursday.
   Record cold settled on parts of the Mississippi and Ohio
valleys. Jonesboro, Ark., had an early morning reading of 51
degrees, breaking by one degree its record low for this date, while
Evansville, Ind., also broke its old record low by one degree with
a reading of 46.
   Smoke from forest fires spread across western and central
Montana, and ash from fires was falling at Great Falls, Mont.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms along the
South Carolina and Georgia coasts and across the Florida Peninsula,
cloudy skies over northwest Washington state and generally sunny
skies elsewhere. Strong, gusty winds were forecast for the northern
Rockies, the upper Missouri Valley, the Dakotas and the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   Highs were expected to be in the upper 50s in northern Maine; in
the 60s in the rest of New England and the Middle Atlantic States;
in the 60s and 70s from northern Montana to Washington and northern
Oregon and along much of the California coast; in the 90s in the
southern and central Plains; and in the 90s to about 105 degrees in
the desert Southwest, eastern California, western Nevada and
southwest Oregon. Highs elsewhere were predicted to be in the 80s.
   At 3 a.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 37 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 87 degrees at Las Vegas, N.V., and Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 partly cloudy; Boston 54 fair; Buffalo 52
fair; Charleston, S.C. 66 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 45 fair;
Cleveland 50 cloudy; Detroit 48 fair; Miami 81 cloudy; New York 57
fair; Philadelphia 54 fair; Pittsburgh 46 fair; Portland, Me. 47
fair; Washington 55 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 52 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
73 fair; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 51 fair; Indianapolis 48 fair;
Kansas City 58 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 56 fair; Nashville 51
fair; New Orleans 70 fair; St. Louis 61 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 61 fair; Anchorage 47 cloudy; Las Vegas 82
fair; Los Angeles 68 fair; Phoenix 87 fair; Salt Lake City 73 fair;
San Diego 70 fair; San Francisco 54 fair; Seattle 58 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 48 fair; Toronto 54 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
