<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Terrorism     09-07 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Terrorism,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 21 Suspected Terrorists in Major Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 21 suspected leftist terrorists and
seized guns and grenades in a major sweep in the Rome area before
dawn today, officials announced.
   Some 200 Carabinieri, or paramilitary police, carried out the
early morning operation, staging raids on four apartments in the
city and suburban areas, said Gen. Roberto Jucci, commander of the
Carabinieri.
   Many of the suspects were surprised in their sleep and officials
said they encountered no resistance.
   Jucci said 12 of those arrested are believed to be members of
the Formation of the Fighting Communist Party, the most dangerous
and active group of what remains of the Red Brigades terrorist gang.
   The group has been implicated in several assassinations over the
past two years, including the killing in April of Sen. Roberto
Ruffilli, a close friend and adviser of Premier Ciriaco De Mita.
   ``This is a severe blow (to the Red Brigades). We hope this will
keep them from commiting futher atrocities,'' Jucci told a news
conference.
   The Carabinieri declined to disclose specific charges against
those arrested, saying the suspects were still being questioned.
The 21 arrested include five women.
   Italo Leopizzi, another Carabinieri official, said 16 pistols,
21 detonators and a large number of hand grenades and rifles were
seized in the pre-dawn sweep, along with $140,000 in cash.
</TEXT>
