<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MTVAwards     09-07 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MTV Awards,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>MTV Awards Enter The Big Time Tonight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The MTV Music Video Awards,
started five years ago as a kind of party to celebrate the instant
success of the video clip format, enters the big leagues tonight
with its 1988 show.
   The 2{-hour show at Universal Amphitheater features performances
by a mix of acts whose first blast of success or career revivals
are largely owed to MTV.
   Among those scheduled to perform on the show either live or by
satellite are Aerosmith, Guns 'n' Roses, Elton John, Rod Stewart,
INXS, Crowded House, Depeche Mode, The Fat Boys and Jody Watley.
   Fitting into neither the new star nor the revived career
category is Academy Award winner Cher, who like many of the awards
show performers is also a nominee.
   Superstar Michael Jackson, for instance, is scheduled to perform
via satellite and receive the 1988 Video Vanguard Award for career
contributions to the medium.
   Jackson rose to superstardom with MTV in 1983 with his
``Thriller'' and ``Beat It'' videos. His ``Bad'' and ``The Way You
Make Me Feel'' videos are nominated this year.
   Jackson's award and a Viewer's Choice award, picked by MTV
viewers the night of the awards by dialing a special ``900''
telephone number, join 15 nominated categories.
   Top nominees are videos from the high-energy Australian pop
group INXS with eight, including best video and best group video
for ``Need You Tonight-ediate,'' and former Beatle George Harrison,
whose videos have five nods, including best video and and best male
performance on a video for ``When We Was Fab'' and ``Got My Mind
Set On You,'' respectively.
   The host is comedian Arsenio Hall, co-star of ``Coming to
America.'' The presenters include Justine Bateman, Cyndi Lauper,
Belinda Carlisle, Suzanne Vega, Los Angeles Laker Earvin ``Magic''
Johnson and Sam Kinison, among others.
   The show will be broadcast live on MTV, and has also been sold
into syndication for airing at a later date on non-cable stations.
   The awards categories are divided into general video nominations
and professional sections, the latter dealing with technical
achievements.
