<2ND_LINE>PM-Escapee Caught,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Found Asleep in Stolen Car is Chicago Jail Escapee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRANVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prison escapee who called himself and
his girlfriend a modern-day ``Bonnie and Clyde'' crime team was
found sleeping in a stolen car and arrested by an Ohio State
Highway Patrol trooper.
   Vincent Bruce, 26, escaped Aug. 26 from the Cook County Jail in
Chicago, where he faced armed robbery charges, by using a bar of
soap carved and blackened to resemble a gun, officials said. Bruce
pulled the gun on an unarmed guard who was escorting him to a
hospital for treatment.
   Bruce and his girlfriend, Catherine Reed, 29, called themselves
a modern-day ``Bonnie and Clyde'' after Depression-era gangsters
Bonnie Parker and Clyde Barrow, who killed at least 13 people,
authorities said.
   Ms. Reed was arrested last summer in Cincinnati in the slayings
of three alleged drug dealers in the Los Angeles-area slayings.
Police in Los Angeles said Bruce, who is also sought in the
slayings, was a ``real violent, mean type.'' A third suspect in the
case has been arrested and is awaiting trial.
   Highway Patrol Sgt. Dick Wells said Bruce was found asleep in a
stolen car at a rest area of Interstate 70 near Newark in central
Ohio around 5 a.m. Tuesday. Licking County authorities are working
with police from Chicago and Los Angeles to have Bruce extradited,
Well said.
