<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CondomSuit     09-07 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condom Suit,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Goes To Court To Seize Defective Condoms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government has gone to court
to try to confiscate nearly 50,000 condoms it says are defective.
   The case is believed to mark the first time the federal Food and
Drug Administration has sought to seize a batch of condoms for
destruction.
   The U.S. Attorney's office filed suit in U.S. District Court
here on Tuesday asking the court to order the U.S. Marshal to seize
the condoms from the warehouse of Mentor Corp. of Minneapolis.
   The seizure would include about 44,350 condoms from a batch of
contraceptives made for Mentor by an East Coast factory, said
assistant U.S. Attorney Roylene Champeaux.
   The FDA routinely tests condoms every three months before they
leave manufacturers' warehouses. If more than three condoms of a
batch of 1,000 leak, the batch is declared substandard, said Mentor
spokesman Al Mannino.
   Previously, manufacturers were allowed to destroy the condoms
and file affidavits with the FDA stating they had been destroyed,
he said.
   But the FDA is now taking a much tougher approach to condom
quality control. Government health experts have advised use of
condoms as a preventive measure against the spread of AIDS, or
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   Judge Paul Magnuson is expected to sign the seizure order later
this week, Champeaux said. Mentor will have until Nov. 10 to
contest the seizure, according to the government's complaint. If
Mentor does not file a claim for the return of the condoms, the
government will destroy them, Champeaux said.
   ``That would be fine. That would save us the cost of destroying
them,'' said Mannino, who said he was baffled by the government's
action.
   FDA inspectors declared the Mentor batch defective Aug. 1,
Mannino said.
   Mentor, which has headquarters in Minnesota and Santa Barbara,
Calif., makes a variety of implantable devices and health care
products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
