<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HeatedSchool     09-07 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heated School,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Heated To 120 Degrees; Plants, Lab Animals Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   School maintenance workers hiked the
heat to 120 degrees hoping to get rid of a pesky mold, but the heat
ended up killing plants and lab animals and sending students in
search of cooler classrooms.
   Officials arriving at Lakewood High School Tuesday morning
walked into a stifling heat that had been simmering for three days
in the school's science wing. Floors buckled, students' plants
withered away, tanks of tropical fish perished, as did a turtle, a
snake and at least one favorite lab rat.
   ``There were many students and a teacher who were emotionally
attached to that rat,'' Science Department Chairman Richard
Henderson said Tuesday afternoon, when the wing had cooled down to
a balmy 90 degrees.
   Lakewood Principal Barbara Broughton said she feared computers,
films and other materials also may have been damaged by the heat.
   Workers turned on the heating system in the science wing in an
attempt to dry the area, Ms. Broughton said. The wing has been
experiencing a persistent mold problem in recent years because a
ventilation system has failed to properly dehumidify the building,
she said.
   By raising the temperature, workers hoped to kill the mold
spores and alleviate the problem.
   But Ms. Broughton said she and her teachers were not warned and
animals and plants were not moved.
   ``As soon as (students) walked in here they knew something
wasn't right,'' Henderson said. ``It really was unbearable.''
   School officials scrambled to find cooler rooms for Tuesday's
classes but expected rooms to be cool enough to be used today.
   Maintenance workers won't know for several days whether the heat
treatment solved the mold problem, said Carol Jackson, public
information officer for the Pinellas County schools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
