<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Garza     09-07 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Garza,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Who Survived 45 Minutes Underwater Starts Another School Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOORHEAD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A boy who survived 45 minutes underwater
in a freezing river has begun a new school year, saying he feels
completely recovered from his icy ordeal.
   ``I'm going to be able to do everything on my own now,'' said
Alvaro Garza Jr., 11, who was trailed Tuesday by reporters and
photographers as he attended his first day of sixth grade.
   He spent his summer ``riding (a) bike, playing baseball, playing
football ... doing a bunch of stuff,'' he said.
   His parents, Alvaro Sr. and Mary Helen Garza, said their son had
recovered from the nerve damage he suffered and no longer required
physical therapy.
   Garza fell through thin ice and into the frigid Red River, which
divides Moorhead from Fargo, N.D., last Dec. 4 as he tried to
retrieve a dead squirrel. When rescuers pulled him from the river,
his body temperature was 77 degrees and he showed no signs of life.
   Doctors used a heart-lung bypass machine to warm his body; four
days later, he communicated by blinking his eyes. He spent 17 days
in the hospital.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
