<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolUniforms     09-07 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Uniforms,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elementary School Adopts Dress Code</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school that draws most of
its pupils from public housing projects will soon require students
to wear uniforms, the school's principal said.
   Parents who refuse to have their children wear the required
attire will face having their children transferred to another
school, school officials said.
   However, William Olds, executive director of the Connecticut
Civil Liberties Union, said requiring uniforms in a public school
is ``blatantly unconstitutional.'' Olds said he doesn't believe the
school system could legally transfer a pupil for failing to comply
with the dress code.
   Although the dress code doesn't take effect until Oct. 3, at
least a dozen boys came to school Tuesday wearing what will be
their required attire: gray pants, white shirts, green ties, and
brown or black shoes.
   ``The girls wanted their dresses today, too. But we told them
they'd have to wait,'' said Jeffie Frazier, principal of the Helene
Grant School, which has about 300 students in kindergarten through
fourth grade.
   Girls will have to wear white blouses, white socks and dark
shoes.
   The dress code is part of an effort to build self-esteem and end
clothing competition, Frazier said. The idea has been so
successful, she said, that 51 families have added their names to a
waiting list to enroll their children in the school.
   Parents who have difficulty affording the uniforms can get
financial aid from community organizations, Frazier said.
   Schools Superintendent John Dow Jr. said he enthusiastically
supports the new dress code. If it proves successful, school
officials added, it may be expanded to other schools.
   About 50 public schools around the nation have adoped dress
codes, among them schools in Baltimore, Washington, D.C., and Perth
Amboy, N.J., according to state and national education officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
