<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SanDiegoSlayings     09-07 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-San Diego Slayings,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>San Diego Appoints Task Force For Killing Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement agencies have formed a task
force to investigate the slayings of 30 women since 1985, saying
they were modeling their effort on Washington state's ``Green
River'' task force.
   A task force consisting of detectives and prosecutors has been
working informally since June and was formally appointed Thursday,
San Diego County sheriff's Sgt. Liz Foster said Tuesday.
   Authorities in both San Diego and Seattle have denied published
reports that there is any conclusive link between the San Diego
slayings and the 48 deaths attributed to the Green River killer,
so-called because many of the bodies were found near the
Seattle-area river.
   In both series of killings, the victims were mostly prostitutes
or transients. San Diego investigators believe at least 10 of the
30 unsolved slayings since 1985 are the work of one killer. The
most recent Green River killings occurred in 1984.
   Foster said the task force began working informally after
several meetings between sheriff's officials and members of the
Green River task force.
   San Diego County prosecutors reportedly are obtaining computers
for the task force because their Seattle counterparts recommended
it, The San Diego Union reported.
   The slayings in Washington's King County are the nation's worst
unsolved series of killings. Forty bodies were found around Seattle
and Portland, Ore., and an additional eight women are missing and
feared victims.
</TEXT>
