<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Rabbi     09-07 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Rabbi,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Rabbi To Conduct Services In East Berlin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American rabbi is on his way
to East Berlin to conduct Jewish holiday services in the communist
capital, a Jewish community spokesman said.
   Rabbi Herman Dicker of New York, who arrived in Frankfurt today,
is to officiate at Sunday evening services at a synagogue in East
Berlin. The tiny East German Jewish community has no permanent
rabbi.
   Michel Friedman, a spokesman for the Frankfurt Jewish Community,
said Dicker was expected to arrive in Berlin tonight.
   The World Jewish Congress in New York said it had reached an
agreement with the East German government for Dicker to lead
services in observance of the Jewish religious holidays of Rosh
Hashana and Yom Kippur.
   The World Jewish Congress said there were 600 Jews in East
Germany, while other estimates put the population at fewer than 450
people.
   The Hungarian-born Dicker, a research librarian at the Jewish
Theological Seminary in New York, lived in Berlin until he fled in
1936 after the Nazis came to power. He served with U.S. forces that
liberated Nazi concentration camps at the end of World War II, the
World Jewish Conference said.
   The World Jewish Conference said it and the East Berlin Jewish
community were still looking for a permanent rabbi to serve there.
   In September 1987, American Rabbi Isaac Neuman became the first
rabbi in 21 years to be appointed to East Germany. But the
Polish-born Neuman resigned in May after criticizing the Jewish
community leadership for allegedly interfering in his work.
</TEXT>
