<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SKorea-Protester     09-07 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SKorea-Protester,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protester In Serious Condition After Brain Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 22-year-old man was seriously
injured today when he was hit by a tear gas canister during a
violent anti-government protest in a southern suburb of Seoul, the
Yonhap news agency reported.
   The South Korean agency said Shin Doo-sup was in serious
condition at a hosptial in Sungnam, about 10 miles south of Seoul,
after brain surgery.
   Shin was among 200 people, most of them college students, who
marched into the streets after a campus rally to oppose the
government of President Roh Tae-woo, the agency said.
   The protesters demanded the arrest of former President Chun
Doo-hwan and his wife, Lee Soon-ja, for alleged involvement in
corruption and financial scandals. Chun stepped down at the end of
a seven-year term in Febuary.
   The protesters hurled rocks at riot police, who retaliated with
tear gas, the report said. Most protesters ran away, but Shin fell
to the ground after being hit by the canister, it said.
</TEXT>
