<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-CampaignAbroad     09-07 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Abroad,0720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Press Comments on Bush-Dukakis Campaign</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports
compiled by Associated Press bureaus on how the U.S. presidential
election campaign is viewed abroad.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a sampling of comment in newspapers overseas on the
presidential race between Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican
George Bush and on Bush's running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FRANCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Dominique Nora in Liberation (leftist) of Paris, Sept. 5: ``For
the moment, George Bush seems to be aligning his campaign more on
foreign policy, while Mike Dukakis concentrates on economic themes.
It is true that well-to-do Republican voters don't really need
reassurance in this field. But paradoxally, Bush gets little profit
from the apparent economic health of the country. His strategic
positioning is delicate: he can neither lay claim to a debatable
heritage nor break with existing policy without disavowing his
colleagues and disappointing his supporters. Will he be one of the
first to belie the old rule according to which obvious prosperity
benefits the incumbents?''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>JAPAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Asahi Shimbun (national, independent), Sept. 1: ``The U.S.
economy has progressed favorably on the surface. Business has seen
nearly six years of expansion, the unemployment rate stands at an
eight-year low. On the other side, however, the external debts are
widning. There is also concern about the recurrence of last
October's `Black Monday'. A trend in the improvement of fiscal and
budget deficits that has continued for some time ... is beginning
to be cloud over. A sense of uneasiness is prevailing within the
United States and people are thinking that things should not be
left they way they are.
   ``Western countries, including Japan, feel the same uneasiness.
...
   ``It is neccessary for the new president, to be elected in
November, to eliminate the uneasiness felt both in and outside the
United States by building up a sound U.S. economy. In concrete
terms, he should restrain excessive consumption and gear up
industry's international competitiveness. ...
   ``The presidential election held every four years is a festival
for the American people as well as an opportunity to check on their
way of living. We hope both candidates and voters would consider
(the nation's) economical responsibility as a superpower.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _The Times of India (national, moderate) of Bombay, Sept. 1:
``The forthcoming U.S. presidential election is disproving the
predictions made earlier by commentators who felt that it would
fail to arouse much popular interest, being viewed by most as a
ho-hum contest between a candidate who was seen as little more than
a `yes-man' to the present incumbent and an opponent perceived to
be as `charismatic as a word processor.' ... The increasingly
popular sport of `Quayling,' which involves beating about the Bush
to flush out the Republican vice presidential candidate's
peccadillos which the media considers fair game to take pot shots
at, has helped allay such qualms.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _The Statesman of Calcutta (north India, conservative), Aug. 31:
``Mr. Quayle is from the far right of the Republican Party, a group
that viewed Mr. Bush's relative moderation as little worse than
apostasy. The choice of the unknown senator has surprised most
observers, though the very fact of his obscurity may be a plus
point for a presidential candidate who so signally lacks charisma.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ITALY</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   _Vittorio Zucconi, in La Repubblica (liberal) of Rome, Aug. 31:
``Bush, wrapped in the stars and stripes flag of an electoral
campaign based on `God, Country, Family, and Defense,' is winning
the rhetorical battle in the distance. He does not want to discuss
real problems.
   ``The Democrats are concentrating their efforts on television
debates in order to improve the weak public appeal of the Greek
from Boston.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   _Rodolfo Brancoli, in Corriere della Sera (moderate) of Milan,
Aug. 31: ``Probably the majority of the voters have not formed a
clear opinion about the two candidates yet, and are changing their
preferences simply on the basis of their last impressions.
   ``The message of Bush is clear and direct: it is `progress
without risk,' a slogan which is natural for any party in power
which has achieved positive results on the whole.''
</TEXT>
