<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1103EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-GandhiCase 1stLd-Writethru a0530 09-07 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Gandhi Case, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rejects Petition Of Condemned Sikhs In Gandhi Murder</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today refused to
review the death sentences of two Sikhs convicted in the 1984
assassination of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, news reports said.
   Press Trust of India quoted a three-judge panel as saying it
found no reason to review the Aug. 3 judgment upholding the murder
convictions and death sentences.
   Satwant Singh and Kehar Singh have no legal appeal left, but
they can ask President Ramaswamy Venkataraman for mercy. If the
president turns down their pleas, they will be hanged.
   The two, and a third Sikh, Balbir Singh, were convicted of
murder and conspiracy by a trial court in January 1986. The
sentence was upheld by the Delhi High Court in December of that
year.
   The Supreme Court acquitted Balbir Singh in July, saying
evidence against him was scanty.
   ``We have examined and re-examined every material on record,''
Press Trust quoted the judges as saying. ``We see no reason to
entertain the review petitions.''
   The three Sikhs were not related. Singh, which means lion in the
Punjabi language, is added to every male Sikh's name by doctrine of
the faith.
   Mrs. Gandhi was shot and killed in the garden of her New Delhi
residence on Oct. 31, 1984, by Satwant Singh and Beant Singh, both
members of her security staff. Beant Singh was shot by other guards
minutes later, and Satwant Singh was wounded.
   Beant's uncle, Kehar Singh, and Balbir Singh, a policeman, were
arrested on charges of conspiracy.
   The assassination was apparently in revenge for an army attack
Mrs. Gandhi ordered on the Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest shrine,
which was being used as a base by militants fighting for an
independent Sikh state.
   The campaign, mainly in the northern state of Punjab, still
lingers and has claimed more than 1,800 lives this year. Sikhs
comprise 2 percent of India's 800 million people, but they are in a
majority in Punjab, a rich agriculture state bordering Pakistan.
   The militants claim they are discriminated against by Hindus,
who make up 80 percent of the country's population. They started
their bloody campaign for a Sikh nation in 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
