<2ND_LINE>PM-Teacher Strikes Rdp, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Walkouts Affect Schools In Five States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with number of states affected
increasing to five, with addition of New Jersey; teachers back at
work in Louisiana district. Picks up 6th graf, `The teachers...'.
SUBS 14th graf, `Classes were...', to UPDATE with orientation held
this morning in Peabody, Mass., ADD detail on New Jersey, UPDATE
Pennsylvania situation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Louisiana teachers went back to school today after a
three-week strike, but officials scrambled for substitutes in
Peabody, Mass., as walkouts affecting more than 110,000 students
began or continued in five states.
   A settlement was signed Tuesday night in southwest Louisiana's
Vermilion Parish after officials agreed to collective bargaining
with the Vermilion Association of Educators representing 600
teachers, cafeteria workers and school bus drivers.
   ``We're very happy. We're going back to school and I think we'll
have a better educational system,'' association President Betty
Girouard said.
   The teachers, on strike since Aug. 26 over the right to
collective bargaining and a 6 percent pay cut imposed in 1987,
returned to work and their 9,500 students today.
   Many of the teachers on strike in 25 public school districts in
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, New Jersey and Illinois were
holding out for raises.
   ``The teachers decided it's time to take a stand and that stand
actually is a walk and that's what we'll be doing tomorrow morning:
walking a picket line,'' Thomas Grady, head of the United Teachers
of Lowell, Mass., said after a unanimous strike vote Tuesday by 970
members.
   The first day of school today was canceled for the city's 13,100
students.
   The teachers are seeking higher pay and longevity bonuses.
   Lowell has filed a petition with the state labor relations board
for a strike investigation hearing, which was set for Thursday,
said Victor Forsley, the School Committee's attorney.
   ``We'll present evidence to prove that an illegal strike is
taking place,'' Forsley said. Teacher strikes are illegal in
Massachusetts.
   Teachers in nearly 40 Massachusetts school districts were going
to work this week without a contract.
   In Peabody, the city's 408 teachers on Tuesday rejected a 17
percent wage increase over three years, holding out for 42 percent.
   ``To sit at the table locked in at 42 percent is totally
irresponsible,'' said Mayor Peter Torigian.
   As teachers picketed peacefully outside, classes went on as
planned today since the program was limited to orientation
sessions, said Assistant Superintendent Gregory Theokas.
Administrators said they were trying to bring in enough substitutes
to cover classes Thursday and Friday. The district has 5,700
students.
   Bert Latessa of the Massachusetts Federation of Teachers
defended the union's position. The 42 percent wage request, Latessa
said, is smaller than it appears because the teachers maintain they
have been performing extra duties such as handling oversized
classes without extra pay.
   In Detroit, more than 1,400 professors and academic staff
members at Wayne State University went on strike Tuesday over union
work rules and salary.
   About 950 clerical workers and secretaries represented by the
United Auto Workers have been on strike there since Aug. 25.
   Here is a brief summary of teacher strikes elsewhere.
   New Jersey: A union representing about 130 teachers, custodians
and clerks at Eastern Regional High School in Voorhees postponed
the first day of school by striking early today after nearly 12
hours of talks broke down, officials said. The school has 1,450
students.
   Michigan: Strikes in 10 districts idled nearly 45,000 students
and more than 2,000 teachers, the Michigan Education Association
said.
   Pennsylvania: Strikes by about 2,750 teachers canceled classes
or disrupted teacher preparation days in 10 districts with 43,800
students.
   Illinois: Strikes in two districts affected 501 teachers and
9,145 pupils in Granite City, Farmer City, Mansfield and Bellflower.
</TEXT>
