<1ST_LINE>r a BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   09-07 0805</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0845</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: gone unnoticed.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 6
   Times-Picayune, New Orleans, on Education Secretary William
Bennett:
   (Education Secretary William) Bennett has clashed often with
public school spokesmen and teacher union officials.
   His critics have attacked him as a gadfly in an administration
that doesn't put its education money where his mouth is.
   There's no question that Bennett purposely has stepped on some
toes.
   But on the whole, he has done a useful and exemplary job of
making his concerns about what is being taught in public schools
everybody's concerns.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 5
   The Mesa (Ariz.) Tribune on the air show crash in Germany:
   Anguished calls have come from some quarters that the United
States disband its Air Force Thunderbirds and Navy Blue Angels
precision flying teams.
   The reason for shutting down decades of esprit and proud
tradition? The crash of three Italian air force stunt planes at an
air show at Ramstein Air Force Base in West Germany.
   What a preposterous and dim-witted proposal in the wake of a
freak accident visited upon the flying team of another country. ...
   Those who are truly concerned about the safety of human beings
will call for the disassembly of chemical and germ warfare units.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 5
   The Decatur (Ala.) Daily on presidential debates:
   It will be good if there are several (presidential) debates, for
from them it is possible to learn more of each man.
   In planned speeches a candidate will only say what he wants the
audience to hear. That is even true in press conferences.
   But a debate is a little different and issues usually are
addressed, even though one or the other or both might have to face
topics not to his liking.
   The campaign is here. Both candidates are at the same starting
line. The one who gets elected is going to be the one who lets the
American people know exactly what he plans and how he is going to
carry out those plans.
   Eight years ago President Reagan said he was going to balance
the budget within four years. He didn't tell us how he was going to
do it and the American voters let him get away with it, and you
know what has happened to the budget.
   Not only do we want to hear what the candidate is going to do,
we want to hear how he is going to do it.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 2
   Farmington (N.M.) Daily Times on U.S.-Soviet friendship:
   The Soviet Union seems to be reneging _ at least a little bit _
on some of its promises which were supposed to bring a new era of
friendship with the United States.
   Along with balking over agreements to dismantle certain
strategic military installations such as the huge radar station
located at Krasnoyarsk in Central Asia, the Soviets seem to be
dragging their feet in withdrawing from Afghanistan.
   We suspect that Soviet General Secretary Mikhail Gorbachev's
overtures toward the United States have been placed on the back
burner until after the U.S. presidential election. ...
   Soviet hesitancy at this time will not go over very well with
Democratic presidential candiadate Michael Dukakis, Republican
presidential hopeful George Bush or the American people.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 2
   The Sheridan (Wyo.) Press on forest fire control policies:
   U.S. Forest Service and Park Service personnel, having gone
through one of the worst forest fire years in their history, are
looking at fire control policies.
   Officials at Yellowstone National Park are under the gun in
particular over their earlier policy of let the fire burn. That
policy didn't last long when fires began to threaten major tourist
areas and since then the park service has put everything it has
into fighting the blazes. ...
   It is easy to be critical of the Forest Service or Park Service
for not getting these fires out immediately. The impossibility of
such a demand is attested to by the extremely dry conditions which
firefighters had to face. ...
   But yes, since the nation's attention is now on forest fires,
the policy should be reviewed. It should be adjusted, wherever
necessary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Sept. 6
   The Flint (Mich.) Journal on low-smoke cigarettes:
   If R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. wants a pat on the back and hearty
congratulations for developing a high-tech, low-smoke cigarette, it
will not get them here.
   The allure of the cigarette, called Premier and to be
test-marketed in three cities starting Oct. 1, is that it will emit
only a trace of ash or smoke that could irritate people nearby.
   However, the Reynolds people aren't claiming that Premier will
be any less dangerous than regular cigarettes.
   Apparently, they are more concerned about prying the
increasingly vehement anti-smoking crowd off their backs than
reducing the health hazard to those who will smoke their cigarettes.
   There's nothing like hitting a problem head on, is there?
</TEXT>
