<DOCNO> AP880907-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AmnestyConcert     09-07 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Concert,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rock Stars On Tour Voice Support for Ethnic Hungarians</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British rock star Peter Gabriel,
speaking in Hungarian learned for the occasion, urged Romania to
respect the rights of ethnic Hungarians during a concert organized
by Amnesty International.
   A capacity crowd of 81,000 that included top Soviet and
Hungarian officials attended the all-star concert Tuesday night at
Nep Stadium, the only Soviet bloc venue on the six-week global tour.
   Bruce Springsteen, dressed in black, played for nearly two
hours. Spectators, many from across the Soviet bloc, sang along
with Springsteen on ``Born In the U.S.A.,'' his opening number.
   British rock star Sting, American folk singer Tracy Chapman and
Senegal's Youssou N'dour also performed in the eight-hour concert,
a rare event in Eastern Europe.
   Individual Western rock groups have been allowed to play in
communist European capitals, but this concert was unusual because
it was sponsored by a Western human rights group. Western
governments and organizations, including Amnesty International,
have accused East bloc countries of rights violations.
   Hungary's premier and Communist Party leader Karoly Grosz, who
met with Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu last month to discuss
the minority issue, was at the concert, but there was no official
report of his presence.
   The state news agency MTI said spectators included Soviet
government spokesman Gennady Gerasimov and Janos Berecz, chief
ideologist of the Hungarian Communist Party and a member of the
ruling Politburo.
   Berecz, described as ``chief patron'' of the concert, was quoted
by MTI as saying, ``There is no need to be afraid of human rights
issues, but persistent efforts are needed for them to be
accomplished.''
   Hungary recently accused Romania of serious rights abuses.
Budapest maintains neighboring Romania is discriminating against
the culture and traditions of the 1.7 million Hungarians in
Romania. Romania has a population of 23 million.
   The major issue is Romania's plan to raze 7,000 villages,
including hundreds of communities populated mainly by ethnic
Hungarians, and resettle the people in agro-industrial centers as
part of a land reform program.
   The tour, which began in London Friday and then went to Paris,
is marking the 40th anniversary of the U.N. Universal Declaration
on Human Rights. It will include 20 cities on five continents.
After the show, the entourage flew to Turin, Italy, where their
next concert is scheduled for Thursday.
   A song by Sting, ``Set Them Free,'' dedicated to children in
South African jails, was especially well received at Tuesday's
concert.
   Hungarian singer Hobo, leader of the local Hobo Blues Band,
asked the audience to ``put our hands together for people who are
oppressed all over the world and (for) our people who suffer in
Romania.''
   Ms. Chapman told the audience: ``You have the right to be free.
Tell the government to support your rights.''
   Some spectators people held up banners pleading the cause of the
Romanian Hungarians and calling for the United Nations to take up
the issue.
   Shortly before 2:00 a.m., the stars got together on stage for a
rendition of Bob Dylan's ``Chimes of Freedom'' and ``Get Up, Stand
Up'' by the late reggae singer Bob Marley.
   In the first media comment, the Hungarian newspaper Esti Hirlap
said, ``Nothing comparable has happened in Nep Stadium since the
late Louis Armstrong's concert here'' in June 1965.
   The newspaper referred to Gabriel, who has performed in Budapest
on his own before, as ``an old friend'' and thanked him for
speaking in Hungarian.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
