<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-FederalRule     09-07 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Federal Rule,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Government Dissolves Legislature Of Northeastern State</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Laldenga, one name, is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national government Wednesday
imposed direct federal rule and dissolved the legislature in the
northeastern state of Mizoram, news reports said.
   The government ordered direct rule, known as president's rule,
in an effort to end a 10-day political crisis prompted by a
rebellion within the Mizo National Front, the state's governing
party, the United News of India said.
   Eight dissident members defected to Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi's Congress Party on Aug. 29, leaving the government of state
Prime Minister Laldenga a minority in the 40-member state
legislature, the news agency said.
   Under the Constitution, elections must be held within a year.
   Mizoram is the fourth state after violence-torn Punjab and
politically unsettled Tamil Nadu and Nagaland to be placed under
president's rule.
   Mizoram, which borders Burma and Bangladesh, was upgraded from
an Indian federal territory to a state in February 1987 under an
agreement signed by Gandhi and the Mizo National Front, which had
waged a 20-year guerrilla war.
   The front took control of the state legislature that month from
the Congress Party, and Laldenga, who led the bloody campaign for
more automony, became prime minister.
   Under the accord, the front agreed to drop demands for
independence from India and the federal government agreed to
upgrade Mizoram to a state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
