<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 09-07 0891</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0581,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Can Keep Cool In Face Of Demonstrations</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `Bush's correction,' to clarify that Pearl
Harbor marked U.S. entry in World War II.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential nominee George
Bush today confused the anniversary of Pearl Harbor Day as he
delivered a tough defense speech to a national American Legion
convention.
   In his talk to about 7,000 members of the nation's largest
veterans' organization, the vice president also said a Democratic
administration would leave the nation ``hostage to Soviet ballistic
missiles.''
   But murmurs spread through the audience as Bush said,``I wonder
how many Americans remember that today is Pearl Harbor Day: 47
years ago to this very day we were hit and hit hard at Pearl
Harbor. And we were not ready ...''
   However, a few minutes into his speech Bush paused abruptly and
said, ``Did I say Sept. 7? Strike that. Dec. 7, 1941,'' Bush, a
World War II Navy pilot, added, ``I'm glad I corrected that, I saw
this guy shaking me off out here.''
   Bush's correction on the date of the Japanese invasion of the
Hawaiian naval base that triggered U.S. entry in World War II won a
good-natured round of applause and laughter from his audience.
   Sheila Tate, Bush's press secretary, said: ``It was 47 years ago
this year and he just said today. He wasn't thinking.''
   The Pearl Harbor remark did not appear in a prepared text of the
vice president's speech.
   Bush spoke a day after President Reagan told the same group that
a victory by Democrats in December would return the nation to a
``Disneyland defense policy.''
   Bush continued along the same vein, claiming rival Michael
Dukakis would weaken the nation's defense.
   ``I do not doubt my opponent's patriotism. But patriotism is not
the issue. The issue is how best to deter war, to keep peace and to
fulfill our country's special responsibility as leader of the free
world,'' Bush said.
   He voiced his strong support for the Reagan's administration's
``Star Wars'' missile defense system.
   ``My opponent opposes the Strategic Defense Initiative. But,
like you in the American Legion, I support it. We canot leave
America hostage to Soviet ballistic missiles,'' Bush said.
   The vice president also said that, if elected, he would not
hesitate in ordering the kind of preemptive military strike that
Reagan called for in 1986 against Libya, if conditions warranted.
   He also said that he would continue to press for the
administration's effort to make the Veterans Administration a
full-fledged Cabinet agency _ if such legislation does not pass
during the rest of Reagan's term.
   On Tuesday, Bush said his experience makes him better able than
Dukakis to keep his cool in the face of the kind of heavy-duty
heckling both candidates were exposed to on the campaign trail.
   ``If I hadn't been through demonstrations before, I would have
gotten a lot tenser,'' Bush told reporters after being jeered by
shipyard workers in Portland, Ore.
   The Democratic nominee, campaigning in the Chicago area,
encountered noisy anti-abortion protesters for the second day in a
row.
   ``I've seen campaigns before,'' Bush said in Everett, Wash.
``I've been at this level of American politics before and there's
nothing like it. It's unique. It's his (Dukakis') first exposure.
   ``When it happens, you don't need to get all uptight about it
and act like you're being put upon, because this is how it works at
this level in politics.''
   Bush will focus on Middle East policy at an address later in the
day to a B'nai B'rith convention in Baltimore.
   Booed and jeered loudly by several hundred unionized iron
workers, some of whom were waving Dukakis signs, Bush told his Port
of Portland audience: ``Don't listen to all this Dukakis stuff.
They're on the ropes and they have to make all this noise.''
   The GOP nominee was taunted and jeered as he spoke to iron
workers at a shipyard. The hard-hattd workers accused Bush of
``union busting'' and booed insistently throughout his speech.
   Bush returned the fire, telling the iron workers to quiet down
and listen to him defend the Reagan administration's record on
job-creation.
   ``The Democrats are trying to mislead you,'' he said. ``Things
aren't going to get worse unless they get elected. I know the truth
sometimes hurts.''
   Bush also produced a 38-year-old union card showing he was a
member of the United Steelworkers of America. Bush belonged to the
union for a brief period when he lived in Compton, Calif., and sold
oil drilling equipment for a Texas-based company. His dues were
paid for 1950 through payroll deductions, the card stated.
   ``How many guys running for president of the United States has
been a member of the U.S. Steelworkers Union?'' Bush asked.
``You're looking at one.''
   Aboard Air Force Two, Bush said the intensity of the protest
surprised him, but he added he may have scored a few points.
   ``When we were in there at the lunch counter, this guy came up
and he says `I'm not for you, I'm still not for you. But you've got
a lot of guts to show up.' Which is nice.''
   Bush said that he counted at least ``two loudmouths'' in the
crowd clearly for him, ``so when I needed succor, I would turn to
them.''
</TEXT>
