<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Tyson-Accident, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0565,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tyson Threatened Suicide, Newspaper Reports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf, ``I'm going ...' with new
quote from source; Picks up 6th graf, `The New ...'; Version moved
on sports wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Tyson, who suffered a concussion when he
smashed his car into a tree, had told his wife shortly before the
crash that he was going to try to kill himself, a newspaper
reported today.
   The Daily News said the information came from ``individuals with
an intimate knowledge'' of Tyson's situation.
   Tyson remains in Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center where he
was taken Sunday after his car struck a tree at the upstate home of
a friend. Doctors said Tuesday that Tyson had lost consciousness
for about 20 minutes and suffered a concussion and amnesia.
   Tyson's Oct. 22 title defense against Frank Bruno in England was
indefinitely postponed because of the injuries.
   ``I'm going to go out and kill myself,'' the Daily News said
Tyson is reported to have told his wife, actress Robin Givens.
``I'm going to crash my car.''
   A source close to Tyson told The Associated Press that the
heavyweight champion was ``brooding all week'' because his wife
refused to be with him at his upstate New York training site,
instead chosing to ``hang out with her fancy friends at the U.S.
Open.''
   The source, however, called any suicide threats just ``idle
threats'' and said those close to Tyson believed he was simply
``looking for a little attention'' from his wife.
   The New York Post today quoted Ruth Roper, Givens' mother, as
saying, ``Mike did absolutely not try to kill himself.''
   Repeated efforts by The Associated Press to reach Tyson's
manager Bill Cayton by telephone were unsuccessful. Dan Klores, a
spokesman for Tyson, said a statement on the Daily News report
would probably be issued later today.
   The News said that after the accident Givens, who is a star of
the ABC television series ``Head of the Class,'' called Tyson's
aides and managers and told them, ``Michael just tried to kill
himself.''
   And the News said Tyson reportedly told Givens in his hospital
room: ``I told you I'd do it. And as soon as I get out of here,
I'll do it again.''
   The News said that according to sources close to Tyson, the
champion has suffered a chemical imbalance since childhood that
prods him to violence, including incidents in which he beat or
threatened his wife.
   According to the News, a psychiatrist treating Tyson has
recommended that he be committed for psychiatric evaluation.
   Doctors evaluating Tyson's physical condition said it would 30
to 60 days before he could resume training.
   The Bruno fight originally was set for Oct. 8, but was postponed
a first time after Tyson broke a bone in his right hand during a
pre-dawn scuffle with former boxer Mitch Green on a New York City
sidewalk.
</TEXT>
