<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iran-Politics     09-07 0748</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Politics,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Withdraws Resignation, Hints At Split In Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's prime minister withdrew his
resignation under orders from Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's
official media reported Wednesday, but he hinted at wide splits in
Tehran's leadership.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said
premier Hussein Musavi told Khomeini in a letter Tuesday night that
he agreed to retract his resignation ``out of concern for Islam and
the revolution and the interests of the country.''
   Musavi later chaired a meeting of his 21-member Cabinet and said
Khomeini's ``instruction'' was a ``divine gift,'' Tehran Radio
reported.
   But in a rare admission by an Iranian leader, he was quoted as
citing ``difficulties in the decision-making process in the
executive'' that he hoped Khomeini's action would eliminate.
   He did not elaborate. But it appeared to be a sideswipe at
President Ali Khamenei, one of his political rivals, underlining
the divisions that have beset the Tehran hierarchy for some time.
   Khomeini's intervention after Musavi submitted his resignation
Monday may have defused the political crisis for now.
   But the political divisions were largely set aside during the
eight-year war with Iraq, and Western analysts believe Iran faces a
period of political turbulence now that the fighting has stopped.
   Musavi said he was resigning because as many as eight of his
ministers, more than one-third of his Cabinet, would fail to win a
vote of confidence in the Majlis, Iran's 270-seat parliament.
   On Tuesday, hours before the parliament was to vote on the
Cabinet, Khamenei's office said Musavi's resignation was turned
down.
   IRNA said Musavi agreed to stay on after Khomeini told him:
``Your resignation letter caused some surprise. ... You should have
at least mentioned something about it to me or high-ranking
officials.''
   Khomeini's letter, broadcast by Tehran Radio, told Musavi: ``In
the event that you fail to reach agreement as regards some of the
ministers, actions will be carried out as they were in the past.''
   Khomeini did not elaborate. But he rescued Musavi from a
no-confidence vote in the Majlis four years ago by appealing to
deputies for unity while Iran was at war with Iraq.
   The revolutionary patriarch stressed: ``It is the legal right of
the Majlis to vote for any minister that it desires to vote for.
   ``In these days, when the people are sending their children to
the fronts of sacrifice to assist Islam, it is no time for
complaining and resigning ... You should continue your service in
your bastion as prime minister.''
   Tuesday's parliamentary session was canceled after Musavi's
resignation was announced, but a new session was scheduled for
Sunday.
   Rival factions in Tehran have disputed postwar policies,
particularly the task of reconstruction and efforts by Parliament
Speaker Hashemi Rafsanjani to bring Iran out of political isolation.
   Rafsanjani, the acting military commander and the most powerful
figure in Iran after Khomeini, and Khamenei favor seeking foreign
investment to help rebuild the country's shattered economy.
   Musavi, a radical technocrat who has been premier for seven
years, opposes outside intervention. He fears it will drive Iran
into debt and allow in the multinationals booted out after the 1979
revolution.
   Philip Robbins of the London-based Royal Institute for
International Affairs said: ``It was easy enough to decide during
the war not to take loans from the West when no one was offering
them anyway.
   ``But now Western companies are willing to do business with
Iran, that presents the Iranians with some difficult decisions,''
he said in a telephone interview.
   Musavi, despite impeccable revolutionary credentials, has no
power base of his own like Rafsanjani, Khamenei and Interior
Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, a hardliner whose influence is
growing.
   Iran's internal divisions were sharpened when Khomeini decided
last month to accept a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire in the war with
Iraq after a string of battlefield defeats.
   Musavi won a personal vote of confidence in parliament in July,
squelching speculation that he might be eased out and replaced,
possibly by Mohtashemi.
   But the political feuding probably will come to a head by next
year when Khamenei's term as president expires, analysts said.
Khomeini has decreed Khamenei cannot run again.
   The debate over Iran's direction in the postwar era is only part
of the power struggle between rival factions over who will fill the
political vacuum when Khomeini dies.
   The 88-year-old revolutionary leader reportedly has been ailing.
Iranian leaders have denied that, but Khomeini has appeared
increasingly frail in recent public appearances.
</TEXT>
