<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Gorilla     09-07 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorilla,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Gorilla Takes Up Residence in Albuquerque Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-day-old gorilla may soon believe
his mother is Edna Moore, who has made a place for the baby ape in
her home.
   The infant lowland African gorilla arrived Tuesday on a flight
from New York, wearing diapers and a white hooded sweatshirt. He
snuggled close to Mrs. Moore, who will raise him until he is old
enough to join his brother, Jamie, at the Rio Grande Zoo.
   Mrs. Moore, wife of zoo Director John Moore, has raised other
gorillas. She said her home has been ready for the baby since it
was born Friday.
   ``I just pulled out the bassinet and started sterilizing
bottles,'' she said.
   The ape's mother, Huerfanita, is on loan for breeding purposes
to the Bronx Zoo in New York.
   ``If the mother could raise the baby I would let it,'' Moore
said. ``But sometimes you lose the baby, so you must take every
precaution to keep them because they're so rare.''
   Mrs. Moore fed the baby a bottle of formula milk twice during
the four-hour, 20-minute Lear-jet flight with Albuquerque Journal
Publisher T.H. Lang as pilot. Zoo curator Ingrid Schmidt
accompanied them.
   Mrs. Moore said she believes the infant will begin recognizing
her as his mother in about a month.
   The couple has two children, and they also have raised four
orangutans as well as Jamie since they came to New Mexico.
   Moore says he knows when the raising of the gorillas stops.
   ``The first time they arm wrestle with you and push you to the
table, it's time to make a move to the zoo,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 09-07 0893</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0571,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Pushing Education As Campaign Launches Nationwide Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 8th graf pvs, `The Democratic,' with
additional plane problems for Dukakis campaign; picks up 9th graf
and edits for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis switched his focus from the
economy to education today as his campaign and the Democratic Party
began major advertising efforts touting his record as Massachusetts
governor and criticizing Republican policies.
   Dukakis took particular aim at GOP rival George Bush who has
said repeatedly that he wants to be known as ``the education
president.''
   In remarks prepared for delivery during an afternoon appearance
at Kean College in Union, N.J., the Democratic nominee criticized
Reagan administration cuts in federal student aid programs and
outlined his own college opportunity proposal.
   Dukakis described his proposal that would have students receive
a loan in return for their agreement to pay back a percentage of
their income for the rest of their working lives.
   As for Bush, Dukakis asked, ``Where was George Bush while his
administration was doing its best to slam the door of college
opportunity in the face of millions of young people across this
country?''
   ``Where was he while his administration was denying
middle-income families the hope for a future of prosperity and
success for their children?''
   ``George was right there all the time. Not doing and not saying
a thing,'' Dukakis said.
   The Democratic nominee arrived home Tuesday night, ending a
strange campaign day that saw his first event disrupted by
anti-abortion protesters and his only other scheduled event
canceled because of minor problems with his chartered plane.
   The campaign's plane troubles continued today as a second craft
carrying additional reporters, televisions crews and campaign
staffers was grounded in Boston by what aides said was hydraulic
problems. The plane, a Midway Airlines DC-9 jet, was the same one
that Dukakis had flown from Chicago to Boston a day earlier.
   Dukakis, some of his traveling press and campaign aides flew to
New Jersey today in their familiar Presidential Airways Boeing 737.
Dukakis had been forced to abandon that plane in Chicago Tuesday
when a Federal Aviation Administration spot inspection found
several minor maintenance problems.
   The plane was later flown to Boston empty and was back in
service this morning.
   Dukakis wasted no time Tuesday in lashing into Bush for telling
a shipyard worker in Oregon earlier that his wages had dropped from
$13.36 to $9.50 per hour during the Reagan administration because
of ``competitive change.''
   ``George Bush made it clear today that he really does not
understand the hopes and dreams and aspirations of millions and
millions of American workers across this country,'' Dukakis said at
the airport. ``That's not an adequate answer to American workers.''
   In ads that began airing Tuesday in several battleground states,
the Democratic National Committee accuses Reagan and Republicans of
misleading Americans about the threat posed by the federal budget
deficit. The ``Hey Pal'' ad asks voters whether they can afford
four more years of GOP control of the White House _ a question
Dukakis has asked at his recent rallies.
   The DNC will supplement that ad later this week with another
commercial focusing on the ``bring prosperity home'' theme, Dukakis
spokesman Leslie Dach said.
   The Dukakis ad, which began airing nationally Tuesday night, is
titled ``New Era'' and was shown in California and Texas prior to
the Republican National Convention. It features a montage of shots
from Dukakis' speech at the Democratic convention and lists his
major accomplishments as governor.
   The Dukakis campaign also began airing a third ad just in Texas,
a 30-second spot touting Dukakis and his running mate, Texas Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, for supporting legislation to give workers 60 days'
notice before a plant closing.
   Reagan and Bush opposed the legislation but the president
allowed it to become law without his signature. Bush's running
mate, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, led the Senate opposition to the
measure; Bentsen was its chief sponsor.
   The ad shows a red stamp reading ``No'' superimposed over photos
of Bush and Quayle as the announcer says, ``Shouldn't there be a
law to give you and your community 60 days' notice?''
   A Dukakis-Bentsen campaign logo then appears on the screen as
the announcer says, ``The choice is clear.''
   Dukakis spent several hours Tuesday stuck in Chicago while the
Federal Aviation Administration conducted a surprise inspection of
his Presidential Airways charter. Inspectors found three minor
safety problems, forcing Dukakis to cancel an appearance in Ohio.
The Boeing 737 was repaired in Chicago and was to rejoin the
campaign today.
   His only other appearance came in what usually is friendly turf
for Dukakis _ an ethnic gathering. But his speech at a
Polish-American restaurant outside Chicago was delayed for several
minutes because of anti-abortion protesters, several of whom were
pushed and dragged out of the hall by Dukakis supporters.
   Dukakis says he personally opposes abortion but believes women
should be allowed to choose to have an abortion.
   On the flight home, Dukakis joined the pilot and co-pilot in the
cockpit for the landing in Boston. Just after the plane landed a
cone over the rear galley popped off and dropped to the tarmac. The
pilot said a passenger had pulled an emergency release cable that
opens the cone only when the plane is on the ground.
</TEXT>
