<DOCNO> AP880907-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1422EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-FloridaPrimary     09-07 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Florida Primary,0797</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mack Savors Victory While Democrats Launch Runoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Connie Mack III, fresh from victory in a
Republican Senate primary, said Wednesday the GOP has a
``tremendous opportunity'' to reclaim the seat, while two Democrats
launched a runoff campaign that threatens to divide the party.
   The conservative Mack, grandson and namesake of the legendary
Philadelphia A's baseball manager, turned back a challenge from
former outspoken federal prosecutor Robert Merkle in Tuesday's
voting.
   State Insurance Commissioner Bill Gunter led a six-way
Democratic race, but failed to win a majority and will compete Oct.
4 against the second-place finisher, Rep. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay.
   In a Nevada Senate primary, Republican Sen. Chic Hecht coasted
to nomination for a second term and will face Democratic Gov. Dick
Bryan, who buried three challengers.
   The Florida seat at stake is now occupied by Democrat Lawton
Chiles, who decided to retire after three terms.
   Mack, 47, began his day in Key West, 90 miles from Communist
Cua, to emphasize his campaign theme of ``less taxes, less
spending, less government _ more freedom.''
   He pledged to reach out to ``conservative Democrats'' and said,
``We felt all along we had a tremendous opportunity, and obviously,
if that becomes a very tense runoff election that's divisive, plus
we add to that George Bush is running very strongly in Florida,
that just adds to our opportunity.''
   Mack got campaign help during the primary from President Reagan
and indicted former National Security Council aide Oliver North,
and expects strong national Republican support for the general
election.
   MacKay, meanwhile, picked up the endorsement of Rep. Dan Mica,
who ran third in Tuesday's primary. Mica overwhelmingly carried his
home Palm Beach County and neighboring Broward, and MacKay, from
Ocala in north-central Florida, said Mica's support should be ``a
tremendous help'' in South Florida.
   ``We're in high gear now, but we've got a lot of work to do,''
MacKay, 55, said as he headed to South Florida for joint news
conferences with Mica.
   Gunter, insurance commissioner since 1976, was in Tallahassee
working out strategy for his third Senate runoff. He told reporters
he wasn't surprised by the Mica endorsement of his opponent, and
said he was pleased with his first-place standing, although he has
slipped from initial polls four months ago.
   ``When you've got undecided voters and when you have a situation
where the front-runner is being dumped on as I was, you're going to
see some settling,'' Gunter said. ``I'm delighted with our
position.''
   Gunter and MacKay both expressed hope for a positive runoff
campaign, but they clashed repeatedly during the primary campaign,
as they had in the 1980 Senate primary.
   Democrats hold a 3-2 lead in statewide voter registration, but
intraparty divisions caused by bitter runoffs were blamed for their
defeat in the 1986 governor's race and 1980 Senate race.
   MacKay, 55, had accused Gunter, 54, of conflict of interest for
accepting contributions from the industry he regulates, and his
campaign manager, Greg Farmer, called Gunter's 12 years in his
current office ``a saga of sleaze.'' Gunter called MacKay
hypocritical for accepting funds from political action committees
that he said wanted to influence votes in ``the ultimate regulatory
body _ Congress.''
   MacKay ran third in the 1980 primary in which Gunter ran second,
then defeated incumbent Richard Stone in a runoff. Gunter lost to
Republican Paula Hawkins, but Democrat Bob Graham won that seat
back by defeating Mrs. Hawkins in 1986.
   With all votes counted, Mack had 394,444 votes, or 62 percent,
to Merkle's 244,926 votes, or 38 percent.
   Gunter tallied 372,434 votes or 38 percent, followed by MacKay
with 258,648 votes or 26 percent. Mica, 44, was third with 179,729
votes or 18 percent. State Sen. Patricia ``Pat'' Frank had 117,379
votes, or 12 percent.
   Former Republican Gov. Claude R. Kirk, 62, was fifth with 50,304
votes or 5 percent, and former Senate postal clerk Fred Rader, 41,
had 11,617 votes for 1 percent.
   Elsewhere in Florida, 10-term Democratic Rep. William Chappell
of Ormond Beach captured 70 percent of the vote against primary
challenger Charley Roberts, a retired Army veteran. Chappell's name
has been mentioned in published reports about the defense
procurement probe, but he denied wrongdoing.
   Mack's predecessor, L.A. ``Skip'' Bafalis, made it into a runoff
as he sought to win back the congressional seat he gave up to run
for governor in 1982. In a five-way race, he finished second with
29 percent to former Lee County Commissioner Porter Goss, who had
38 percent. Retired Army. Gen. James Dozier, held hostage 42 days
in 1981 by Red Brigade terrorists in Italy, finished third, at 18
percent.
</TEXT>
