<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Burundi     09-07 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Burundi,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Asks International Inquiry into Burundi Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday it has
asked the government of Burundi to accept international involvement
into an inquiry on last month's tribal massacre that is believed to
have claimed thousands of lives.
   Department spokesman Charles Redman said the inquiry would cover
both the causes and solutions to the violence that has erupted
periodically in Burundi, in central Africa.
   More than 100,000 Hutus, who make up more than 85 percent of the
population, were killed in 1972 and an estimated 5,000 died in the
slaughter last month. The Hutus have been feuding for decades with
the Tutsis, who dominate Burundi's politics.
   Redman confirmed earlier independent accounts that government
forces were responsible for some of killings. While condemning the
armed forces' role, he said authorities in Burundi have permitted
journalists and embassy observers free access to area where the
atrocities occurred.
   Redman said there has been no cutoff of U.S. aid but that
officials are assessing the situation.
</TEXT>
