<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1455EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachWastes     09-07 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Wastes,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Signs Beach Waste Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL STASHENKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anyone who illegally dumps the kind of
infectious medical wastes that turned 1988 into a nightmare for
beachgoers faces longer jail terms and stiffer fines under
legislation signed into law Wednesday.
   Gov. Mario Cuomo said the syringes, blood vials and other
medical debris that washed ashore this summer ``threaten the
livelihood of thousands who work at our beaches and the enjoyment
of the millions of New Yorkers who use the beaches for recreation.''
   Several popular beaches were temporarily closed during the
state's hottest summer in decades when the debris came ashore.
   Under the bill approved by Cuomo, penalties of up to four years
in prison and fines of up to $50,000 could be brought against
people convicted of illegally disposing of so-called red bag
medical wastes. The name refers to waste that is to be thrown out
in specially marked containers.
   Previously, state law had provided for illegal medical waste
dumpers to face up to 15 days in jail and fines of up to to $2,500,
according to state Department of Environmental Conservation
spokesman R.W. Groneman.
   Cuomo also said he signed a companion bill Wednesday that
provides $2 million to pay for stepped up enforcement of the
infectious waste disposal rules by the state departments of
Environmental Conservation and Parks, Recreation and Historic
Preservation.
   The bills are aimed at putting teeth into regulations recently
established by the state Environmental Conservation and Health
departments that set out guidelines for disposal of medical wastes
and require ``cradle to grave'' tracking.
   Among the debris discovered on New York beaches this summer were
vials containing human blood infected with the HIV-virus _ the
AIDS-related immune system deficiency _ and hepatitis, according to
state Health Department tests.
   Groneman said the DEC has not finalized its report on the source
of the debris.
</TEXT>
