<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOORHEAD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alvaro Garza Jr., who survived 45 minutes
underwater in a river last December, began a new school year
feeling completely recovered.
   ``I'm going to be able to do everything on my own now,'' said
Alvaro, who was trailed by reporters and photographers Tuesday, his
first day of sixth grade.
   The 11-year-old boy fell through ice on the Red River, which
divides Moorhead from Fargo, N.D., as he tried to retrieve a dead
squirrel. When pulled out of the water by rescuers, his body
temperature was 77 degrees and he showed no signs of life.
   Doctors used a heart-lung bypass machine to warm his body, and
four days later he could communicate by blinking his eyes. He went
home after 17 days in the hospital.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suzanne Marx, known here as the queen of
charity fund raising, says she's found a project to culminate her
20 years of do-gooding _ the Nancy Reagan Center to rehabilitate
drug users.
   Mrs. Marx has promised the first lady she will raise $10 million
to get the project going.
   ``The first lady plans to devote even more of her time to this
cause once she leaves the White House. It is very important to
her,'' Mrs. Marx, 50, said in a recent interview.
   Mrs. Marx isn't alone in soliciting funds for Mrs. Reagan's
anti-drug center.
   Merv Griffin kicked off the campaign with a May 2 breakfast,
where about $2.5 million was pledged. Another $2 million is the
goal of philanthropist Carroll Petrie and American Express Chairman
James Robinson III, who will focus on the New York area.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
