<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrazilianFugitives     09-07 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazilian Fugitives,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warrants Ordered for Leaders of Therapy Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arrest warrants were issued Wednesday for two
leaders of a Brazilian-based therapy group after the defendants
failed to appear in federal court on currency violations.
   The defendants were identified by authorities as Norberto Keppe,
founder and head of the International Society of Analytical
Trilogy, and another leader, Claudia Pacheco. Both are Brazilians.
   They were arrested June 24 at Kennedy International Airport for
allegedly failing to report, as required, $100,000 in cash which
was hidden in their luggage, authorities said. They were charged
with two counts of currency violations and if convicted, would face
a maximum of 10 years in prison.
   Trilogy was founded during the 1970s in Brazil by Keppe, who
claims to have developed a method of therapy that can cure mental
and physical illnesses, including cancer and AIDS.
   After the two didn't attend a pretrial hearing Wednesday, U.S.
District Judge Raymond Dearie ordered arrest warrants.
   The prosecutor, Assistant U.S. Attorney Thomas Roche, said the
government also would begin forfeiture proceedings for the
defendants' joint $1 million bail, which was secured by two
buildings owned by the society.
   Harvey Kaminsky, who represents the defendants, told Dearie he
had tried to contact his clients last week and this week but had
not heard from them. He said he did not know where they had gone.
   Kaminsky said Trilogy had about 100 patients in New York,
thousands in Brazil and participants in Europe and other parts of
the world. Patients are encouraged to live in communal households
and attend therapy sessions at least once a week.
   The society also has established various business enterprises,
including a travel agency, cleaning service and a printing house.
   Kaminsky said Keppe and Pacheco were on their way to London to
attend an international conference for Triology when they were
arrested at the airport.
</TEXT>
