<HEAD>Cuomo: Governor as Crime Fighter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo joined the battle against
subway crime Wednesday, helping police run down a man who allegedly
had stolen tokens from a station.
   ``It happened very, very suddenly,'' Cuomo said. ``We joined the
chase.''
   Cuomo was on his way to a school to promote school construction
legislation when he and two state troopers in his car spotted a
group of transit police officers chasing a man with a bag of tokens
around his neck in Harlem.
   Cuomo said his driver, Trooper Mary Ellen Fitzpatrick, tried to
cut the man off with the car. When he kept running, she and Cuomo
jumped out and gave chase.
   Fitzpatrick, who was dressed in a business suit, kicked off her
shoes and ran in her stockings.
   ``I maintain _ she differs with me _ that I beat her down the
block,'' Cuomo later joked.
   The man ran into a store, where he was stopped by a New York
City police officer. He was charged with tampering, larceny and
resisting arrest.
   Al O'Leary, spokesman for the transit police, said the man had
been seen tampering with a turnstile at a subway station, and
personally collecting tokens from passengers.
