<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AirShow     09-07 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Show,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Toll Climbs To 54 In Air Show Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAMSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The death toll from the Ramstein
air show disaster rose to 54 on Wednesday when a West German man
died from severe burn injuries, a state official said.
   ``A 35-year-old man died at about 11 a.m. today at a clinic in
Offenbach,'' Rhineland-Palatinate state spokesman Juergen Dietzen
told The Associated Press.
   He said the victim was from Rhineland-Palatinate state.
   Dietzen also said 162 people remained hospitalized from the Aug.
28 disaster at the U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein, in
Rhineland-Palatinate state.
   ``About 30 of them are in serious condition and a few are in
critical condition,'' Dietzen said.
   The Ramstein air show disaster occurred when three Italian
stunt-flying jet planes collided and one of them hurtled into a
huge crowd of people, exploding into a fireball.
   Spectators _ children as well as adults _ ran in terror from the
burning wreckage, many of them with horrible burns. Dietzen said
seven children were among the dead.
   He gave the following nationality breakdown for the dead: 47
Germans, two Americans, one each from France and the Netherlands,
and the three Italian pilots.
   Dietzen also said four people are still missing, but ``there is
no certainty that these people were at the air show.''
   Meanwhile, in Farnborough, England, the first full-scale display
since the disaster began.
   The Red Arrows, the Royal Air Force's display team of seven
scarlet Hawk fighters, performed daredevil aerobatics with
customary flair and precision for a crowd of 35,000. The team will
perform daily through Sunday, when the show ends.
   In Grimbergen, Belgium, an air show scheduled for Sunday was
canceled because of the German disaster, organizers said.
   Grimbergen Airfield Promotion said in a statement the
cancellation of its show was ordered by the town of Grimbergen,
north of Brussels.
</TEXT>
