<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Lotto 4thLd-Writethru a0665 09-07 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lotto, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0665,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lottery Officials Expect To Announce Winner</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to include Ryan's age.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate broker who said six
numbers had been ``driving me crazy'' presented a winning Lotto
ticket today to claim her record $55 million prize.
   Sheela Ryan of Winter Springs said she didn't know what she'd do
with her winnings and was unsure whether she would quit her job.
She can pick up her first check for $2,767,361 next week.
   ``I've always been middle class and the middle class always
needs money,'' she said at a news conference with her two attorneys
and Lottery officials.
   Ms. Ryan, 63, a native New Yorker, said she was single and had
no children.
   She said today marked her first trip on a plane, her first news
conference and ``this is the first time I've ever won $55 million.''
   She said she picked the first six numbers that she read on the
front page of The Orlando Sentinel: 3, 27, 19, 35, 20 and 5. She
bought the winning ticket in the central Florida town of Longwood.
   ``These numbers were driving me crazy,'' she said. She had won
$4 twice previously in the game. Ms. Ryan said she had been buying
four tickets a week until Florida offered a $23 million jackpot in
early August. Since then, she's been buying five tickets.
   Before Ms. Ryan claimed her prize, several dozen Lotto players
claimed they had the winning ticket.
   ``We've had several dozen calls from folks saying, `We have the
winning ticket. What do we do?' without identifying themselves or
their city or anything else,'' Lottery Secretary Rebecca Paul said
Tuesday. ``Until someone comes through the door with a ticket, we
take it all with a grain of salt.''
   It's not a crime to claim a winning lottery ticket, but it's a
felony to present an altered lottery ticket for payment.
   One of the claimants was Charles Hill, an elementary school
janitor in the tiny hamlet of Bristol, about 280 miles northwest of
Longwood. Officials said Hill told them his wet ticket was
recovered from a pile of laundry after Saturday's drawing.
   Hill's claim was enough to get him a $23,000 Chevrolet van with
no cash down.
   Tommy Thomas, owner of a Panama City Chevrolet dealership, said
Tuesday that he gave a brand new mauve van to Hill after Liberty
County Sheriff Harrell W. Revell told the credit manager that the
ticket was bona fide.
   ``We took a chance with them,'' Thomas said. ``I figured if they
were lucky enough to win the lottery, we could do that.''
   But lottery officials said today that Hill did not have the
winning ticket.
   ``We have denied Mr. Hill's claim based on the fact he does not
have the original of his ticket,'' a statement by Tom Bell, general
counsel for the Lottery Department, read. ``The Lottery's
verification procedures on the copy provided by Mr. Hill indicate
that he does not have the winning ticket.''
   Several dozen people other than Hill have called the department
claiming to have the winning ticket, according to Mrs. Paul. She
said one identified himself as a resident of Minnesota, and another
caller came from central Florida.
   The jackpot's final value was put at $55.16 million, which
breaks down into 20 annual payments of $2.76 million before taxes.
Earlier estimates put the jackpot at $54 million, a record for a
state lottery.
   Gov. Bob Martinez, who has opposed the lottery, announced
Tuesday that it had broken $1 billion in sales since it began in
January. The biggest winners, he said, are Florida's schools.
   ``This record-breaking pace is exciting, both for the players
and public education in Florida,'' Martinez said.
   Since 35 percent of lottery sales go to education, $350 million,
or double earlier projections, will go to support education,
Martinez said.
</TEXT>
