<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-Dole     09-07 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Dole,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Welcomes Quayle Back To Senate, Hedges on Asset to GOP Ticket</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole welcomed Dan
Quayle back to the Senate on Wednesday, giving him a fire
extinguisher to fight off the press but stopping short of calling
Quayle an asset to the GOP ticket.
   ``I know you've been on a roller coaster ride,'' Dole said as he
welcomed the Indiana senator back after a summer recess in which
Quayle became the party's vice presidential nominee.
   ``Thank goodness our roller coaster is going up and (Michael)
Dukakis' is disappearing out of sight,'' Dole said. Dole said
Dukakis should get ``the Rip Van Winkle Award for 1988 ... He's
been asleep. ... He just disappeared.''
   Since his nomination, Quayle has been dogged by controversies
over his military service, personal life and academic record, and
some in his own party have expressed skepticism about whether the
41-year-old senator should be on the ticket.
   Dole, a onetime presidential hopeful who was on George Bush's
short list of vice presidential prospects, has himself expressed
reservations about Quayle. Dole said recently that people of his
generation might have problems with allegations that Quayle used
his wealthy family's influence to get into the National Guard
during the Vietnam War.
   He repeated that view Wednesday, saying, ``If he did get certain
breaks ... that would create a problem in the minds of many,
particularly I would say in my generation.''
   Dole was asked by reporters after his reception for Quayle
whether he now thinks Quayle is an asset to the Republican ticket.
   ``I think he's becoming an asset,'' Dole said. Did that mean the
senator thought Quayle had achieved that status yet, he was
pressed. ``Becoming,'' Dole replied.
   At the reception, Dole presented Quayle with a small fire
extinguisher, which he said Quayle could ``spray on the press from
time to time.''
   He also gave Quayle a framed copy of the Pledge of Allegiance.
The Republicans have critized Dukakis, the Democratic presidential
nominee, for vetoing a Massachusetts bill that would have required
teachers to lead students in the pledge. Quayle devoted his Labor
Day fall campaign kickoff speech to the pledge.
   Dole called Quayle a ``rising young star in our party.'' Later,
he told reporters that despite Quayle's rocky start as the vice
presidential nominee, the young senator was ``catching on pretty
fast.''
   ``You just get out there and do it,'' Dole said. ``It's a whole
new world when you start a national campaign. There's constant
media attention and I think he's adapted very well in the last few
weeks.''
   But Dole gave a somewhat equivocal answer when asked about
Quayle's qualifications for national office.
   ``I think Dan Quayle is a very quick study. It's probably not
fair to compare him with somebody who's been in the Senate for
12-18 years or more.'' Dole said.
   Quayle's Democratic counterpart, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, is
completing his 18th year in the Senate.
   ``My view is that he (Quayle) is qualified. It's like saying
compared to who? You can always find someone better than anybody I
know of in any business or profession. There are others who have
more experience. But I think Bush saw certain attributes he thought
would be helpful to get him elected and he chose Dan Quayle. It's
George Bush's choice,'' Dole said.
   Quayle told his fellow Republican senators, ``No matter what
happens in this election, the people who know me best and the
people I am closest to are the people right here in this room.''
   ``I can't wait to get back out there'' on the campaign trail, he
said. Quayle leaves Thursday for a quick trip to Illinois and Ohio.
He said he would return to Washington for key Senate votes as he
was needed.
</TEXT>
