<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Jet Crash,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Jet Crashes In Southern Germany, Kiling Pilot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALW, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British air force fighter jet
crashed Wednesday, killing the pilot and injuring the American
co-pilot, police said.
   Police in the town of Calw, about 20 miles southeast of
Stuttgart, said the plane crashed at about 11 a.m. in an open field.
   They said the Royal Air Force plane hit a high-voltage line just
before it crashed, but it could not be determined if that was the
cause of the accident.
   Police said the British pilot of the Jaguar jet was killed in
the crash. An American who co-piloted the jet was slightly injured
after he ejected.
   British Army spokesman Col. Michel Baugniet said the aircraft
was from the the Coltshall base in England and was in West Germany
on a routine training mission.
   Officials declined to release the names of the crew pending
notification of relatives.
   The crash came 11 days after three Italian Air Force jets
collided during an air show at a U.S. Air Force base in Ramstein.
One of the stunt jets plowed into a crowd of spectators and
exploded, killing more than 50 people.
   A series of NATO warplane crashes in West Germany in recent
weeks has prompted demands that low-level military training flights
be reduced or stopped.
   At least 80 people have died as a result of military air crashes
in West Germany since March 30.
  
