<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BarnardCentennial     09-07 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Barnard Centennial,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One of Seven Sisters _ Barnard College _ Kicks Off Centennial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With trumpets blaring and a procession of alumni
from classes dating to 1893, Barnard College on Wednesday kicked
off a yearlong centennial celebration.
   Thirty-one years after women earned the right to vote, women in
New York City earned the right to get a college education without
leaving home when Barnard opened its doors on Oct. 7, 1889.
   It was the first women's college in the city and is one of the
elite ``seven sister'' colleges. Barnard is an independent college,
though affiliated with Columbia University.
   Speaking at a special convocation at Riverside Church, Barnard
President Ellen V. Futter said the college will continue to press
government leaders to address the needs of women and men.
   She called for ``a restatement of the goals of the women's
movement,'' and for resolution of national issues including
maternity and paternity leave, care of children and the aging,
flexible work schedules and preschool education.
   Ms. Futter said it was also ``long past time to do more than
just acknowledge the feminization of poverty'' and time to ``offer
a stronger hand up to women of color.''
   Francine du Plessix Gray, a 1952 Barnard graduate and author of
``Lovers and Tyrants'' and ``World Without End,'' delivered the
keynote speech.
   In it, she also spoke about the past and how women of the '60s
gave up motherhood for ``sisterhood'' and how the emphasis is once
again on motherhood and the family.
   ``Only in the last two or three years have we begun to strive
for a synthesis of sisterhood and motherhood _ a synthesis which,
if we complete it, may offer us greater serenity and power than
we've ever had,'' she said.
   Following the convocation, alumni paraded to the main campus for
the dedication of the new, $20 million Centennial Hall dormitory
which will house 400 students.
   The oldest participate was 99-year-old Hannah Bessmer.
   Thousands of balloons in Barnard blue were released as faculty,
students and their families feasted on a four-foot-high birthday
cake.
   Barnard has 2,200 students. Tuition and fees total about $13,000
a year.
</TEXT>
