<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1645EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SharpevilleSix     09-07 0619</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highest Court Considers Appeal From Condemned Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of blacks whose death
sentences have drawn worldwide protest spent their 1,000th day on
Death Row on Thursday, waiting for the country's highest court to
decide whether they can appeal.
   The five-judge Appeal Court in Bloemfontein, which turned down
an earlier appeal from the Sharpeville Six, heard arguments
Wednesday from defense attorneys asking that the case be reopened
to hear evidence from a state witness who said police pressured him
to lie.
   The government has indefinitely postponed the hangings of the
five men and one woman until the judicial proceedings are complete.
The court did not say when it would render its decision.
   President P.W. Botha has resisted appeals from the United
States, Britain, the United Nations, most European nations,
Australia, Japan and Canada to grant clemency in the case.
   Diplomats from 13 countries attended the hearing.
   The defendants were sentenced to die for their roles in the 1984
mob killing of black town councilor Kuzwayo Dlamini.
   No evidence was presented that the six contributed physically to
his death. But they were convicted in 1985 under the principle of
``common purpose'' because they allegedly were active members of
the crowd that stoned and burned Dlamini during riots over a rent
increase.
   Botha has said he will not intervene in the judicial process,
and he already has turned down a request for clemency before the
new evidence of possible perjury was brought forward.
   The state attorneys told the Appeal Court it had no jurisdiction
to review the case once the president had made a decision, even if
new evidence was raised.
   In June, the lower court judge who imposed the death sentences
rejected a motion to reopen the trial to consider the new evidence.
He said the defendants could appeal to the higher court but he felt
their only hope lay with Botha.
   Sydney Kentridge, a defense lawyer, said the controversy
surrounding the witness, Joseph Manete, could be resolved only if
the case were reopened to allow new oral evidence. But he also
agreed with a suggestion by one of the judges, J.L. Van der Merwe,
that Wednesday's hearing could constitute the actual appeal. He
said he could imagine no further argument than had already been
presented.
   The defense submitted an affidavit in which Manete said he
falsely testified that two of the defendants were at the scene of
the killing. He also wrote a letter to Botha, describing in detail
how police allegedly assaulted and threatened him and other
witnesses.
   ``I cannot interfere with the judicial system in South Africa
unless it is completed, and only when it is completed will I, as a
human being, deal with this matter on merit,'' Botha said in a
British television interview Tuesday.
   Some of Botha's critics have accused him of hypocrisy on this
issue, noting that he ordered a halt to prosecution of South
African soldiers about to go on trial for murder in South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia.
   The Sharpeville Six are Francis Mokgesi, 31; Reid Mokoena 24;
Oupa Moses Diniso, 32; Duma Joshua Khumalo, 28; Reginald Sefatsa,
32, and Theresa Ramashamola, 27.
   Ms. Ramashamola would be the first South African woman executed
in connection with a case widely viewed by activists as political.
Violence against black officials who cooperate with the
white-dominated government's segregated political structures is
considered by many blacks to be a consequence of apartheid.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
