<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Soviets-Alaska     09-07 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets-Alaska,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Turns Out To Greet Soviet Visitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOME, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first official delegation of Soviets to
cross the Bering Strait since it was closed 40 years ago arrived
Wednesday in this historic gold-mining town, seeking to improve
contacts between the superpowers' most remote regions.
   Crowds braved rain and a 42-degree temperature to cheer the
Soviets' arrival aboard the Dmitri Laptev, a hydrological research
vessel. Several Eskimos in the group hugged and talked in their
native language, greeting relatives and friends they had not seen
for decades.
   ``It's just like home,'' said Oleg Kulinkin, mayor of the Soviet
town of Provideniya, across the strait. ``In the first minutes,
there was the land, grass, the weather and, most important,
friends.''
   The visit by the 11-member Soviet delegation and a crowd of
Soviet and foreign journalists came in response to a June
``friendship flight'' that took 82 Alaska Eskimos, politicians and
journalists to Provideniya.
   Gov. Steve Cowper had invited the Soviets in July to make the
return visit. The group will be in the state through Friday.
   Members of the group said they hope to improve tourist,
economic, scientific and cultural ties between the two sides of the
Bering Strait. They said theirs was mainly a good-will visit, not
one that would seek official agreements.
   ``We hope that, in any case, there will be direct contacts
within the next year in order to complete tourist trips, postal
exchanges. We're counting on it,'' Vyacheslav Kobets, chairman of
the government council of the Magadan region, said in an interview
aboard the Soviet vessel.
   A reception was scheduled at the city's convention center and
the guests later were to be treated to a reindeer teriyaki luncheon.
   A banner stretched across Nome's Front Street featured the U.S.
and Soviet flags. ``I never thought I'd see the day when the hammer
and sickle would be flying in Nome,'' said Tom Busch of radio
station KNOM.
   The group was scheduled leave later Wednesday for Anchorage,
where plans call for them to visit a shopping mall and have dinner
at an Anchorage hotel. They were to return to Nome on Thursday and
then return to the Soviet Union on Friday.
</TEXT>
