<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1547EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-GWENApproval     09-07 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GWEN Approval,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force OKs Final Phase of `Doomsday' Radio Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force has quietly approved the final
construction phase for a nuclear ``doomsday'' radio network,
concluding that the project can be expanded without harming the
environment.
   The decision to expand the so-called GWEN network of radio relay
towers across the nation was made last month by Air Force Deputy
Assistant Secretary James F. Boatright, said Kevin Gilmartin, a
spokesman for the Air Force Electronic Systems Division at Hanscom
Air Force Base, Mass.
   It followed a review of public comments received since Sept. 25,
1987, when the Air Force published a final environmental impact
statement on the work, Gilmartin said Wednesday.
   Approval of the final construction phase means the GWEN network
ultimately will grow from 56 radio towers linking 38 terminals at
military bases to 96 towers linking 49 terminals, the spokesman
said.
   That represents a reduction from the 126 towers proposed last
fall but will still provide a ``final operational capability,'' he
added.
   GWEN _ an acronym for Ground Wave Emergency Network _ is a
system of low-powered radio antennas and transmitters designed to
ensure adequate communication links for U.S. military forces
following a nuclear attack. The Air Force says the network is
needed to ensure that a president can give a launch order to
Strategic Air Command bombers.
   The service has said it would like to complete the expanded
system by January 1992.
   A typical GWEN station consists of a thin, 300-foot tower and
three small shelters surrounded by a fence. The shelters house
electronic equipment and an emergency generator and fuel. The
stations normally require a 700-square-foot parcel of land.
   Each GWEN antenna is connected to a small grid of copper wire
buried underground at its base and operates with less than 2,000
watts of power.
   The Air Force currently is completing construction of what it
calls the ``thin line'' system of 56 GWEN towers. Fifty of those 56
towers are already operating, receiving and relaying brief test
messages every 20 minutes.
   Some of the towers in the initial system generated public
controversy, with citizen groups in such states as Massachusetts,
Oregon, Pennsylvania and California banding together to fight GWEN
on grounds the towers increased the likelihood of their towns
becoming nuclear targets.
   The Air Force repeatedly dismissed those arguments, asserting
the isolated towers were not worth that type of targeting attention
by the Soviet Union.
   GWEN's construction surfaced anew as a political issue a few
weeks ago when former Defense Secretary James Schlesinger
criticized Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis for
opposing the project.
   Dukakis, the governor of Massachusetts, wrote letters in 1986
and 1987 opposing the placement of GWEN towers in his state both on
environmental and policy grounds.
   Now that Boatwright has certified expansion of the system as
posing ``no significant impact'' to the environment, the Air Force
must perform environment studies for each individual tower site and
award a contract for additional equipment, Gilmartin said.
   The Air Force estimates the entire system will cost roughly $600
million when completed, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1550EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Solidarity-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0592 09-07 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solidarity-Reagan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0592,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solidarity Official Urges Warsaw To Start Talks Soon</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top 18 grafs new to update with White House meeting, fresh
quotes, picks up graf 18th pvs, ``Solidarity is.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity's national spokesman won fresh
support from President Reagan on Wednesday and urged Polish
authorities to make good on their pledge to negotiate with the
banned independent trade union.
   ``Time is running out,'' said Janusz Onyszkiewicz, who has been
the spokesman for Solidarity since 1981.
   ``People are expecting that some kind of compromise, finally,
will be thrashed out and if nothing will indicate this is something
that will happen soon, then people's patience will wear thin,''
Onyszkiewicz said, predicting more labor unrest if the government
doesn't bargain with Solidarity.
   The government, seeking to end a 19-day strike wave that swept
Poland from the Baltic coast in the north to the Silesian coal
fields in the south, last Wednesday held talks with Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa for the first time since releasing him from
martial law internment in November 1982.
   The strikes are over, but in Warsaw government spokesman Jerzy
Urban said that talks would not resume until later this month.
Urban also said they would be called off if any more ``political''
strikes occur and urged workers to join government-sponsored trade
unions rather than try to revive Solidarity.
   Poland's communist authorities proclaimed a state of war against
Solidarity on Dec. 13, 1981, and outlawed the union the following
year. Before last week, the government refused to negotiate with
Walesa and still refuses to allow Solidarity to operate as a legal
union.
   Walesa called Urban's remarks irresponsible.
   Onyszkiewicz warned that ``if the people see that the talks are
just a smokescreen, there will be more unrest in Poland.''
   ``When we ended the last strikes (in August 1980) we had
cast-iron guarantees in writing'' that the government would allow
the creation of independent trade unions. ``This time we don't,''
said Onyszkiewicz.
   ``The only thing that we can say for sure is that there was an
agreement to hold talks on all issues, including unions,'' said
Onyszkiewicz, who is making his first visit to the West in five
years.
   ``But it would be extremely foolish of the Polish government not
to come up with something.'' If not, ``there will be new strikes in
a few months,'' he said.
   If the government negotiates in earnest with Solidarity now, it
can do so without the pressure of nation-wide strikes and protests,
and can reach a reasonable compromise, said Onyszkiewicz, who by
profession is a lecturer in mathematics at Warsaw University.
   ``In two or three months, they will be forced into
concessesions, and they will be viewed as a group that can be
talked to only with a pistol to their heads,'' he said.
   After meeting with Reagan in the Oval Office, Onyszkiewicz told
reporters the U.S. president was committed to maintaining pressure
on the Polish government.
   ``I didn't ask for anything specific, but it is obvious that if
you want to see Poland in a stable condition ... then you must
obviously keep the pressure on the authorities. And President
Reagan said that this pressure will be kept,'' he said.
   Reagan imposed economic sanctions on Poland after the martial
law declaration, and did not lift them until military rule ended
and most political prisoners were released. This year, Poland and
the United States exchanged ambassadors for the first time since
1982.
   The Solidarity spokesman said economic reforms, introduced by
Polish leader Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski to decentralize some
decision-making, will not win popular support unless there are
``deep changes, deep political changes'' in Poland.
   ``Austerity can't be imposed by sheer force. We need not only
economic changes, but political changes in the country, that's why
we need independent institutions. That's why so many Poles think we
need Solidarity,'' said Onyszkiewicz.
   ``Solidarity is a group that is committed against the use of
force. That gives it a moral power and it gives us hope that change
will come in the future and that it will be bloodless,'' he said.
   ``I am optimistic. In the long run, we can't lose. The most
difficult period is still ahead. It is going to be hard,'' he said.
   ``For geopolitical reasons, we must accept the leading role of
the communist party in setting out foreign and defense policy. But
we would like to be allowed to discuss and to help decide domestic
policy issues, such as housing,'' he said.
</TEXT>
