<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Corruption     09-07 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Corruption,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Depicts Soviet Republic as Wracked With Corrupt
Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Wednesday depicted a Soviet
republic at the heart of the trial of Leonid Brezhnev's son-in-law
as plagued by officials who lined their pockets through
influence-peddling.
   Prosecutors on the third day of the trial said the law
enforcement apparatus in the Central Asian republic of Uzbekistan
sold promotions and accepted gifts from officers who paid bribes to
remain on the force.
   One of the defendants, Pyotr Begelman, was accused of taking
$1,600 from officers to help them get off a waiting list for buying
a new car. Soviets sometimes wait years for a car.
   Begelman was quoted in a document read in the Soviet Supreme
Council as saying it was ``well known that to work in the
Uzbekistan police or Interior Ministry, you had to give bribes.''
   ``And where could you get the money if not from subordinates,''
Begelman asked rhetorically.
   The charge sheet read in court Wednesday said Begelman bribed an
official of the Communist Party's policy-making Central Committee
in Uzbekistan to become a deputy interior minister in 1982.
   Begelman laughed sarcastically as a court reporter read some of
the things he is accused of doing.
   Another co-defendant, identified only as Kh. Norbutaev, was
accused in the charge sheet of taking 12,000 rubles ($19,047) from
one witness alone, either in cash or in gifts such as alcohol,
sheep, shoes, fur hats and a Finnish suit.
   Another of the nine defendants stood up in the dock at the start
of the session to complain that investigators were using ``moral
and psychological pressure'' to make him confess in Moscow's
Lefortevo prison, where the accused are being held during a trial
that is expected to last up to eight weeks.
   That defendant, former Uzbek Interior Minister Khaidar Yakhyaev,
slept during some of the afternoon session.
   An attorney for Yakhyaev, 61, said the defendant maintains he is
innocent of all charges. The defendants have not yet been given an
opportunity to enter their pleas pending completion of the reading
of the charges against them. The indictment runs about 1,500 pages.
   On Tuesday, the government finished laying out its case against
Brezhnev's top police official, who was said to have killed himself
following discovery of his extravagant lifestyle financed by
bribery.
   The government charged that Nikolai A. Shchelokov, who served as
interior minister under Brezhnev, took cash bribes as well as
extravagant gifts, including wine and pearls.
   The principal defendant in the case is Yuri M. Churbanov, a
Shchelokov deputy who is married to Brezhnev's daughter, Galina.
Churbanov's wife has not appeared in court. His lawyer told
reporters she is ill but will testify in defense of her husband
later in the trial.
   The trial is seen as a further attempt to discredit Brezhnev,
whose regime is routinely referred to by Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and his top officials as a period of stagnation.
   Western reporters are being allowed to witness the opening days
of the trial and have been told they will also be permitted to
attend for the verdict.
</TEXT>
