<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Polygamists-Charges     09-07 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamists-Charges,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murder Charges Filed Against Three Polygamist Clan Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three polygamist clan members were
charged Wednesday with second-degree murder in the death of a state
corrections officer killed during a shootout that ended the clan's
13-day standoff in a rual compound.
   The charges, filed in 3rd Circuit Court in Summit County, name
clan leader Addam Swapp, his brother Jonathan Swapp, and John
Timothy Singer.
   State attorneys had waited to file charges in the death of
Department of Corrections Lt. Fred House until after the three men
and clan matriarch Vickie Singer had been sentenced last week by a
judge following a federal trial on firearms, attempted murder and
bombing charges.
   Assistant Attorney General Creighton Horton said that barring
new evidence, Mrs. Singer would not be charged in House's death.
   Evidence presented during the federal trial showed the bullet
that killed House was fired by John Timothy Singer, 22, son of Mrs.
Singer, during the shootout at the Singer homestead in Marion on
Jan. 28. The gun battle seriously wounded Addam Swapp, who
triggered the siege when he bombed a nearby Mormon chapel.
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge Bruce Jenkins sentenced Addam
Swapp to 15 years in federal prison. Jonathan Swapp, 21, and John
Timothy Singer were sentenced to 10 years in prison and Mrs.
Singer, 45, was given a five-year term.
   The penalty for second-degree murder is five years to life in
prison.
   Third Circuit Judge Maurice D. Jones ordered that the three be
held without bail, but it was not immediately known if they would
be moved to the Summit County Jail in Coalville or would remain in
the Salt Lake County Jail.
   The complaint was signed by Ronald E. Miller, criminal
investigator for the state attorney general's office. It said the
three men had either killed House, 35, ``or acting under
circumstances evidencing a depraved indifference to human life ...
engaged in conduct which created a grave risk of death to another,
and thereby caused the death of Fred House.''
   The document listed 34 people who witnessed the slaying or
otherwise provided evidence. No arraignment was scheduled.
   The murder complaint said that after the three are tried, they
will be ``returned to the custody of federal officials to begin
serving their prison sentences'' for the federal convictions.
   Swapp said the bombing of the Kamas Stake Center was ordered by
God as a sign of the impending collapse of the Mormon Church and
all government. He also said the act would trigger the return of
family patriarch John Singer, slain by police nine years before for
resisting arrest.
   The clan maintained Singer was killed in a church-state
conspiracy and that the family had been harassed for years by
police and neighbors.
</TEXT>
