<1ST_LINE>u a AM-OrchardFires     09-07 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orchard Fires,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wind Shifts; Firefighters Attack Blaze Threatening Orchard Country</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ENTIAT, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington's orchard belt was spared from a
blistering 30,000-acre forest fire Wednesday by farmers who turned
on their irrigation systems and by a shift in wind and temperature.
   The arrival of cool, humid weather and more favorable winds gave
firefighters the upper hand for the first time in three days.
   ``The plan is for direct attack today,'' said Doreen Medina,
U.S. Forest Service spokeswoman.
   The blaze, believed to be human-caused, grew from about 160
acres Monday. For a time, it had threatened the lush green fruit
orchards that run for miles along the opposite bank of the Entiat
River. The orchards are the backbone of the local economy, and
would take years to replace.
   The Chelan County Sheriff's Department had asked growers along a
five-mile stretch of the river to turn on their sprinklers to keep
the blaze from spreading on the orchard side of the river.
   About 700 firefighters used bulldozers to ring the fire while
dozens of aircraft and helicopters bombed it with water and flame
retardant. An addditional 100 people, including National Guardsmen,
are supporting the firefighters.
   The fire, 50 percent surrounded by fire lines Wednesday, was not
expected to be completely contained before Friday.
   ``We had done a lot of defensive work. Now most of that is
holding and they are taking the resources and putting them on the
(fire) line,'' Medina said. ``We're actually going out and building
line.''
   Smoke from the fire was so thick Tuesday that a 40-mile stretch
of U.S. 97 between Chelan and Wenatchee was closed. The shift in
winds helped officials reopen the highway Wednesday, and dozens who
had evacuated from their homes were allowed to return. One home on
the outskirts of this central Washington town of 400 was destroyed.
   More than 3 million acres of public and private forests in
eastern Washington were closed because of the fire danger, and bans
or restrictions have been levied statewide on hunters, fishermen
and campers.
   The major area of concern was the Entiat fire's west and
northwest side, a critical winter range for one of the state's
largest mule deer herds.
   ``This is the turning point on this fire,'' said Ron DeHart,
spokesman for an interagency task force battling the fire.
   ``Right now we've got it pinned in a corner,'' with the fire
stopped by the Entiat River on the southern flank, Highway 97 on
the eastern flank, DeHart said.
   Elsewhere in Washington, five fires were burning in the
northeast corner of the state. Those have burned 58,000 acres and
were requiring the efforts of 4,000 firefighters.
   Janet Edwards, a spokeswoman for the firefighting effort in the
Colville National Forest, said only one of the fires was still
growing. That one, near Republic, Wash., was at 17,600 acres
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
