<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1945EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Senate-WarPowers     09-07 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senate-War Powers,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Repeal of War Powers Act Urged By Retired Generals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three top retired military officers testified
Wednesday that the War Powers Act should be repealed on grounds
that its restraints on a president's ability to expose U.S. forces
to the risk of combat are unworkable and possibly unconstitutional.
   ``I think the nation would be best served by repealing the
entire act,'' said retired Air Force Gen. David C. Jones, a former
chairman of the military joint chiefs of staff. ``It is a continual
sore in relations betweeen the executive and Congress.''
   Another joint chiefs chairman, retired Army Gen. John W. Vessey
Jr., said he agreed with Jones that ``repeal of the act would be a
good thing.''
   Retired Air Force General Brent Scowcroft, national security
adviser in the Ford administration, also called for repeal,
describing the act as ``well-meaning but deeply flawed.''
   The three retired officers testified before the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, which is examining possible steps to
strengthen the the War Powers Act, enacted over President Nixon's
veto in 1973.
   The act requires the president to notify and consult with
Congress whenever he orders troops into combat conditions, and says
those forces may have to be withdrawn within 60 days unless
Congress approves their continued deployment.
   The hearings were chaired by Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., his first
official act since his recovery from brain surgery earlier this
year.
   Scowcroft said that while the consultations between the
president and Congress called for by the act are a worthwhile goal,
the act does not make clear what is meant by consultations.
   ``How does the president deal with objections to his plans?'' he
asked. ``How can a president deal with confidentiality? What if
Congress is out of session?''
   ``To a layman, it seems that the law most clearly is
unconstitutional,'' he said. ``If being commander in chief has any
meaning at all it must include the ability to move troops.''
   He and the others said Congress can use its power of the purse
as expressed in the appropriations process to force a president to
withdraw U.S. forces.
   ``This act is an invitation to struggle between the two
branches,'' he said. ``We need to increase cooperation between the
two branches, not an attempt by one branch to tie the other down.''
   Vessey said that the way things stand now, the War Powers Act
provides the nation's adversaries with ``an opening to drive a
wedge between president and Congress and the American body
politic.''
   Sen. Brock Adams, D-Wash., said the arguments for repealing the
act amount to a declaration that it is ``better to let the pot boil
until there is an explosion between the Congress and the president
or between the people and the president, rather than go ahead with
an orderly procedure under the War Powers Act.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Carlucci     09-07 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Carlucci,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Satisfied With Chinese Statements On Arms Deals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said
Wednesday he is satisfied with China's assertions that its growing
arms trade will not contribute to instability in the Middle East
and other volatile regions.
   He told reporters two days of talks were the ``best discussions
we have ever had'' on the question, he was ``fully usatisfied''
with the Chinese explanation and ``I hope we can put this issue
behind us.''
   The United States ``will continue to work to expand the
technology that is being made available to China,'' Carlucci said,
adding without elaboration that new technology exchange programs
are being discussed in aviation and other fields.
   Boeing is negotiating the sale to China of about a dozen CH-47
transport helicopters for use by a rapid deployment force. The
United States has supplied China with helicopters, technology for
fighter jets, torpedoes and other ammunition.
   Carlucci met on Wednesday with 84-year-old Deng Xiaoping,
China's leader and head of the Central Military Commission.
   He conferred Tuesday with Defense Minister Qin Jiwei, Premier Li
Peng and Vice Premier Wu Xueqian.
   Among matters discussed were U.S.-Soviet arms reduction talks,
the Soviet military withdrawal from Afghanistan, the situations in
Cambodia and Korea, modernization of China's armed forces and
Chinese domestic policy.
   The Chinese ``clearly attach great importance'' to their own
satellite launching service, which could suffer serious losses if
Washington does not issue export licenses for U.S. communications
satellites, Carlucci told reporters.
   Defense Department officials said the issue was raised by all
the Chinese leaders Carlucci met on Tuesday, and urged the Reagan
administration to approve launching of U.S. satellites by China.
   ``I indicated that from my perspective I did not see this as a
national security issue,'' the defense secretary said. ``They have
given us all the assurances we need on the safeguarding of the
technology. It is not a technology transfer issue. It is a trade
issue.''
   The Commerce Department and some U.S. congressmen have argued
that launching American satellites with the Chinese Long March
rocket would undermine efforts by U.S. companies to establish
commercial launching services.
   Carlucci also was asked about a statement by Deng Xiaoping that
he hoped Vice President George Bush would win the presidential
election.
   Bush headed the U.S. liaison office in Beijing in 1974-75,
before full diplomatic relations were established, and has met Deng
and other Chinese leaders in frequent visits to China since then.
   ``I gave him (Deng) about a billion absentee ballots,'' Carlucci
said jokingly.
   Deng generally receives only visiting presidents and premiers.
His meeting with Carlucci underscored the importance with which
China views overall relations and military links with the United
States.
   Military ties have developed since diplomatic relations were
established in 1979. Exchanges of senior military officials are
common, the United States sells a small amount of military hardware
to China and U.S. warships made a port call in 1986 at the Yellow
Sea port of Qingdao.
</TEXT>
