<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignAds     09-07 0597</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Duakakis Ad Says Choice is Clear, But Bush Ad says He's The
Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential campaign ads began this week on
an upbeat note, with Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican George
Bush promoting themselves as candidates of compassion in two
high-stakes states.
   ``Who cares about your life?'' a narrator asks at the end of a
Dukakis ad keyed to a plant-closing bill that became law over the
objections of the Reagan administration.
   The spot, running in Texas, concludes, ``The choice is clear.''
   Or is it?
   ``I want a kinder and gentler nation,'' Bush says at the outset
of a 30-second spot running in California, in an excerpt from his
convention acceptance speech. ``I'm a quiet man, but I hear the
quiet people others don't. ... I hear them and I am moved.''
   The convention footage is intercut with an array of domestic
scenes _ Bush cooking corn in a big pot, Bush biting into a
sandwich at a picnic, Bush lifting a grandchild into the air and
kissing her.
   The Dukakis plant-closing spot shows a padlocked plant gate as a
narrator asks, ``Shouldn't there be a law to give you and your
community 60 days' notice? George Bush says no and Dan Quayle led
the fight in the Senate against making it a law.''
   The ad says Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis passed one of the first
notification laws in the country and touts Texas Sen. Lloyd
Bentsen, Dukakis' running mate, as ``the man who won the fight to
make 60-day notification law.'' The two are shown in their
shirtsleeves, chatting genially with a group of workers at a plant.
   The Dukakis campaign bought network time starting Wednesday for
an ad called ``New Era,'' which first aired in a very limited
fashion during the Republican convention last month. The ad, the
first paid national exposure for Dukakis, features excerpts from
his acceptance speech and a list of his accomplishments.
   A second Bush ad, also running in California, uses another chunk
of Bush's acceptance speech intercut with shots of the White House
lit up at night, a flag waving in the background.
   ``What it all comes down to in this election is the man at the
desk and who should sit at that desk,'' Bush says in the speech
excerpt. ``My friends, I am that man.''
   The Dukakis campaign and the Democratic National Committee
unveiled one negative ad scheduled to start airing late this week.
The ad, produced for the DNC, takes the Reagan administration to
task for the tripling of the federal debt since 1980.
   The ad, called ``Hey Pal,'' features printed text describing the
climb of the debt from $900 billion in 1980 to $1.8 trillion in
1985 to $2.6 trillion in 1988. The text is intercut with a laughing
actor depicting a Republican.
   ``Hey pal,'' he says, ``how about a couple hundred billion? I'll
pay you right back. ... What's another trillion between friends?''
The ad concludes with these words on the screen: ``We can't afford
the Republicans.''
   ``Sorry, pal,'' the narrator says.
   Campaign spokesman Leslie Dach said the ad ``very clearly states
what the record is in this administration on the national debt.''
He said it would air in battleground states, but declined to reveal
which ones.
   A group called Americans for Bush, not associated with the Bush
campaign, has prepared two ads slamming Dukakis' record on crime
and plans to show them on several national cable networks. The ads
were to be unveiled at a news conference Thursday.
</TEXT>
