<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CruiseSanitation     09-07 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cruise Sanitation,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Detailed Cruise Ship Sanitation Reports Proposed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national Centers for Disease Control plans more
rigorous sanitary inspections of cruise ships and new health
scorecards that will help the public judge a ship's history, a CDC
official said Wednesday.
   Dr. Vernon N. Houk, director of the CDC's Center for
Environmental Health and Injury Control, said the center plans to
hire additional inspectors and set up an improved inspection
routine of the cruise ships.
   Houk said the proposed new reporting procedures would replace
pass-fail designations with a numeral rating and include a median
score of all inspections from the previous five years.
   ``A single inspection score does not accurately predict the
possibility of an epidemic on a particular cruise,'' said Houk.
``However, an epidemic is significantly less likely to occur on a
vessel whose staff maintains a higher level of sanitation over a
period of time.''
   He added, ``Scores over a five-year period would provide the
traveling public with more information than is now available.''
   Meanwhile, outbreaks of germ-related illnesses has remained
stable on passenger vessels although more ships are docking at U.S.
ports.
   Cruise ship voyages from the U.S. have nearly doubled from the
mid-1970s to about 3,500 trips yearly, but Houk said the number of
gastric diseases since 1980 has remained steady at about two cases
per 10 million passenger-days. That figure represents the total
number of days at sea.
   Since the CDC resumed unannounced cruise ship inspections in
March 1987, five outbreaks affecting about 22,000 passengers have
been investigated.
   The CDC spot inspection program, halted in 1985, was refunded by
Congress after limited cooperation from cruise ship lines using
private inspectors.
   Only about 30 percent of 78 cruise ships inspected by the CDC
since March 1987 achieved scores above 85, the minimum passing
mark, on first inspection. However, all but five ships passed on
reinspection, according to CDC figures.
   The inspections include checking water, food preparation and
storage and general cleanliness, said the bi-weekly CDC cruise ship
report summary distributed to travel agents and cruise ship
operators.
   Houk said at a public meeting here Wednesday that the numeral
reporting system could be implemented early next year if approved
by federal officials. There is no fine or other penalty for cruise
ships failing CDC inspections, but the lines could suffer losses if
tour operators direct clients to other vessels or the public learns
of the low score.
   ``Reputation is invaluable in the cruise ship industry,'' said
John Layzell, a vice president at Miami-based Admiral Cruise, one
of 22 lines operating out of U.S. ports. ``If the traveling public
reads about an unsatisfactory score in their Sunday travel
sections, then they might just change their minds.''
   James Mitchell Jr., a travel agent from Hanover, N.H., who
attended the conference, said the CDC reports will not have full
impact until they are circulated among most of the 30,000 tour
brokers around the country.
   ``Right now, at best, 3 percent of the travel agents get the
reports,'' he said. ``Most agents don't even know these reports
exists.''
</TEXT>
