<2ND_LINE>AM-Fruit Outlook,110</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fruit Production Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smaller crops of some fruit will mean fewer
cans on grocers' shelves in the coming year, the Agriculture
Department said Wednesday.
   The department's Economic Research Service said those crops
include apricots, clingstone peaches, bartlett pears and apples.
Moreover, it said in a new outlook report, smaller inventories
already on hand ``will keep most canned fruit supplies tight again
this season.''
   Demand from both domestic and export markets has been relatively
strong, the report said.
   ``Several canned fruit prices have advanced recently because of
strong movement, tight supplies and higher contract prices for raw
fruit,'' the report added. ``Prices are expected to remain strong
throughout 1988-89.''
