<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     09-07 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Union Opposes Restoration Of Solidarity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief of Poland's official trade union
said Wednesday that talks with Solidarity expected to begin this
month will address union pluralism, but appeared to rule out
legalizing the banned group.
   ``If there are different trends afoot, let us find a proper
solution: join (the official) union, take part in the elections,''
said Alfred Miodowicz, head of the All-Poland Alliance of Trade
Unions and a member of the Communist Party Politburo.
   Miodowicz, speaking at a news conference at the trade federation
headquarters in Warsaw, did not rule out a meeting with Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa before the talks begin.
   Howevever, he said:
   ``The legalization of Solidarity as another trade union would be
inconsistent with our concept, which says there is one trade union
in an enterprise.''
   Last week Walesa persuaded workers to end strikes. In exchange,
he received a pledge from Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak
of negotiations whose topics would include legalizing Solidarity,
the first independent trade union movement in the Soviet bloc.
   The strikes began Aug. 16 at the July Manifesto coal mine in
southern Poland by workers who demanded higher pay and legalization
of Solidarity.
   Miodowicz told reporters that current worker dissatisfaction
resulted from poor implementation of economic reforms by the
government.
   In a speech to the Communist Party's Central Committee on Aug.
28, Miodowicz said government leaders should be held personally
acccountable for the economic problems that touched off the strikes.
   On Tuesday, the official union formally called for the
government of prime minister Zbigniew Messner to resign. It asked
for a no-confidence vote at the next meeting of Parliament,
expected sometime this month.
</TEXT>
