<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mideast 1stLd-Writethru   09-07 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast, 1st Ld-Writethru,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Asks Egyptian, Israeli Foreign Ministers to Meet in NY</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 9-12 new with Israeli reaction in Jerusalem; final two
grafs new with Israeli speech in Washington.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has invited the foreign
ministers of Egypt and Israel to a mini-summit meeting in New York
on Sept. 26 to try to give new impetus to lagging Mideast peace
efforts, U.S. and diplomatic sources said Wednesday.
   Initially, Secretary of State George P. Shultz planned to meet
with Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and Egyptian Foreign
Minister Ahmed Esmat Abdel Meguid while all were attending the
special session of the U.N. General Assembly.
   Reagan decided to step in to demonstrate that U.S. interest in
promoting a settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict had not flagged
despite a lack of progress in recent months and elections to be
held in the United States and Israel in November. Shultz also will
participate.
   ``They want to show the initiative is still alive,'' said a
diplomatic source who, like the others, demanded anonymity. A U.S.
official said Reagan wanted to ``put his weight'' behind the U.S.
proposal for a Mideast peace conference and see whether the 1979
peace treaty Egypt signed with Israel can be expanded further into
the Arab world.
   The president's invitation was conveyed Tuesday to a senior
Israeli embassy official who readily accepted in behalf of his
government. Shultz called in Egyptian Ambassador Abdel Rauf
El-Reedy on Wednesday to outline the U.S. initiative.
   While Reagan is in New York he also will address the U.N.
session.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman declined to say
whether Reagan would meet with the foreign ministers. ``A lot of
meetings are possible in New York, but I'm not at a point where I
can confirm those at this point,'' he told reporters.
   Peres, head of the Labor Party, has supported Shultz's efforts
this year to convene a Mideast peace conference. But Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir, head of the Likud coalition, has resisted, partly
because the administration proposes that Israel yield most of the
West Bank and Gaza in exchange for Arab recognition.
   Shamir's Likud associates suggested in Jerusalem that the Reagan
administration was meddling in Israeli affairs by setting up a
meeting just five weeks before Israel's election. The Nov. 1
balloting is viewed as a referendum on Israel's Mideast policy.
   ``At this hour, I still don't have all the details on the
meeting,'' the prime minister said. ``I will just say one thing. We
must not forget that we are on the eve of elections.''
   Uri Oren, political adviser to Deputy Prime Minister David Levy
of Likud called the meeting ``a bad joke'' and ``astonishing
evidence of improper policy, both external and internal.''
   ``Everybody understands that such a meeting cannot advance any
political process several weeks'' before the elections, he told an
Associated Press reporter in Jerusalem.
   Jordan's King Hussein has insisted on a guaranteed Israeli
withdrawal as a condition for attending peace talks. Shamir
rejected the proposition during a trip by Shultz to the region last
spring and Hussein subsequently said he would no longer try to
intercede on behalf of the Palestinian Arabs who live in the
territories Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967
Mideast war.
   The U.S. blueprint for peace envisaged Jordan resuming its
control of West Bank territory, which it held from 1948 to 1967,
while Shamir favors self-rule but not statehood for the 1.4 million
Palestinians in the West Bank and Gaza.
   There is no place in the administration's plan for a separate
Palestinian state.
   Reagan's predecessor, Jimmy Carter, engineered the
Israeli-Egyptian peace treaty by holding a summit at Camp David,
Md., in 1978 with former Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin and
the late Egyptian President Anwar Sadat.
   A meeting in New York would give Israel another opportunity to
step up its relations with Egypt under the treaty. President Hosni
Mubarak has resisted, however, until the settlement can be
broadened to include Palestinians.
   Meanwhile, Yehoshafat Harkabi, a former chief os Israeli
military intelligence, on Wednesday called on his government to
negotiate with the Palestine Liberation Organization for the
creation of a Palestinian state on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   In a Washington speech, Harkabi, who now teaches, writes and
lectures, called the PL0 ``the enemy'' and an ``ugly''
organization. But, he said, Israel must recognize ``there either
will be a Palestinian state as our neighbor or Israel will be the
Palestinian state.''
</TEXT>
