<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TelevisonTimber     09-07 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Televison Timber,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Probation For Chopping Down Neighbor's Tree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDD EVERHART</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DANBURY, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who chopped down a neighbor's
stately oak tree to improve reception on his television satellite
dish was placed on two years' probation Wednesday and ordered to
stay off the tree owner's property.
   Superior Court Judge Thomas G. West granted the request by
Arthur Anderson, 59, of Redding for accelerated rehabilitation, a
form of probation, on charges stemming from the felling of the
83-year-old oak.
   In his decision, the judge didn't address tree owner Charles
Marriner's request that Anderson's satellite dish be taken away
from him during the probationary period.
   ``He's going to be able to enjoy the fruits of his crime,''
Marriner, 62, also of Redding, told the court.
   Anderson's lawyer, Jeffrey B. Sienkiewicz, told West that his
client is ``very regretful about this entire incident.''
   ``I don't believe that Mr. Anderson knew that the tree was on
Mr. Marriner's property,'' Sienkiewicz said.
   Marriner said, however, that Anderson had to go over a stone
wall and a fence to get to the tree, which was about 170 feet from
the Marriner home.
   Police said it was the second time Anderson was caught on
Marriner's property. They said he cut down a tulip tree there in
May 1987 and was warned then against trespassing.
   West said he was not ordering Anderson to make restitution
because that issue is pending in a civil suit Marriner has filed.
He seeks $37,000 in compensation for the two trees.
   Anderson, a construction worker, cut down the tree June 12,
police said. He told police that he and his wife are ``television
addicts'' and said, ``Now I can get the Disney Channel.''
   Under the accelerated rehabilitation program, available only to
first-time offenders, if the defendant completes probation
successfully, the charges are erased from his record.
</TEXT>
