<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-American-SovietSpace     09-07 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American-Soviet Space,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Experts Praise Soviet Handling Of Space Emergency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American experts say the Soviets handled
Tuesday's crisis on their Soyuz spacecraft with a sophistication
and confidence that comes from years of successful missions.
   Nicholas Johnson, a U.S. authority on Soviet space, said despite
the drama of two men caught in a malfunctioning space capsule, the
situation was much less serious than problems the Soviets
encountered on earlier flights.
   ``The Soviets have had major anomalies about every four years
since 1967,'' said Johnson, who works for Teledyne Brown
Engineering in Colorado Springs, Colo., a major space contractor.
   ``These are situations which are potentially life threatening
and this one was probably the most modest of all of them,'' he said.
   The Soviets lost one cosmonaut in 1967, three in 1971. In 1975
there was an in-flight launch abort during a prelude to the joint
U.S.-Soviet mission in which an Apollo spacecraft linked up with a
Soyuz in space. And in 1983, there was a launch abort when the
rocket caught fire on its pad and the cosmonauts had to be pulled
off with an emergency system.
   Donald K. Slayton, who was one of the three astronauts aboard
Apollo in the joint mission, said the fact the Soviets passed up an
opportunity to land safely but off target on Tuesday shows there
was no panic or severe emergency.
   ``If they had had a serious problem of running out of
expendables (oxygen) they would have gotten it down somewhere,''
Slayton said. ``That tells you they had it under control.''
   Marcia Smith, the Soviet-space expert at the Library of
Congress, said the successful landing ``was a feather in their cap,
especially for ground controllers who sorted out what the problem
was and sorted out the fix for it.''
   The experts acknowledged they need a great deal more information
before passing final judgments but Slayton said the way in which
the Soviets handled the problem shows they certainly are more
sophisticated now than they were in 1975.
   ``The've got a lot more epxerience now than they did then and
it's probably simpler for them now,'' he said. Slayton, one of the
original seven American astronauts, is vice president of Space
Services Inc., a private launch company in Houston.
   Miss Smith said she does not know whether the Soyuz problem was
with an infra-red sensor that determines the position of the
spacecraft by taking readings of the Earth's horizon or with the
ship's computer.
   ``There is some indication now there was a misprogramming of the
computer,'' she said.
   Being marooned in space has been a concern of all space
travelers since humans first went into orbit. Slayton said this
concern was reflected in the design of the Mercury spacecraft,
America's first manned orbiting vehicle. He said the one-man craft
had three solid retro rockets, any one of which could have brought
the astronauts to Earth, ``somewhere.''
   The Soyuz had two engines: the main one can be shut down and
restarted, while the backup can be fired only once.
   ``I'm interested in what engine they fired,'' said Miss Smith.
She called the backup ``the last shot to get them home.''
   Johnson said the Soviets were just as candid with the public
about their problem nine years ago when Soyuz-33 malfunctioned with
a Soviet and a Bulgarian aboard and had to abandon its plans to
dock with a space station.
   ``We didn't hear all the details after the 33 incident, but they
told us there was a malfunction in the main engine,'' he said.
``The waited 24 hours and used the backup engine to get back.''
   By coincidence, he pointed out, one of the cosmonauts on the
space station was Vladimir Lyakhov, the commander of the Soyuz that
got in trouble on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
