<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia     09-07 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Blow Up Key Oil Pipeline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas blew up Colombia's
main oil pipeline, and fierce fighting is driving hundreds of
peasants out a southern state, the Defense Ministry said Wednesday.
   President Virgilio Barco offered Sept. 1 to negotiate peace with
Colombia's six guerrilla groups, but there has been no answer from
the insurgents.
   One of the guerrilla groups, the National Liberation Army, blew
up the Canon Limon oil pipeline on Tuesday, the Defense Ministry
said in a news release.
   Guerrillas have attacked oil pipelines 46 times this year.
   Canon Limon is an oil field in northwest Colombia with 1 billion
barrels of reserve petroleum, discovered four years ago by the
Occidental Petrolum Co.
   The pipeline, which pumps 225,000 barrels of oil a day, will be
shut down at least until Saturday for repairs, the state oil
company Ecopetrol said in a news release.
   The 500-mile pipeline takes oil from Canon Limon, in the state
of Arauca, to the Caribbean port of Covenas.
   Ecopetrol has estimated that guerrilla attacks on oil
installations have cost Colombia $300 million this year.
   Meanwhile, the Defense Ministry communique said heavy fighting
is going on between guerrillas and the army in the southern state
of Tolima. Hundreds of peasants are fleeing the area, the statement
said.
   It said nothing about casualties in the battle with elements of
the leftist Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces.
</TEXT>
