<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reagan-Ambassador,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Select Californian As Top Envoy To India</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate John
Randolph Hubbard of California to be ambassador to India,
succeeding John Gunther Dean, the White House announced Wednesday.
   Hubbard, 69, began his career with the Interstate Commerce
Commission where he served as private secretary to the commissioner
from 1939-41.
   He served in the U.S. Navy from 1941-46, then became a teaching
fellow at the University of Texas. Later, he was dean and associate
professor of British and European history from 1953-58 and dean and
professor of British and European history from 1965-69.
   From 1965-69, Hubbard was chief education adviser at the U.S.
Agency for International Development mission in New Delhi, India,
and since 1969 has served at the University of Southern California
as academic vice president, provost and professor of history and
also has been co-chairman of the Indo-U.S. Subcommission on
Education and Culture.
