<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Israel     09-07 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Source: Israeli Flier Now Held By Iranian-Backed Militants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem faction
is holding an Israeli soldier who was captured two years ago when
his plane was shot down in south Lebanon, a Shiite source said
Wednesday.
   The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Israeli
airman, Ron Arad, ``is now under the control of the Faithful
Resistance Movement,'' a faction based in the Bekaa Valley that
broke away from Justice Minister Nabih Berri's mainstream Shiite
Amal militia early this year.
   The movement is headed by Mustafa Dirani, Amal's former security
chief who was dismissed Feb. 26 on charges of trying to create an
Iranian-controlled wing within the Syrian-backed militia.
   Amal had officially claimed it was holding Arad, 30, the
navigator of an Israeli F-4 Phantom jet downed in south Lebanon
Oct. 16, 1986. But an Amal spokesman, who also refused to be
identified, said ``the Israeli airman is not under our control.''
He declined to elaborate.
   According to the Shiite source, Amal ``lost control'' of Arad
when it fired Dirani, who established his headquarters in the Bekaa
in east Lebanon.
   The source added: ``The Israeli airman has been held by Dirani
all the time and he still holds him.''
   Last Friday, the Israeli army said it was working for Arad's
release and holds Amal responsible for his safety.
   ``Israel stresses and reiterates it considers the Amal
organization, and its leader (Berri), responsible for the health
and safety of the navigator and hopes all necessary steps will be
taken in keeping with this responsibility,'' an Israeli army
statement said.
   Arad's F-4 was shot down by Palestinian guerrillas using a
shoulder-fired Sa-7 missile to defend against an Israeli bombing
raid in south Lebanon. The pilot was rescued by an Israeli
helicopter, but Arad was captured by Shiites.
   Five other Israelis are missing in Lebanon.
   Two soldiers captured in February 1986 are believed held by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God. Three others were
reported missing after a tank battle with the Syrian army in the
Bekaa.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in the Bekaa, north Lebanon and west and south Beirut.
   In another development, police said two Soviet-designed Katyusha
rockets hit a house in the town of Hasbaya on Wednesday in Israel's
self-designated border ``security zone'' in south Lebanon,
``wounding a number of civilians.''
   Although the police statement did not say who fired the rockets,
Moslem guerrillas regularly attack the Israeli zone.
   The Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army, a mainly Christian
militia, retaliated at 11 a.m. by shelling the village of Kfir,
north of the security zone, with tank fire, polices said.
   The barrage damaged the village's elementary school and eight
houses. Two schoolchildren were wounded, police reported.
   Israel set up the 6-to-10-mile-wide security zone to curb
cross-border raids when it withdrew the bulk of its army from south
Lebanon in 1985.
</TEXT>
