<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MoscowEmbassy     09-07 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moscow Embassy,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Private Study Recommends Dismantling U.S. Embassy in Moscow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private engineering study of the bug-riddled
new U.S. Embassy in Moscow finds that the structure cannot be
salvaged and recommends it be dismantled and rebuilt, says a House
member involved in the issue.
   This time, the engineers told the State Department, only
American labor and materials should be used, there should be better
security on the construction site and the building should be
pre-constructed in the United States as much as possible.
   Rep. Olympia Snowe, R-Maine, said the report by BDM Corp.
supported the conclusion she had reached following a tour of the
site more than a year ago, soon after it was discovered that the
building was suffused with a sophisticated Soviet eavesdropping
system.
   One earlier study, by former Defense Secretary James R.
Schlesinger, had concluded the eight-story building could be
partially salvaged by removing and rebuilding the top three floors
for use in unclassified embassy work and called for building a new
annex for top-secret activities.
   ``The administration should move quickly to begin tearing down
the new building this fall so that they take advantage of the warm
season,'' Snowe said in a statement. She said some $38 million
remains available in the construction account that could be used
for the dismantling.
   The structure should be taken apart carefully, she said, rather
than demolished, so that building components can be shipped back to
the United States for further study by intelligence experts, who
still haven't fully figured out the technology used in the Soviet
bugging system.
   BDM, which studied the embassy problems at the State
Department's request, concluded that complete dismantling and
reconstruction would cost $160 million and take 45 months to
complete, Snowe said. There is no way the new structure can be
modified to make it secure, she said.
   Abandoning the new project and trying to rehabilitate the
current outmoded embassy building would cost $170 million and take
80 months, leaving the project susceptible to security problems for
a longer time and increasing the likelihood of inflationary cost
increases, the firm concluded.
   The Reagan administration has not yet decided what to do about
the embassy building, which has already cost nearly $60 million in
construction costs and studies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bases     09-07 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bases,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Offers Philippines Nearly Half-Billion In Aid To Retain Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has offered the Philippines
$489 million in aid this year in an effort to extend American use
of two major military bases for two years, congressional sources
said Wednesday.
   The offer includes a doubling of the yearly fee for using Subic
Bay Naval Base and Clark Air Base from $180 million to $360 million.
   But the Philippines government is asking for a more sizable
increase _ to more than $1 billion in aid overall.
   The negotiations on renewing the base agreement, whose terms
expire in 1991, are in suspension at least until Foreign Minister
Raul Manglapus meets here next week with State Department officials
and key members of Congress, said the sources, who spoke only on
condition of anonymity.
   This year's military and economic aid to the Philippines totals
$463 million. The Reagan administration is seeking congressional
approval of $289 million for next year, in addition to food aid,
which this year amounts to $62 million.
   Although negotiations over the U.S. bases in the Philippines and
also in Greece have broken down, the State Department on Tuesday
voiced confidence the talks would be resumed and settlements
reached.
   Both allies benefit from the presence of U.S. military forces on
their territory, spokesman Charles E. Redman said. He said the
talks with the Philippines would be reopened on a ``mutually
convenient date'' and the negotiations with Greece had been
suspended temporarily.
   Redman said Ambassador Nicholas Platt had returned to Washington
from Manila for ``long-planned consultations'' and that further
discussions probably would be held when Manglapus, chief negotiator
for the Philippines, is here next week.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz is scheduled to meet with
Manglapus on Sept. 30, during the special session of the U.N.
General Assembly in New York.
   The Philippines, a former U.S. colony, have had strong ties with
Washington since their partnership against Japan in World War II.
Since Corazon Aquino took over as president in 1986, U.S. military
and economic aid has totaled $1.3 billion.
   The Subic Bay and Clark bases are among the most important U.S.
military bases overseas.
</TEXT>
