<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Accutane     09-07 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Accutane,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Announces Steps To Prevent Use Of Acne Drug During
Pregnancy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The maker of the anti-acne medicine Accutane
announced a federally sanctioned program Wednesday aimed at
preventing the drug's use during pregnancy, a practice that studies
show can cause birth defects.
   The drug, sold by Hoffmann-La Roche Inc. since 1982, has been
identified by the company as a factor in at least 70 cases of birth
defects. And U.S. Food and Drug Administration spokeswoman Faye
Peterson said incidents of deformities caused by the drug ``are
notoriously underreported.''
   Donald D. Hollander, president of the the Nutley-based company's
Roche Dermatologics division, said the manufacturer will begin
requiring physicians prescribing Accutane to obtain a signature on
a patient consent form advising of the drug's risks.
   Womens' health groups and some professional associations have
long sought such a procedure for Accutane. Hollander said such
consent forms are unprecedented for a drug already approved by the
federal government.
   ``In essense, the message we wish to communicate is simple,''
Hollander said. ``Accutane should not be prescribed or taken if
pregnancy cannot be excluded during therapy.''
   Hollander said Hoffmann-La Roche was taking another highly
unusual initiative in offering to pay for women using Accutane to
receive an initial pregnancy test and birth-control evaluation it
recommends.
   The company also promised to distribute pregnancy information
kits, offer a pregnancy counseling referral service and make major
changes in the way it packages the drug to include health warnings.
   The offer to reimburse doctors for pregnancy testing and birth
control exams ``is strictly a company initiative,'' but the other
moves announced at a New York news conference essentially amount to
an adoption of guidelines written in April by an FDA advisory
committee, said Ms. Peterson.
   ``We recommended these steps in order to curb overprescription
of the drug, which should really be used as a last resort for
people with severe, recalcitrant acne when other methods of control
have failed,'' Ms. Peterson said.
   At the April meeting, the federal committee rejected calls to
pull the drug off the market, noting that it is the only effective
treatment for a severe, disfiguring form of acne.
   She said the FDA expected to complete evaluation of Hoffmann-La
Roche's new packaging proposal within two months.
   Dr. William Cunningham, company assistant vice president and
director of medical affairs, said the proposal calls for the drug
to be packaged in 10-tablet, individually wrapped envelopes, a
change from the 100-tablet bottles previously marketed.
   Cunningham said the packets, which will be covered with warnings
against use of the drug during pregnancy, will help prevent overuse
of the drug.
   Reaction to the company's announcement from medical and womens'
groups was enthusiastic.
   Cindy Pearson, program director of the National Women's Health
Network in Washington, said the use of patient consent forms would
ensure that doctors and patients discuss the risks before the drug
is taken.
   William Heineke, spokesman for the American Academy of
Dermatology, said the group favors the use of all other alternative
treatments for severe acne before resorting to Accutane.
   ``A female using Accutane should employ effective methods of
contraception, should have a negative pregnancy test two weeks
prior to using the drug, at least once a month during use and a
month after completion of treatment,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
