<DOCNO> AP880907-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CottonPesticide     09-07 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cotton Pesticide,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cotton Pesticide To Be Recalled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The two sellers of chlordimeform, a pesticide
used on an eighth of the nation's cotton crop, have agreed to quit
marketing the product and will recall leftovers from farmers after
the current growing season, the Environmental Protection Agency
said Wednesday.
   The agency said it would make the distribution or use of the
chemical, a suspected cancer agent, illegal after Feb. 19. The
product has been used to destroy the eggs and larvae of the tobacco
budworm and the cotton bollworm.
   Pesticide recalls are rare, and a spokesman for one of the
companies, Ciba-Geigy Corp., said in Grensboro, N.C. he could
recall none that took products back from farmers.
   Recalls will begin in four or five weeks, after use for the
current growing season is over, said the spokesman, Steve Powell.
Farmers will receive refunds for unused amounts and reimbursement
for any shipping expenses.
   ``It's our hope'' that little will be left over, he said.
   The other licensed seller is Nor-Am Chemical Co. of Wilmington,
Del. Powell said he did not know whether Nor-Am bought its product
from Ciba-Geigy or manufactured its own. At Nor-Am, spokesmen who
could discuss chlordimeform had gone for the day.
   Ciba-Geigy has sold chlordimeform under the trade name Galecron
and Nor-Am sold it under the name Fundal. About a million pounds
annually had been used in recent years.
   In 1985 and 1986, EPA said it intended to undertake a special
study of chlordimeform because of evidence that it caused tumors in
laboratory animals.
   In February, the companies proposed to stop sales and give back
their licenses, and this proposal, now accepted by EPA, means that
the special study will not be started.
   Use on food crops was stopped in the 1970s after cancer in lab
animals began to appear, and usage restrictions were tightened. EPA
said it did not believe there was any significant dietary risk from
chlordimeform, but it intends to revoke the regulations permitting
a small residue on treated food.
   Although there appear ``significant risks for applicators
exposed over a lifetime, the available data do not support'' an
immediate emergency ban on use, EPA said.
   One of the breakdown products of chlordimeform, a chemical
called 5-CAT, appears to cause the tumors observed in lab animals,
said Karem Ahmed of the consulting firm of Environ Corp., who
studied chlordimeform while at the Natural Resources Defense
Council.
   The chemical 5-CAT is also used as a raw material in the
dyestuffs industry in Germany and one group of dye workers studied
there showed higher than normal incidence of bladder cancer,
according to Ahmed. This chemical is no longer used in the United
States, and EPA said it would treat it as a new chemical requiring
an EPA safety review if any company wants to re-introduce it.
   Some workers in the leather and other industries who use
dimethylformamide, a starting chemical for one method of mking
chlordimeform, have developed excessive testicular cancer.
   EPA said it was consulting the Centers for Disease Control and
the Association of State and Territorial Health Officers, as well
as the companies, on whether and how workers should be notified of
possible effects of exposure to chlordimeform and related chemicals.
   Powell said the company had told its own production workers
about chlordimeform's effects, but he did not know what might be
required for notices to farm workers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
