<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EltonJohn     09-07 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Elton John,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elton John Sale Tops $6 Million After Two Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The running total for the auction of rock star
Elton John's castoff possessions soared to $6.2 million Wednesday
with two days left to go.
   ``It is as much as we had expected all four days of the sale to
fetch,'' said Philippe Garner of Sotheby's auction house, who
catalogued and ran the second day's sale of rare art nouveau and
art deco glass, furniture and statuettes.
   Sotheby's said the 500 lots fetched $4.2 million, bringing the
total for the first two days to $6.2 million.
   John said earlier he is selling off items from his mansion near
Windsor, west of London, because he has no more room and wants to
collect other things.
   In contrast to the opening day, when John's fantastic
eyeglasses, costumes, platform boots, rock music memorabilia and
personal jewelry drew crowds of pop fans, American and European art
dealers were out in force Wednesday.
   ``But there were still a lot of strangers and new buyers and a
lot of them were in very trendy clothes,'' said Fiona James, a
Sotheby's publicist.
   Because of the connection with the pianist-singer-composer, the
art objects went for well above estimates. Glass vases by Frenchman
Emile Galle and lamps by Charles Louis Tiffany of New York went for
three times the expected prices.
   An unidentified American buyer paid the top price of the day,
$152,400, nearly double the top estimate, for a sofa and four
chairs with upholstery designed about 1925 by French artist Raoul
Dufy.
   The Macklowe Gallery of New York paid $152,400 for three leaded
glass table lamps and Seibu, the Japanese department store which
bought several lots of jewelry Tuesday, paid $115,200 for a lamp
and a 1920s bronze and ivory figure of a woman.
</TEXT>
