<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-07 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gibraltar-IRA,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioner: Police Couldn't Cope With IRA Agents, Asked Army
Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The police commissioner testified at a
coroner's inquest Wednesday that he asked the British army to help
seize IRA agents because of fears a car bomb might explode and
police couldn't handle with the situation.
   The three unarmed IRA agents were shot and killed by British
soldiers on March 6, raising strong criticism of the government of
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and spurring charges that
the deaths were part of an unofficial ``shoot-to-kill'' policy
against the IRA.
   The Thatcher government denied the charges. Observers from the
human rights organization Amnesty International and from Ireland
are attending the inquest.
   Hearings began Tuesday in the deaths of Mairead Farrell, 31,
Daniel McCann, 30, and Sean Savage, 24, who the Irish Republican
Army said were IRA members in active service when they were killed
in the British fortress colony.
   The inquest has no power of prosecution, but the Gibraltar
attorney general is expected to return criminal indictments if it
rules the killings unlawful.
   Gibraltar Police Commissioner Joseph Canepa told Coroner Felix
Pizzarello and his jury that he was informed March 4 that the three
IRA members had been sighted in Malaga, Spain, about 75 miles
northeast of Gibraltar.
   Police in Gibraltar then set up observation posts at strategic
locations on the rock, near Spain's southernmost tip.
   At 12:30 p.m. on March 6, McCann and Farrell were identified by
police as the two entered Gibraltar from Spain on foot, Canepa said.
   They went to the Gibraltar Assembly area where they met Savage,
who earlier parked a white Renault in the neighborhood.
   Canepa said arrests were almost made at that stage. At 3:25
p.m., the three moved north toward Gibraltar's border with Spain.
   ``I asked the soldier to examine the car (Renault) and he
reported that in his view the car contained a bomb,'' Canepa
testified. ``I felt the police couldn't cope with the situation and
so I requested the military help.''
   The soldier Canepa refered to was one of seven military people
believed to have been from Britain's elite Special Air Service unit.
   It was then, Canepa said, that he signed a form asking the
military to intercept and apprehend the three suspects.
   ``I formed the view that we should arrest on suspicion of
conspiracy to murder,'' Canepa testified.
   Minutes later, he received a report that the three IRA activists
had been shot dead as they walked toward the border, Canepa said.
   Canepa said it was later determined there was no bomb in the
Renault.
   Two days later, however, Spanish police located a car rented by
the three IRA agents in a parking garage in Marbella, Spain, a city
about halfway between Gibraltar and Malaga. They said it contained
140 pounds of explosives and a timing device.
   Another witness, a senior British security officer identified
only as `O' for security reasons, told the court the intelligence
service failed to foresee these developments before the shootings:
   _That the three IRA members would cross into Gibraltar from
Spain unarmed two days before a suspected bombing attempt.
   _That the three would first drive an empty car in from Spain to
block a space near the suspected bombing target.
   _And that they would use a timing device rather than remote
control to detonate the bomb.
   `O' testified while concealed from the public by a curtain
around the witness stand.
   Belfast lawyer Patrick McGrory, representing the families of
those killed, tried to show in cross-examining `O' that British
intelligence did not have enough evidence to justify killing the
three rather than simply arresting them.
</TEXT>
