<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-IRA,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Suspects Linked To Belgian Shooting, Other Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gibraltar-IRA</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criminal investigators said
Wednesday they believe two suspected IRA men arrested in West
Germany were involved in at least four bombings and shootings on
the Continent aimed at British forces.
   They said they had evidence the two were involved in an Aug. 12
attack in Belgium that killed a British soldier.
   ``According to our investigations so far, we have found links
between attacks against British forces in the Netherlands, West
Germany and Belgium,'' said Alexander Prechtel, a spokesman for the
federal prosecutor's office.
   The men, identified as Gerard Thomas Hanratty, 29, and Terence
Gerard McGeough, 30, were heavily armed when they were arrested in
West Germany on Aug. 30 after they crossed the Dutch border. Police
found two Kalashnikov AK-47 automatic rifles and three .38-caliber
pistols in their car.
   Prechtel said weapons tests indicated that one of the pistols
was used in the fatal shooting in Ostend, Belgium, of a British
soldier.
   The IRA claimed responsibility for the attack.
   On July 13, a bomb attack on a British barracks in Duisburg,
West Germany, injured nine soldiers. On May 1, a shooting attack
killed one member of Brtain's Royal Air Force and wounded two in
Roermond, the Netherlands.
   Two soldiers were injured in the bombing of a British barrack in
Duesseldorf, West Germany, on Aug. 5.
   Authorities believe others were involved and the prosecutor's
office has offered a $27,000 reward for information leading to
their capture.
   The mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting to
end British rule in Protestant-ruled Northern Ireland and unite it
with the 95-percent Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
