<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Amnesty     09-07 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Amnesty,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Proposes Amnesty For Participants In 1956 Uprising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on proposed a general
amnesty Wednesday for people who were imprisoned for taking part in
the 1956 uprising, Budapest radio reported.
   Government spokesman Gyoergy Marosan also was quoted as saying
changes were needed in a decade-old joint project with
Czechoslovakia to build dams and power plants on the Danube River.
He gave no details.
   The amnesty program means ``1956 cases'' will be erased from
individual files and criminal records, allowing those cleared to
have passports and travel abroad, Marosan said. The proposal is to
be presented to the presidential council for formal approval within
a month.
   The 1956 uprising began Oct. 23 with mass demonstrations for a
new government and demands that Soviet troops leave Hungary. On
Nov. 4, 200,000 Soviet soldiers and 2,500 tanks entered Budapest to
crush the revolt.
   How many people would be affected by the amnesty program was not
known immediately.
   A source in Budapest, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
changes int the power project were decided upon after the
government received 30 studies by official agencies and scientific
institutions, nine of them critical.
   The Czechoslovak-Hungarian project began 10 years ago. It has
has been criticized by environmentalists in Hungary and Austria,
who say it would destroy drinking water reserves, wetlands and
wildlife.
   At an international symposium on the project in Budapest last
weekend, independent experts called for a halt in construction on
the Hungarian side and for a referendum to decide whether the
project should be completed.
   According to the broadcast, Marosan said the government
discussed the project and decided the best solution was to get on
with construction after the unspecified ``partial modifications''
are made.
   On the basis of scientific opinion available to it, the
government will submit a report to Parliament when it meets Oct. 5.
An Academy of Sciences committee will be fornmed to deal with the
necessary changes, the broadcast said, but the government will not
propose a referendum.
</TEXT>
