<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan-Warplane     09-07 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan-Warplane,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pakistan Downs Afghan Warplane</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED AFTAB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistani fighter jets shot down an
Afghan warplane 12 miles inside Pakistan on Wednesday and Afghan
air raids hit three mountain villages within this country,
authorities said.
   The U.S. government on Wednesday protested Afghan raids in
Pakistan, which serves as a base for guerrillas fighting the
Soviet-backed Afghan government.
   A Defense Ministry spokesman said several Afghan aircraft
intruded into Pakistani territory but were spotted by a two-plane
Pakistan air force patrol which fired on the intruders.
   He said one Afghan jet was shot down over Nawagai, 120 miles
northwest of Islamabad, but did not say what happened to the pilot.
   The spokesman refused to say what type of plane was involved,
but sources said it may have been a MiG-23. All spoke on condition
of anonymity,
   The spokesman said that when intercepted by the Pakistani
aircraft, the Afghan warplanes turned back toward their country.
Some dropped their extra fuel tanks and bombs, which fell over the
villages of Bandagai and Guro, close to Nawagai. Four people were
injured and two cows were killed, he said.
   In a separate incident, three people were injured when Afghan
aircraft dropped 10 bombs on the villages of Shago Khas, Girokhawar
and Dauda Pahar, 20 miles inside Pakistan, a police spokesman said.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said in Washington
that warplanes from Afghanistan have repeatedly raided Pakistani
territory.
   ``We again condemn it and view with grave concern these
successive violations of the Geneva accord and international law,''
he said.
   Wednesday's downing was the fourth Afghan-Soviet aircraft lost
over Pakistan since U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas began fighting
the Marxist government in Afghanistan in 1978.
</TEXT>
