<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Explosion     09-07 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Explosion,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Kills Man Outside South African Shopping Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded Wednesday at a
shopping center entrance in an exclusive white suburb of
Johannesburg, killing a black man and shattering windows.
   The man's body was torn asunder outside the main entrance of the
North Park Plaza in suburban Northcliff.
   No one else was hurt.
   Police did not identify the type of bomb or say whether the man
was carrying it when it went off at 7:25 p.m..
   Security at shopping centers, restaurants and other public
places in South Africa was increased recently after the public
demanded more thorough searches of people and parcels.
   On Tuesday night, government-run television broadcast a special
program on bombs, with a reporter displaying the most common types
used in South Africa and showing how he could hide two under his
coat.
   Wednesday's bombing was the second in three weeks at a shopping
center in an affluent white suburb and followed a declaration
earlier this year by guerrilla leaders of the outlawed African
National Congress that they would take their fight to the white
neighborhoods.
   The government usually blames such bombings on the ANC. The
group seldom comments on such incidents, although it has said it is
conducting a campaign of sabotage aimed at ending the apartheid
system of racial separation and white dominance of the government
and economy.
   Seventeen people have been killed and nearly 200 injured in
nearly 40 bombings in South Africa this year.
   More than 100 explosions have caused 31 deaths and about 565
injuries since the government declared a national state of
emergency on June 12, 1986. Police were given wide powers to detain
people without charge, restrict the press, prohibit certain
statements and almost all forms of public protest.
   Office buildings occupied by anti-apartheid organizations have
also been bombed and grenades have been planted or thrown at the
houses of government opponents.
   The latest occurred Aug. 31 when an explosion shattered Khotso
House, a building housing the South African Council of Churches and
other prominent groups.
</TEXT>
