<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Army, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0723,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Under Investigation in Draft-Dodger Scandal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 3rd graf pvs, Some Israelis ...
UPDATING with suspect released. Picks up 4th graf pvs, The scandal
...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17th suspect was arrested Wednesday and
Israel radio said a general was suspected of involvement in the
sale of exemptions from military service, a scandal that has
tainted the nearly sacrosanct army.
   The latest suspect is a Tel Aviv eye, nose and ear specialist
who allegedly sold false medical certificates. Israel radio said
the doctor, Gideon Bialistock, was a Dutch citizen who has lived in
Israel on a tourist visa for 20 years.
   Some Israelis have paid up to $10,000 for exemptions from
compulsory military service.
   Later Wednesday, authorities released a lieutenant colonel, one
of 16 suspects taken into custody Monday, Israel Television said.
It did not elaborate.
   The scandal came to light Monday when military and civilian
police arrested 16 Israelis, including high-ranking officers and
doctors, after a six-month undercover investigation.
   Foreign Minister Shimon Peres praised the army's response. ``I
appreciate the fact that the army reacted immediately, publicly,
and didn't cover up anything,'' he said on Israel radio. Peres is a
former defense minister.
   Army officials said they would review the procedures for
granting exemptions.
   The scandal has angered Israelis who consider the army a sacred
institution and inspired scathing editorials in many newspapers.
   ``The uncovering of an entire network ... whose beneficiaries
may have run into the hundreds poses a new problem for the army,''
the Jerusalem Post said. It cautioned against ``crying havoc'' but
recommended ``greater vigilance'' in the future.
   Members of the ring allegedly arranged exemptions from draft or
reserve duty for hundreds of people by providing false medical
certificates or tampering with army computers.
   Two army majors are the key suspects, Israel radio said
Wednesday _ one who had access to army computers and another who
headed the manpower division's medical committee.
   It said a brigadier general was suspected of involvement in the
scheme but had not yet been arrested.
   Army officials said further arrests were expected.
   ``This is just the tip of the iceberg,'' said Col. Renaan
Gissin, a deputy army spokesman. ``The last word has not been
said.''
   He described the number of people involved as unprecedented.
   Jewish men and women are drafted at age 18 in Israel, whose
population is 4.1 million. Men serve for three years, followed by
62 days of reserve duty each year until age 55. Women serve two
years, with no obligatory reserve duty.
   Avoiding service is a social taboo and many employers ask
applicants to prove they did army service.
   Israel has virtually no conscientious objectors and fewer than
300 people have refused to serve in controversial operations in
Lebanon or the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip during the last
decade.
</TEXT>
