<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BriberyTrial     09-07 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bribery Trial,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former State Official Pleads Guilty To Misdemeanor In Potato
Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former state administrator pleaded
guilty Wednesday to a misdemeanor charge and avoided going on trial
for bribery in connection with a 2-year-old scandal over a failed
potato sale to Honduras.
   Laurence McMerty, the state Agriculture Department's former
marketing director, pleaded guilty to unlawful compensation for
assistance in a government matter, a charge punishable by up to one
year in jail and a $1,000 fine.
   McMerty, 43, was accused of accepting a Caribbean cruise and up
to $4,000 in cash from a Miami agent, William Messner, who acted as
a middleman in the potato deal.
   Prosecutors dropped felony bribery charges in exchange for the
guilty plea, in which McMerty admitted accepting $3,200 in cash,
which he claims was reimbursement for expenses.
   Jury selection had started in state district court Wednesday
morning for McMerty's trial on the bribery charges. If convicted,
he faced up to 10 years in prison.
   ``I am confident and comfortable justice has been served,''
Deputy Attorney General Bruce Quick said after McMerty entered the
plea Wednesday.
   Messner pleaded guilty July 8 to bribery as part of a plea
agreement that requires him to pay $60,888 in restitution to the
state. Messner, who also was placed on probation, was in jail for
six months prior to the plea.
   McMerty claimed Wednesday's guilty plea exonerated him of any
serious wrongdoing in connection with the potato scandal, which
already had tarnished the career of state Agriculture Commissioner
Kent Jones.
   ``There is no implication of bribery. There is no implication I
did anything to harm the state in any way,'' McMerty said in a
telephone interview from his home.
   McMerty acknowledged Wednesday that he received $3,200 from
Messner's company, Petrolear Holdings Ltd., but he said he believed
he was entitled to the money as reimbursement for expenses he
incurred in 1985 while trying to set up the potato sale.
   McMerty claimed that costs were built into the eventual potato
sale so he could be reimbursed for the 1985 trip to Central
America. McMerty has maintained that he reimbursed Messner for the
cruise, which was not involved in the misdemeanor charge to which
he pleaded guilty Wednesday.
   The state offered McMerty basically the same plea agreement last
November, Quick said.
   No date for McMerty's sentencing was set.
   The potato sale soured in August 1986 after the financial
arrangements came to the attention of Attorney General Nicholas
Spaeth.
   Messner secured from the state $1.85 million in notes that
Spaeth says were issued without authority by Jones and former Bank
of North Dakota President Herbert Thorndal. Messner returned a
$1.55 million note after Spaeth disclosed the deal but he had
already discounted and sold a $300,000 note.
   The state is still owed $104,000 for 400,000 pounds of seed
potatoes that were shipped to Honduras before the deal fell through.
</TEXT>
