<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ExecutiveDiscrimination     09-07 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Executive Discrimination,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds No Discrimination In Executive Suites</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A study of business graduates has found no
evidence of widespread discrimination against Jews in the executive
suite, and says their pay actually increased faster than that of
Christians.
   The study, released Wednesday by the American Jewish Committee,
tracked the careers of 444 men and women who received master of
business administration degrees in 1974 or 1979 from Harvard
University, Columbia University or Drexel University.
   The study found:
   _Five to 10 years after starting out as junior executives, 83
percent of the Jews held administrative positions, compared with 69
percent of Protestants and 53 percent of Catholics.
   _Jews had average salaries of about $111,000, compared with
$83,000 for Protestants and $82,000 for Catholics, partly because
Jews tended more often to go into commerce rather than
manufacturing and service, where salaries tend to be lower. Between
the time of their graduation and the time of the survey, Jews had
average annual raises roughly double those of Christians, the
survey said.
   _Nearly two-thirds of the Jewish MBAs identified Christians as
their corporate mentors.
   The study found that half the Jewish MBAs could not read Hebrew
letters, and ``ritual observance, on the average, did not extend
much beyond attendance at a (Passover) Seder and lighting candles
on Hanukkah. At the same time, a majority participated in Christmas
observances, with a not-insignificant number having Christmas trees
in their homes.''
   The coordinator of the project, Murray Friedman, director of the
committee's Middle Atlantic States region and acting chairman of
the U.S. Civil Rights Commission, said however that that despite
Jewish gains in recent years, ``discrimination has not disappeared,
nor are all businesses and economic sectors fully open to Jews.''
   Friedman said in Philadelphia, for example, some business areas
``employ Jews at the higher levels mainly in specialized areas like
public relations and law.''
   ``Sudden shifts in the American economy or the political climate
could reverse the gains that have been made,'' he added.
</TEXT>
