<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QALQILYA, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops blockaded
Qalqilya for a second day Wednesday, turning the town zoo into an
army base, and helicopters circled overhead searching olive groves
for Palestinian stone-throwers.
   Also Wednesday, three Palestinians, including two 16-year-olds,
were wounded in stone-throwing confrontations with troops near the
West Bank town of Nablus, about 12 miles east of Qalqilya, hospital
officials said.
   Except for dozens of soldiers patrolling the streets, Qalqilya
was a virtual ghost town one day after the army swept in and
arrested more than 150 Arabs as part of a new tactic to quell the
9-month-old Palestinian rebellion.
   By Wednesday night, more than 200 Qalqilya residents were in
custody, Israel radio said. It said without elaborating that the
detainees included members of several gangs that had hurled
firebombs at Israeli cars.
   ``We have no illusions this measure will stop rock throwing and
firebombing,'' Col. Ranaan Gissin told reporters during an escorted
tour of Qalqilya. ``This measure ... is to send a deterrent message
to the people.''
   Gissin, the army's deputy spokesman, said the town, where troops
have cut telephone lines and blocked all entrances, would remain
under curfew for at least several more days.
   The town and surrounding areas also under curfew are home to
about 35,000 Palestinians.
   On Wednesday, Israeli settlers who live in the area were
permitted to drive through Qalqilya's deserted streets to their
homes.
   During a two-hour tour of Qalqilya, reporters saw two
Palestinians, handcuffed and blindfolded, being transported by jeep
to interrogation in makeshift army bases set up at a local high
school and the town zoo.
   Dozens of troops, some wearing shielded helmets and others
carrying clubs and automatic weapons, patrolled the narrow streets
on foot and in jeeps.
   Several Arabs complained that during house-to-house searches for
suspected rioters the army broke into homes and damaged property.
One Palestinian man pointed to a broken lock and smashed windows in
his home.
   Some residents watched troops from their windows and rooftops. A
small child was seen flying a kite from a rooftop, and remnants of
other kites hung from electrical wires.
   An elderly Arab man emerged on another rooftop where he yelled
at troops, claiming they were calling Arabs profane names.
   ``Is this what you learned in the army? You should be ashamed of
yourself,'' the man, who was surrounded by several children,
shouted in Hebrew.
   On the street below, one soldier was heard saying to another:
``We'll deal with this guy later.''
   Many of the Palestinians arrested belonged to the outlawed PLO
youth group, Shabiba, the army said. It said they were suspected of
throwing stones and firebombs at Israeli cars, or participating in
riots.
   ``The chopper overhead is to locate Palestinian squads who have
escaped into the orchards,'' Gissin said. ``When we see them, we
pick them up.''
   Besides uncovering caches of knives and axes, troops also found
a workshop for making nail-studded iron pieces, called ``ninjas,''
for puncturing the tires of passing cars.
   Gissin said Qalqilya, 1.5 miles from Tel Aviv's northern
suburbs, became a particular problem because hundreds of vehicles
from nearby Jewish settlements and Israeli cities pass through the
town everyday.
   Qalqilya is one of the largest West Bank towns near Tel Aviv.
One soldier accompanying the tour pointed to a hilltop in the town
from where he said Jordanian troops fired the only shell to hit Tel
Aviv during the 1967 Middle East War.
   Also Wednesday, police said a 25-year-old West Bank Palestinian
confessed to last month's killing of an 18-year-old Israeli woman,
Ziva Goldovsky.
   The suspect, a friend of the victim, said he killed her for
nationalist motives after Ms. Goldovsky refused to give him a
pistol, police investigator Uri Weisskoop told Israel radio.
   She was the fifth Israeli to die in the Palestinian uprising,
which has claimed the lives of at least 259 Palestinians.
   Troops lifted a 13-day curfew from the West Bank village of Bani
Naim, near Bethlehem. During the closure, Arab residents said
troops confiscated about 150 cars in an effort to force
Palestinians to pay their taxes.
   Underground leaflets have called on Arabs to refrain from paying
taxes to the Israeli military government.
</TEXT>
