<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TeacherStrikeRdp     09-07 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher Strike Rdp,0685</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teacher Walkouts Affect Schools In Five States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Teacher strikes in six states disrupted classes for 110,000
students Wednesday, but schools in Louisiana and Michigan reopened
when teachers reached agreement on contracts.
   Many of the teachers on strike in 26 public school districts in
Michigan, Pennsylvania, Massachusetts, New Jersey, Illinois and
Ohio were holding out for raises.
   ``We are doing this because we are the lowest paid teachers in
the whole area and we have been for many years,'' said Lowell,
Mass., teacher Coe Kevghas as he picketed in front of the Rogers
School Wednesday. ``We don't want to strike but we are forced to
strike. Veteran teachers earn less than rookie police and firemen.
Why?''
   A settlement was signed Tuesday night in southwest Louisiana's
Vermilion Parish after officials agreed to collective bargaining
with the Vermilion Association of Educators representing 600
teachers, cafeteria workers and school bus drivers. The teachers
had been on strike for three weeks.
   ``We're very happy. We're going back to school and I think we'll
have a better educational system,'' association President Betty
Girouard said.
   In Michigan, teachers in Fenton ended their one-day strike,
pending ratification of a three-year contract. Terms were
unavailable. Teachers returned to classrooms in the 2,800-student
district.
   Elsewhere in the state, walkouts continued in at least nine
public school districts.
   Strikes continued Wednesday in Garden City, Napolean, Michigan
Center, Holland, Manistee, Baraga, Stockbridge, Pontiac and West
Ottawa school districts.
   More than 1,400 professors and academic staff members at Wayne
State University in Detroit went on strike Tuesday over union work
rules and salary.
   About 950 clerical workers and secretaries represented by the
United Auto Workers have been on strike there since Aug. 25.
   In Peabody, Mass., school officials canceled Friday classes. The
city's 408 teachers on Tuesday rejected a 17 percent wage increase
over three years, holding out for 42 percent.
   ``To sit at the table locked in at 42 percent is totally
irresponsible,'' said Mayor Peter Torigian.
   Bert Latessa of the Massachusetts Federation of Teachers
defended the union's position. The 42 percent wage request, Latessa
said, is smaller than it appears because the teachers maintain they
have been performing extra duties such as handling oversized
classes without extra pay.
   Elsewhere in the state, Lowell's 970 teachers voted unanimously
Tuesday to stay off the job because of dissatisfaction with a
proposed salary package. The first day of school Wednesday was
canceled for the city's 13,100 students.
   Teachers are seeking higher pay and longevity bonuses.
   Teacher strikes are illegal in Massachusetts, and the state
Labor Relations Commission on Wednesday declared Peabody's strike
illegal and ordered teachers back to work. The move was a
relatively routine step designed to set the contract negotiation
process in motion.
   Around Massachusetts, teachers in 35 communities were still
without contracts Wednesday as classes began.
   Sixty substitutes replaced striking teachers in Blue Ridge,
Ill., allowing schools to open, while negotiators in Granite City
headed for the bargaining table in the state's only other teachers'
strike.
   Granite City's 444 teachers walked off their jobs Tuesday,
idling 8,200 students in the district's 12 schools. School started
Aug. 25. Teachers voted last Thursday to reject the board's offer
of a 4 percent pay raise. The union has asked for a two-year
contract with salary increases of 10 percent this year and 10
percent next year, Superintendent Gilbert Walmsley said.
   Here is a brief summary of teacher strikes elsewhere:
   New Jersey: A union representing about 130 teachers, custodians
and clerks at Eastern Regional High School in Voorhees postponed
the first day of school by striking Wednesday after nearly 12 hours
of talks broke down, officials said. The school has 1,450 students.
   Pennsylvania: Strikes by about 2,750 teachers canceled classes
or disrupted teacher preparation days in 10 districts with 43,800
students.
   Ohio: Contract talks involving 357 teachers and support
personnel at five Cleveland schools serving 1,250 handicapped
students will resume at the end of the week, school and union
officials said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
