<1ST_LINE>u a AM-America'sCup 1stLd-Writethru a0715 09-07 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-America's Cup, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0715,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America's Cup Race Finally Gets Under Way</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GOX7</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `The heavily ... to UPDATE with race winner;
INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf, ``I'm not ... to UPDATE with
smaller crowd turnout; picks up 8th graf: `Overcast skies ...;
version moving on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sailing became the No. 1 spectator sport in San
Diego on Wednesday as the America's Cup got under way and
enthusiasts tried to grab the best viewing spots on land and sea.
   Sailors aboard aircraft carriers and waterfront restaurant
patrons peered through binoculars as the American catamaran Stars &
Stripes and the massive yacht New Zealand moved through San Diego
Bay toward the race starting line.
   The heavily favored U.S. boat, skippered by Dennis Conner, took
an early lead in the first race of the best-of-three series. Stars
& Stripes went on to defeat New Zealand by a margin of 18 minutes,
15 seconds, covering the 40-mile course in 4 hours, 53.54 seconds.
   The next two races are scheduled for Friday and, if needed,
Sunday.
   Conner was the skipper of the yacht that won the America's Cup
back from Australia last year, after losing it to the Aussies in
1983.
   A crowd gathered on a grassy embankment at Embarcadero Marina
Park, site of the America's Cup tourist village, to watch the race
proceedings live on a stadium-sized video screen positioned on a
barge just offshore.
   ``It's going to be fun once we get our Kiwi beer,'' said Chris
Hammonds, 26, of Cambridge, New Zealand, who is on the first leg of
a three-year, round-the-world trip.
   ``I'm not a big sailing fan, but a proud Kiwi (New Zealander),
and we want to make our presence felt,'' he said.
   America's Cup Village organizers had said that the compound
would accomodate up to 70,000 people, but police estimates
indicated only about 3,000 turned out for the start of the first
race, said Officer Ken Winklepleck.
   ``I think there'd have been a larger crowd here if it was a
multinational race with everyone sailing similar boats,'' said Mike
Malcom, 28, of Atlanta. ``But it's still very exciting.''
   Overcast skies cleared to brilliant blue as Stars & Stripes and
the New Zealand began the race at noon Wednesday, after months of
legal skirmishes and harsh words between the competitors.
   Through court action, New Zealand had forced San Diego into an
early defense of the Cup, upsetting San Diego Yacht Club plans for
a multinational event in 1991. San Diego responded by choosing to
sail a catamaran, a first in the Cup's 137-year-old history.
   High-spirited race buffs on spectator boats ranging from tugs to
large yachts cheered and waved at landlubbers as they headed out to
a marked viewing area several miles offshore.
   One boat speeding out of the bay created swells that sent
another craft, which was to carry reporters along the race course,
crashing against a cement dock. The media boat was damaged but no
one was injured.
   ``Get that boat's name!'' a man shouted as the craft sped on.
   Banners, balloons and flags flew from the spectator boats, but
the best decoration was provided by nature: A school of dolphins
leapt skyward as they passed by the American catamaran a few hours
before race start.
   At the America's Cup Village, souvenir vendors were busy selling
T-shirts, pins and other memorabilia. Video monitors stationed
throughout provided race information and features on the two
competitors.
   ``I almost cried when I saw our boat (New Zealand) sail out to
the starting point,'' said Carol MacLeod, 25, of Auckland. ``It was
so big and graceful. It looked good in the water.''
   Fans of the Stars & Stripes cheered loudly as Conner and his
crew waved from their 60-foot catamaran as they made their way to
the starting point, four miles off Point Loma.
   ``This is a great birthday present,'' said Mike Cordell of San
Diego, who turned 33 on Wednesday. An America's Cup fan since 1974,
Cordell said the race would be exciting despite the politics
surrounding it.
   But one disgruntled New Zealander said the contest between the
catamaran and yacht, considered lopsided by sailing experts because
of the cat's speed advantage, reflected poorly on the Americans.
   ``The Stars & Stripes are making the Kiwis look stupid in front
of the Americans, but they're making themselves look like fools in
front of the rest of the world,'' said Tracy Barclay, 23, of
Cambridge, New Zealand.
</TEXT>
