<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TropicalWeather 2ndLd-Writethru a0757 09-07 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tropical Weather, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0757,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Florence Forms in Gulf</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with new position, eastward drift, name of
earlier hurricane; no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Florence formed off Mexico's Yucatan
Peninsula Wednesday and began drifting eastward in the southern
Gulf of Mexico but posed no immediate threat to land, hurricane
forecasters said.
   An Air Force reconnaissance plane measured Florence's top winds
at 55 mph at 7:30 p.m. EDT as the storm swirled over warm Gulf
waters. It was located about 100 miles north of Merida, Mexico,
near latitude 22.6 north and longitude 89.6 west, said the National
Hurricane Center.
   The plane crew reported near-hurricane force squalls near the
storm's center.
   ``Florence could reach hurricane strength within the next 24 to
36 hours,'' forecaster Bob Sheets said in an advisory.
   September and early October are the height of the hurricane
season.
   ``At this time of the year, a hurricane is always a
possibility,'' forecaster Noel Risynchok said. Air Force
reconnaissance planes will check the storm regularly, he said.
   Forecasters said steering currents around the storm remained
weak Wednesday evening, and they had no idea where the storm might
head once it strengthens.
   ``It's out in the open waters of the gulf right now,'' Risynchok
said. ``The only current threat would be to marine interests.''
   Florence is the sixth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic Hurricane
season. Only Debby, which struck Mexico's Gulf Coast, had wind
strengthen to more than 74 mph, making it a hurricane.
</TEXT>
