<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-PLO     09-07 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-PLO,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PLO Chiefs To Meet On Provisional Palestine State Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior PLO official said Wednesday the
group's executive panel will meet this week prior to a conference
whose main topic is creation of a provisional government for an
indepandent Palestinian state.
   Yasser Abed-Rabbo, a member of the Palestine Liberation
Organization's executive committee, said the meeting Saturday in
Tunis will consider proposals to be placed before an emergency
session of the Palestine National Council, the Palestinians'
parliament-in-exile.
   A planned mid-September meeting by the council was postponed
while PLO leaders sought international recognition for a
provisional Palestinian government. Sources say the council
probably will meet next month in Algiers.
   Support for the PLO to proclaim a provisional government has
increased since Palestinians in the Israel-held West Bank and Gaza
Strip began their uprising Dec. 8. More than 280 Palestinians and
five Israelis have died.
   The continuing protests against Israeli rule have bolstered the
PLO's flagging fortunes, with many figures within the PLO urging
declaration of an independent state in the occupied territories.
   Jordan's King Hussein decided July 31 to sever Amman's legal and
administrative links with the West Bank, adding to the pressure on
the PLO by challenging it to assume responsibility for the occupied
region and live up to its claim to be the Palestinians' sole
representative.
   A top Arafat lieutenant, Salah Khalaf, was quoted by Kuwait's
Al-Anbaa daily Wednesday as calling on the PLO to take the
``historic ... realistic political decision'' of declaring an
independent state soon.
   ``We have no option but to take a key step that responds to the
dictates of the Palestinian uprising and its continuation, Jordan's
legal and administrative disassociation with the West Bank and the
international detente which envisages solutions to regional
problems,'' he said.
   Israeli officials have refused to deal with the PLO, calling it
a terrorist organization. Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has also
vowed to wreck PLO plans for a provisional government or a
Palestinian state.
   The United States also refuses to deal with the PLO until it
accepts U.N. Security Council Resolution 242, which implies
recognition for Israel's right to exist.
   Abed-Rabbo said he expected the national council to issue a
``policy declaration which ... would be based on international
legality, beginning with (U.N. Security Council) Resolution 181 and
ending with 242.''
   Resolution 181 established the state of Israel, but also called
for a Palestinian state.
   Israel has already annexed part of the Arab land captured from
Jordan and Egypt in 1967 where the PLO hopes to create its state.
Israeli critics have also complained that the 1948 partition
resolution calls for giving up part of pre-1967 Israel as well.
</TEXT>
