<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-US     09-07 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-US,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Suggests That Washington Is Meddling In Israeli Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir suggested
Wednesday that Washington is meddling in Israeli affairs by
inviting Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, his political rival, to a
Mideast peace summit one month before Israel's election.
   Israeli Foreign Ministry officials confirmed that President
Reagan will act as host at a meeting between Peres and Foreign
Minister Esmat Abdel Meguid of Egypt to discuss the peace process.
   U.S. and diplomatic sources in Washington said the meeting will
take place Sept. 26 in New York. Israel's general election will be
held Nov. 1, and voters in the United States go to the polls on
Nov. 8.
   Both Shamir's right-wing Likud bloc and Peres' left-of-center
Labor Party have billed the voting as a historic referendum on how
to solve the Arab-Israeli conflict and deal with the 9-month-old
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Labor backs the U.S. Middle East peace plan, which calls for the
return of land for peace and negotiations in the framework of an
international peace conference. Likud opposes key elements of the
U.S. plan, ruling out the return of occupied lands and favoring
direct talks on limited Palestinian autonomy.
   Reacting to the news of Reagan's move, Shamir said: ``At this
hour, I still don't have all the details on the meeting. I will
just say one thing. We must not forget that we are on the eve of
elections.''
   Senior Likud officials went further in their criticism.
   ``This is a bad joke,'' said Uri Oren, political adviser to
Deputy Prime Minister David Levy of Likud. ``It is astonishing
evidence of improper policy, both external and internal.''
   ``Everybody understands that such a meeting cannot advance any
political process several weeks'' before the election, he told The
Associated Press.
   Likud officials also accused Peres of acting behind Shamir's
back by not informing the prime minister of the invitation which
was conveyed to senior Israeli officials in Washington on Tuesday.
   But Peres said he only found out about the proposed meeting from
journalists on Wednesday. ``I'm surprised by this. I didn't know
about it,'' he told Israel radio in an interview.
   Peres welcomed the new U.S. initiative and rejected charges that
it was aimed at boosting Labor, which is slightly trailing Likud
and its potential coalition partners in the latest polls.
   ``I don't see a reason that just because we are on the eve of
elections, we have to stop working for the advancement of the peace
process,'' Peres said.
   Peres is scheduled to leave for New York on Sept. 22 to attend
the annual session of the U.N. General Assembly. During the visit,
he said he would meet with foreign ministers of nations playing a
role in the Middle East conflict.
   Secretary of State George Shultz sought support for the U.S.
peace plan during four shuttles to the region this year, but failed
to win backing from most regional leaders. Egypt was the only Arab
state to endorse the plan.
</TEXT>
