<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YonkersDeseg     09-07 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yonkers Deseg,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Doomsday' Plan Put In Effect As City Faces $1 Million-A-Day Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city of Yonkers, which faces $1
million-a-day fines starting Friday, will begin laying off hundreds
of employees as part of a ``doomsday plan'' to delay bankruptcy,
state officials said Wednesday.
   The fines stem from the City Council's refusal to approve a
housing desegregation plan ordered by a federal judge.
   Under the spending-reduction plan approved by the state
Emergency Financial Control Board, the city Parks Department and
public library will shut down Saturday; the Planning Department
will virtually close, with just two employees staying on; and $3.7
million in employee fringe benefits will be cut.
   A total of $20 million will be saved under this phase of the
plan, said Secretary of State Gail S. Shaffer, the chairman of the
control board. The layoffs of 447 employees Saturday also will come
from the departments of real estate, civil service, fiscal services
and public works.
   Other belt-tightening measures will kick in over the next few
months if needed, allowing the city to continue to operate until at
least next year, Shaffer said.
   ``The thrust of this plan is to preserve the most important
services as long as possible,'' Shaffer said. ``We're making some
fairly painful choices, but the accelerated cuts will stretch out
police, fire and public safety services.''
   The control board ruling infuriated City Councilman Edward
Fagan, one of four council members who have blocked approval of the
desegregation plan.
   ``It eliminates people we would need. ... There's no concern in
terms of employees' rights,'' Fagan said after storming out of the
meeting.
   U.S. District Judge Leonard Sand ruled in 1985 the city had
segregated housing and education for 40 years. The city's schools
were desegregated under a plan approved by Sand, and the City
Council agreed in January to develop 1,000 units of low- and
moderate-income housing designed to promote integration.
   But Fagan and Councilmen Peter Chema, Henry Spallone and
Nicholas Longo voted Aug. 1 to block the second portion of the
plan. In response, Sand levied escalating fines against the city _
$100 for the first day and doubling every day after that.
   Sand also imposed personal fines against the four councilmen and
threatened them with jail.
   The penalties were stayed pending appeal. Last week, the U.S.
Supreme Court reinstated the fines against the city, with a cap of
$1 million a day. The court upheld the stay of the councilmen's
punishment.
   City officials have said the fines would bankrupt the city by
Thanksgiving. Gov. Mario Cuomo said Wednesday that as long as the
U.S. Supreme Court was considering the case, he would not begin
proceedings to remove the four councilmen.
   Spallone, appearing Wednesday on the syndicated ``Donahue'' TV
show, suggested the city might refuse to pay its fines.
   ``I'm going to have to vote on the transfer of funds to pay the
fines. And I'm saying this publicly, I'm not voting for it,''
Spallone said. ``I'll never surrender the vote of the people.''
   The City Council was scheduled to meet Thursday to vote again on
Sand's order.
</TEXT>
