<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Congo-Angola     09-07 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congo-Angola,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angola, South Africa Resume Talks Amid Reports More Cubans Sent To
Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRAZZAVILLE, Congo (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan-South African peace talks
resumed Wednesday with South Africa stopping just short of accusing
Angola of violating a month-old cease-fire. At issue are claims
Cuba sent 10,000 more soldiers to Angola, bringing its force to
60,000.
   South African President P.W. Botha, speaking in South Africa,
said, ``If the recent reports of a further large-scale buildup of
Cuban troops and armaments in Angola are correct _ we will have to
make sure of that _ then it is a breach of the principles agreed to
in New York and of the provisions of the Geneva protocol.''
   Angola has denied the Cuban force has been augmented. Officials
of the Cuban delegation, which joined in the U.S.-mediated talks,
also denied the report.
   The Cubans help Angola in its fight against anti-Marxist
guerrillas and also in blocking South African military incursions.
   U.S. sources in Washington first made the claim of Cuban
reinforcements, but the State Department subsequently said it
continued to estimate there were 50,000 Cubans in Angola.
   Guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi took up the claim in a news
conference last week and said U.S. diplomats tried to persuade him
to accept an agreement that would allow the Cubans three years to
withdraw their forces.
   Savimbi's Union for the Total Independence of Angola, or UNITA,
which receives support from South Africa and the United States, has
been fighting the Marxist government since Portugal granted Angola
independence in 1975.
   The Cuban withdrawal issue remains the main stumbling block.
Negotiations were adjourned last week to give the four parties a
chance to review their positions.
   South Africa, which says it has withdrawn its forces from
Angola, has insisted the Cubans be withdrawn within one year. It
has said it will grant independence to South-West Africa, or
Namibia, if the Cubans withdraw. Angola initially said it would
take four years for the Cuban withdrawal, though it apparently has
offered to send them home in three years.
   In a related development, Savimbi said he would be prepared to
work under Angolan President Eduardo dos Santos, provided
democratic elections are held following any peace agreement, news
reports in Lisbon, Portugal, said Wednesday.
   Savimbi said in an interview in the state-owned daily Diario de
Noticias, ``I am prepared to work under orders of Eduardo dos
Santos. ... I would accept a position of second, third, fourth
place, it doesn't matter to me.''
   The rebel leader added though, ``I set one condition _ that
elections will be realized within a period agreed on by UNITA,
MPLA, FNLA and other patriotic forces.''
   The MPLA is dos Santos' Popular Movement for the Liberation of
Angola. The FNLA, or National Front for the Liberation of Angola
saw its support smashed after a defeat by MPLA troops in 1976.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2311EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissingNewlyweds     09-07 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Missing Newlyweds,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>College Student Who Vanished With New Husband Injured In Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAYWOOD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who disappeared from Wheaton
College along with her new husband, prompting a nationwide search,
suffered serious injury in a car accident and may be charged with
drunken driving, police said Wednesday.
   Carolyn MacLean Swanson, 22, of Glen Ellyn was reported in
serious condition at Loyola University Medical Center one day after
the collision Tuesday.
   The accident occurred in suburban Wheaton when Mrs. Swanson
apparently tried to pass a car and ran into the back of another
auto that was waiting in a left-turn lane. The driver of the car
she struck, a 16-year-old Wheaton girl, was reported in good
condition at another hospital.
   ``Based on witnesses' statements ... in conjunction with the
accident investigation, charges including driving under the
influence, transportation of open liquor in a motor vehicle and
improper lane usage are pending against Ms. Swanson,'' said a
statement from Wheaton police.
   A blood test at Loyola revealed that Ms. Swanson is pregnant,
officials said.
   Ms. Swanson and Scott Swanson, 23, were secretly married a week
before they disappeared April 2 from the private Christian college.
Their ransacked car was found in a Chicago alley with the engine
running, leading to fears of foul play.
   The couple turned up unharmed July 27 in San Diego, where they
said they had been living under assumed names, pursuing ``perfect
love.''
   On Aug. 31, an Army panel said Swanson, an ROTC cadet until the
disappearance, should be removed from the program and required to
repay more than $16,000 he received for tuition and related
expenses.
</TEXT>
