<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2213EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Bangladesh-Flood 2ndLd-Writethru a0668 09-07 0800</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Flood, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0668,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Aid Donors Say Time Has Come for Long-term Solution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 16th graf, American flood ... UPDATING
with Red Cross, U.S. group appeal for relief aid. Picks up 17th
graf pvs, Several Bangladeshi ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DHA4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three-fourths of Bangladesh was under
water Wednesday, and some aid donors say it is time for long-term
solutions in an impoverished land that becomes a vast flood plain
every monsoon season.
   ``We have started thinking about the focus of our development
aid,'' a diplomat from one industrial nation said privately. ``It
doesn't really make sense to pour millions into this country every
year and see it washed away.''
   Floods began in June with the annual monsoon season. They have
claimed 416 lives by the government's count, which is considered
low, and 1,267 on the basis of unofficial tabulations by Dhaka
newspapers.
   The government said Wednesday night all major rivers remained
above flood stage but that water levels fell during the previous 24
hours in all rivers except two small tributaries near the Bay of
Bengal.
   But people still were marooned on rooftops and scarce patches of
high ground, and as many as one-quarter of the nation's 110 million
citizens were homeless.
   Wells and pumps have been submerged and people have begun
drinking flood water, causing a rise in diarrhea cases and fear of
epidemics.
   On Wednesday night, the health service reported 16,813 new cases
of diarrhea in the previous 24 hours, bringing known cases in the
past two weeks to 119,882. Eighty-three of those people have died
and are included in the official death count.
   Statistics come only from areas that can communicate with Dhaka,
however, so the figures probably are low.
   Officials say total damage and reconstration needs cannot be
assessed until the waters recede, but President Hussain Mohammed
Ershad said Tuesday the cost of rebuilding roads and railways alone
would be $156 million.
   Bangladeshi officials, donor nations and international
organizations all say the most pressing need is a regional plan to
stop flood waters that originate outside Bangladesh.
   Water rushes down from the Himalayas each monsoon season in
rivers that empty into the Bay of Bangal through the Bangladesh
delta.
   Ershad and other top Bangladeshi officials emphasize the need to
work with neighboring India and nearby Nepal and Bhutan for a
solution, but a senior U.N. official said he has pushed regional
planning in vain for nearly a decade.
   Until long-term steps are taken, major aid donors say they have
no choice but to help feed the people of Bangladesh, who are among
the world's poorest, and provide medical assistance.
   The United States, for example, is giving Bangladesh $131.5
million in aid this year, including $73 million for food. The rest
is for development assistance, but generally goes for such things
as health, family planning and agricultural research.
   Washington has pledged $3.6 million of flood relief but most
already was in the pipeline as part of the annual aid package.
   American flood relief consists of speeding up delivery of $2.5
million worth of wheat already in Bangladesh for distribution this
year, plus $1.1 million consisting of seed and constributions to
relief funds.
   The International Red Cross appealed for $6 million for the
flood victims. American Red Cross President Richard F. Schubert Jr.
said the funds would be used over the next two months to feed up to
1 million people, clothe up to 100,000 and provide medical relief
and housing for the neediest of families.
   World Vision, an international Christian relief and development
agency based in Monrovia, Calif., appealed for $500,000 for flood
relief aid for Bangladesh.
   Several Bangladeshi officials handling relief said Wednesday
they could not compute the total amount offered from abroad so far.
   A senior U.N. official, whose office helps coordinates foreign
aid, also was unable to provide a total. He said part of the
problem was that much of the aid comes from funds that already had
been allocated for Bangladesh but now is being applied directly to
flood victims.
   ``The figures are changing almost every hour,'' he said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``A number of embassies are
exploring what the scope might be and have not yet made a final
commitment.''
   A senior Western diplomat who follows aid donations closely
said, ``People talk about flood control, (but) the major problem
for Bangladesh is overpopulation.''
   Population density in Bangladesh is 2,000 per sqaure mile, the
world's highest after Hong Kong and Singapore.
   While Hong Kong and Singapore are little more than city-states,
however, Bangladesh is an agricultural nation of about 55,000
square miles, roughly the size of Wisconsin.
   Seventy-five percent of its people work in agriculture, working
the rice paddies and jute fields inundated by the floods.
</TEXT>
