<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ForestFires-WyoDelegation     09-07 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires-Wyo Delegation,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simpson, Wallop Call For Disaster Designation For Yellowstone</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Forest Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyoming's congressional delegation asked
Interior Secretary Donald Hodel on Wednesday to declare the state a
disaster area because of wildfires in Yellowstone National Park and
surrounding forests.
   U.S. Sen. Malcolm Wallop also called for the resignation of
National Park Service Director William Penn Mott ``for the simple
reason that he continues to find some reason to celebrate this
event while all the rest of us are suffering.''
   Wyoming's congressional delegation disagrees with the Park
Service's policy of allowing fires of natural origin to burn
untended as long as they don't threaten structures or people.
   However, in the last month Yellowstone officials have tried to
suppress all new fires, whether caused by man or nature. But
unusually dry conditions and gusting winds have prevented thousands
of firefighters from gaining control.
   Republicans Wallop and Sen. Alan Simpson, along with Montana
Sens. Max Baucus and John Melcher, met with Hodel in Washington,
D.C., to express their displeasure with the way fires in the
Yellowstone area are being handled.
   In Yellowstone alone, 644,000 of the park's 2.2 million acres
have been charred since late June, while more than 1 million acres
have been blackened in the park and its surrounding national
forests.
   Simpson also pressed the delegations' demands with President
Reagan during a separate meeting.
   A disaster declaration, which would have to come from Reagan,
would make low-interest loans and cash assistance available to
businessmen and homeowners affected by the fires. Wyoming tourism
has fallen off drastically because of the blazes.
</TEXT>
