<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2338EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wallach-Media     09-07 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wallach-Media,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wallach Says He Was Convicted By News Media</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E. Robert Wallach, the Edwin Meese III friend
under indictment in the Wedtech bribery case, said Wednesday night
that he was convicted by the news media even before he was indicted.
   Wallach, speaking at an American University forum on the press,
said the First Amendment guarantee of freedom of the press ``does
not give them authority to desecrate the Sixth Amendment right: the
presumption of innocence.''
   The San Francisco lawyer, who goes on trial Jan. 3 in New York
on federal racketeering and conspiracy charges, said he was the
victim of the media and a special prosecutor's investigation whose
purpose ``was to drive Ed Meese from office.''
   ``I became an appropriate ... vehicle to help to accomplish
that. I became a rag doll you chewed,'' said Wallach, who is under
indictment for allegedly taking payoffs from Wedtech officials to
influence Meese, the former White House counselor and attorney
general, and other public officials.
   ``I was convicted before I was indicted. I was convicted by the
American media,'' said Wallach.
   Lyn Nofziger, the former White House political director
appealing his conviction of illegal lobbying his former Reagan
administration colleagues, told the forum that although some
reporters are careless, he received fair coverage at his trial.
   ``You can't point a finger at the profession,'' said Nofziger, a
former reporter.
   Two reporters on the same panel, Ruth Marcus of The Washington
Post and James Polk of NBC News, insisted the press had no power to
indict or convict anyone.
   Polk said Wallach's problems stemmed from his indictment and the
special prosecutor's investigation of Meese, not the media's
reporting of them.
   ``The press is not the legal system. The legal system, to which
Bob Wallach belongs (as a lawyer), ... decides guilt or
innocence,'' said Polk, a Pulitzer Prize-winning investigative
reporter.
   Wallach said the way the press reports indictments makes people
look guilty.
   ``An even mediocre prosecutor can get a grand jury to indict a
ham sandwich. I'm not a sandwich and I'm certainly not a ham
sandwich,'' said Wallach, a law school classmate and longtime
associate of Meese.
   ``I don't think it would change the public perception at all if
we began every story with, `Another presumably innocent man was
indicted today,''' said Polk.
   Polk, however, said he personally feels the press ``has fostered
an assumption of guilt on the part of Bob Wallach before trial.''
He said juries often begin with the assumption that a defendant is
guilty.
   But Marcus, a Harvard-trained lawyer who covers the Justice
Department, said it is the judge's job to ensure that juries set
aside any preconceptions and reach their verdict solely on the
evidence.
   Wallach was also airing his complaints about the media at a news
conference at the National Press Club Thursday.
   Wedtech was the Bronx, N.Y., minority-controlled defense
contractor that collapsed in a bribery scandal in 1986.
   Nofziger is appealing his conviction on three counts of
violating the Ethics in Government Act. He has been sentenced to
three months in jail and a $30,000 fine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
