<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Non-Aligned     09-07 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Non-Aligned,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-Aligned Movement Criticized As Ineffective</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ambassador said Wednesday that a
tendency by the non-aligned movement to generate voluminous
resolutions which have little or no impact has robbed the movement
of the influence it once had in the world.
   The criticism came during the opening session of a four-day
conference of foreign ministers from nations that profess
non-alignment, and it was echoed by several other speakers who
called on the movement to review its role.
   Delegations from 92 of the movement's 101 members attended the
meeting, including 70 foreign ministers. The conference is expected
to map out the movement's policies for the rest of the century.
   ``The movement has become a marginal force on the world stage,''
producing many declarations after each meeting ``which appear to
have no impact,'' Singapore's representative, Ambassador Kishore
Mahbubani, said in a speech.
   ``We will have to re-examine carefully the procedures and
practices of the movement that have allowed it to stagnate,'' he
said. ``The central question ... is this: Can we attempt some bold
restructuring ... within the movement to make it once again a vital
force on the world stage?''
   Zimbabwe's foreign minister, Nathan Shamuyaria, said the
movement risks becoming ``ineffective and irrelevant'' if it does
not follow through on its resolutions and streamline its
operations. ``We must ensure that NAM (the movement) is present at
the tables where decisions are taken,'' he said.
   ``Our major problem,'' he added, ``may not only be the volume or
quality of our documents but rather the degree of our faithfulness
in upholding, promoting and defending the positions we adopt by
consensus in those documents.''
   In general, the movement's documents lack concrete proposals for
solutions to the problems they analyze, Shamuyaria said.
   In his keynote address, President George Vassiliou of Cyprus
said the meeting must focus on bolstering the economies of its
members, which include the world's poorest nations.
   Vassiliou told the 800 delegates the meeting was being held ``at
a time of dramatic changes in the international scene ... in an
atmosphere of optimism as a result of several positive political
developments.''
   He mentioned superpower detente and progress toward the
settlement of conflicts in Iran and Iraq, Afhganistan, Angola and
the Western Sahara.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``We note with sadness that the economic
conditions of most developing countries has not improved. In fact
it has deteriorated.''
   The conference will end Saturday.
</TEXT>
