<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietEmigration     09-07 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Emigration,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Solarz Raises Possibility Of Freer Emigration From USSR</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., said Wednesday
that based on discussions he had recently with Soviet officials in
Moscow, he believes it is possible that the Soviet Union may
eventually remove its historic barriers against people moving
abroad.
   ``I came away with the impression that it is no longer
inconceivable that within a few years you could have something
approaching freedom of emigration for Jews and perhaps other
citizens of the Soviet Union,'' Solarz told reporters.
   During an August visit to the Soviet capital, he said, ``I had
some of the most remarkable discussions I have ever had'' with
Soviet officials who have influence on matters of clearance to
leave the country.
   Solarz added that the officials, whom he declined to identify,
told him that ``continued restrictions on the right of emigration
are in fact inconsistent with glasnost and perestroika'' _ openness
and restructuring, the key reform policies of Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   While not saying when it would happen, ``they said they wouldn't
be at all surprised'' if the policies would change in the future,
said Solarz, a member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee.
   ``I was stunned to hear ... Soviet officials talk about this as
a conceivable possibility,'' Solarz said, noting that he had become
accustomed to ``haggling over the fate of each individual'' seeking
to leave the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
