<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ForestFires-Towns 1stLd-Writethru a0725 09-07 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Fires-Towns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0725,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yellowstone Fire Skirts Tourist Towns; Other Fires Pose New
Threats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Red Bench blaze; picks up
4th graf: ``Now, with ...; ADDS 4 grafs details on Red Bench.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Laserphoto Upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COOKE CITY, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters singed the edges of two
small tourist communities Wednesday in a so-far successful effort
to protect the towns from a huge wind-blown forest fire making its
way out of Yellowstone National Park.
   Another blaze, the 5,000-acre Red Bench fire in the state's
northwest corner, swept into Glacier National Park on Wednesday and
destroyed ranger stations before raging through the evacuated
community of Polebridge, on the park's western boundary.
   Gusty wind fanned backfires lighted along a hillside north of
Silver Gate and nearby Cooke City, creating a charred buffer zone
in advance of the main body of the 119,000-acre Storm
Creek-Hellroaring fire.
   Flames from the backfire roared past Silver Gate late Tuesday
night, coming within 200 yards of buildings clustered along the
community's main street before continuing east past Cooke City on
Wednesday.
   The flames, driven by winds up to 35 mph, leaped a safety line
Wednesday and raced five miles east, destroying four remote summer
cabins near a mountain pass.
   Firefighters sprayed foam on buildings in Colter Pass, 2{ miles
east of Cooke City and saved about 40 structures before the heat of
the soaring flames drove them out, said fire official Bob Martines.
   ``Now, with the fuels burned out, at least on this side of the
valley, there won't be anything left to burn,''' said Bill Stalker,
fire information officer.
   However, fire officials remained concerned that winds could
shift and drive the main portion of the fire into dry, unburned
timber south of the canyon towns.
   Survival of the towns was a matter of luck. Driven by wind with
gusts up to 25 mph, flames from the backfire jumped a line at just
the right spot and traveled down the north side of the canyon
rather than through Silver Gate and Cooke City.
   Asked how close the backfire came to structures at Silver Gate
on Tuesday night, fire information officer Dave McMorran replied:
``Zero. It's right up behind the buildings.''
   The only thing between the fires and structures was the initial
fire break itself, which McMorran described as ``one or two
(bulldozer) blades, 10 to 20 feet.''
   Stalker said, ``The blackened areas on the north sides of both
Silver Gate and Cooke City should significantly reduce the danger
of fire slopping over'' from the main blaze, which was still about
a mile from Silver Gate.
   Evacuated residents may complain about the ugly scene of
blackened timber marking the flames' passage, but it would have
burned anyway, he said. Had the main fire been allowed to sweep
into Silver Gate unchecked, ``that would have eaten the whole town
in 15 to 20 minutes,'' Stalker said.
   In Silver Gate, exhausted firefighters slept anywhere they could
find a grassy spot. Some had worked for more than 24 hours,
protecting buildings from the flames that raced by on the hillside.
   The Red Bench fire breeched the western boundary of Glacier Park
on Wednesday, and quickly charred more than 1,000 acres of the
park, burning several vacant cabins and two ranger stations.
   An abrupt wind shift sent the flames south and through the small
evacuated community of Polebridge, said Madelyn Kempf, fire
information officer.
   ``I'm sure there was extensive damage,'' she said. But officials
could not determine the extent since ``we can't send people in
there because of the firestorm conditions'' created by the
fast-moving flames, Kempf added.
   About 100 people live in the forested Polebridge area.
   Two campgrounds in Glacier were evacuated and closed, officials
said.
</TEXT>
