<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Rig-Bodies,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Divers To Bring Up Oil Rig Modules Thought To Contain Missing Men</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABERDEEN, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Divers worked around the clock
Wednesday on two sunken sections of the Piper Alpha oil rig thought
to contain the bodies of many of the 120 men still missing in the
disaster, officials said.
   The platform's operator, Occidental Petroleum, estimated the two
living-area sections that fell into the North Sea in the July 6
explosion and fire could be lifted from the seabed by the end of
the month.
   ``The harrowing task before us will be a complex operation in
demanding work conditions,'' said John Brading, the company's chief
executive in Britain. ``We will do our utmost to recover as many of
the missing men as we possibly can.''
   In all, 167 men died when the platform exploded into flames
about 120 miles off Scotland. A third living-area module broke up
in the disaster.
   A company spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
18 divers were working in shifts 24 hours a day to prepare the
modules for lifting.
   The two sections found on the ocean floor would be lifted onto a
crane barge and taken to shallow water for inspection, the
spokeswoman said.
   The main module weighs 1,100 tons and is about as high as a
four-story building, she said.
   Occidental said the bodies could not be recovered until the
platform was secured and its 36 wellheads plugged, a process
completed on Monday.
</TEXT>
