<DOCNO> AP880907-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bomb-SniffingDog     09-07 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb-Sniffing Dog,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dog Who Sniffs President's Luggage for Bombs Retires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bomb-sniffing dog whose
nostrils give President Reagan's luggage the once-over has been
retired.
   Eight-year-old Arno, the first canine to serve on the Santa
Barbara County Sheriff's Department, served his last day on the
force Tuesday. He now nips at flies and relaxes at the rural home
of Deputy Andrew Stanley.
   ``We hated to see him go,'' Sgt. Eric George said Wednesday.
``But he's got freedom now. He'll be able to get out and move
around a little more now, but he whines and cries when he sees his
handler going to work.''
   Arno was retired because he has an incurable spinal disorder,
said George. ``He's undergone two surgeries but we are worried now
that he could injure himself where it might paralyze him.''
   ``Now, he can live out the rest of his life in relaxation.''
   For six years, Arno has accompanied either George or Stanley on
various assignments: protection, tracking, searching and bomb
detection. Arno was trained with private donations, but has served
a very public function with Reagan regularly vacationing at his
ranch near here.
   ``He's been utilized on bomb sweeps for President Reagan and
Vice President Bush, Geraldine Ferraro and Gary Hart,'' George said.
   Arno also sniffed for bombs during the 1984 Summer Olympics when
events were held at the University of California, Santa Barbara.
   ``No, he never found a bomb,'' the sergeant said, adding:
``Nothing ever exploded after a sweep, so I guess we did OK.''
</TEXT>
