<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PTL     09-07 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL,0653</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions Raised About Bakker's Mysterious Greek Financiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man representing mysterious Greek
financiers who former TV evangelist Jim Bakker says are backing his
$172 million offer to buy PTL has been convicted of fraud, a
television station reported Wednesday.
   WBTV in Charlotte, N.C., said from 1970 through 1981, Louis
Pihakis, who runs International Financial Consultants in Pensacola,
Fla., was arrested or served time for a variety of charges
including fraud, mail fraud, conspiracy, forgery, counterfeiting
and parole violations.
   The station did not say where it got its information. The report
said Pihakis admitted to the station serving eight months in jail
during that time on charges he said were trumped-up.
   Pihakis' home telephone number in Pensacola is unlisted and he
could not be reached for comment.
   Bakker's lawyer, Jim Toms of Hendersonville, N.C., told The
Associated Press in a telephone interview Wednesday night that
neither Bakker nor his lawyers know the identity of the Greek
businessmen.
   He said they are relying on the word of longtime Bakker friend
and Chicago businessman Jerry Sinclair, who led Bakker to Pihakis
and has acted as a middleman between them. Toms described Pihakis
as the U.S. representative for the Greek businessmen.
   Sinclair, who declined to say what his business is but was
identified by Toms as a songwriter, told The Associated Press in a
telephone interview from Fort Mill that he was aware that Pihakis
had a criminal record, but he did not know how extensive it was.
   Sinclair said he has had positive verification, which did not
come through Pihakis, that the Greek money does exist.
   He said Pihakis has paid for any mistakes he may have made in
the past. ``We know him and trust him because he canot afford to
make a mistake,'' Sinclair said.
   ``That's the thing about the Christian ministry that you must
remember, that we're a very forgiving group, that if somebody makes
mistakes we don't mind that,'' Sinclair told the television
station. ``It matters who they are today. You can find a record on
just about anybody. Maybe the record might not be criminal, but you
got a record of sinning.''
   Sinclair said as long as adverse publicity about Pihakis does
not scare away a Midwest bank that has agreed to handle the Greek
funds, the deal to buy PTL's Christian theme park, satellite
television network and real estate should go through in a matter of
days. The bank has not been publicly identified.
   Bakker had said Tuesday he had $2.9 million of $3 million he
needs for a down payment on a $172 million offer he has made to buy
PTL's assets. The Fort Mill-based ministry he left with massive
debts last year after a sex-and-money scandal must sell the assets
as part of a Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization.
   Sinclair said he told bankruptcy trustee M.C. ``Red'' Benton
Tuesday about Pihakis's criminal background after being contacted
by a reporter for WBTV. Sinclair said Benton did not seem overly
concerned.
   Benton, who had set a Thursday deadline for the down payment,
did not return phone calls Wednesday. His secretary said he would
not talk to reporters until Friday, which she said was the earliest
contracts might be signed with Bakker.
   Toms said he was unsure how much money Bakker has raised in his
effort to gather $3 million in cash and pledges. Bakker and his
wife, Tammy Faye, used a direct-mail campaign to ask supporters for
donations, reciting their troubles and offering copies of Mrs.
Bakker's latest gospel album.
   Benton has a deadline of Saturday to present a buyer to U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds, who is based in Greensboro, N.C.
Benton said Tuesday he may present more than one offer to Reynolds.
A $113 million offer from Canadian real estate executive Peter
Thomas is still standing.
</TEXT>
