<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:Mayol ADV19   09-07 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Mayol, ADV 19,0796</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv19</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday AMs, Sept. 19, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>The `Big Blue' Is Home to Jacques Mayol</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The diver Jacques Mayol believes dolphins are
the smartest animals around, and he tries to emulate their way of
life.
   ``That is my hobby, to see how we are related to the dolphins,''
said Mayol, the inspiration for the film, ``Big Blue.''
   ``Its examples should always be followed by man. Its purity and
simplicity. Its respect of its own behavior with nature. He who
lives in harmony with nature can only do good.''
   ``Big Blue,'' directed by Luc Besson, chronicles Mayol's life
from his childhood. Mayol, however, points out that the film
differs greatly from what actually happened.
   ``You can't make a movie totally based on my own life; it could
be a little boring,'' he said. ``It would be too much like a
documentary, too scientific, too philosophical.''
   In ``Big Blue,'' he grows up in Greece and has a diver for a
father. However, Mayol was actually born in the Orient and later
went to Greece to study. His father was not a diver but an
architect and did not like to swim.
   ``Besson made a psychological transfer of his youth in Greece,''
he said. ``He distorted everything, which doesn't matter because
it's a movie. I just accept it, like dolphins do.''
   Much of ``Big Blue'' is devoted to Mayol's friendly rivalry with
Enzo Maiorca, an Italian free diver. Maiorca, whose name was
changed to Molinari in ``Big Blue,'' is determined to dive deeper
than Mayol and dies at the end of the film. The real Enzo Maiorca
is alive.
   ``He's very proud. Very much like he's depicted in the film,''
Mayol said. ``He claims he hasn't seen it. But I knows he's seen
it. He was irritated to the point where he's going to attempt to
beat me again.
   ``The truth is that this rivalry after 22 years still exists.''
   The actor Jean-Marc Barr portrays Mayol in ``Big Blue.''
   ``He's almost like a son to me,'' Mayol said. ``I admired his
desire and his total sincerity in trying to supplicate the little
he knew about me. It was fantastic what he did physically. He dove
day after day.''
   Mayol says it was Besson's idea to make the movie.
   ``Luc went to see me and I thought it was a fabulous thing. I
couldn't believe it. He was just a kid.''
   The film has already been released in Europe and has brought
renewed interest in Mayol's career. But Mayol is not interested in
being a celebrity: ``I don't need the glory, I have it already.''
   Mayol was born April 1, 1927, in Shanghai, which he points out,
means ``On the sea.''
   ``I was a very mischievous child and extremely stubborn and very
bad-tempered,'' he said. ``The hospital where I was born was being
attacked by the Chinese Communists. They wanted to chase all the
white people out. I presumed this marked me.''
   From an early age, Mayol had an interest in the sea.
   ``It's just something that came from within _ totally
unexplained as if it was predestined. I remember as a kid dreaming
I was hanging on to whales.''
   Mayol says his childhood in Shanghai influenced his approach to
diving. ``You go into the sea humbly. It's a very weird feeling.
It's completely another level of conciousness, another reality.''
   In the 1950s, he worked as a journalist in the United States and
was encouraged by friends to competitively test his diving skills.
   Mayol and Maiorca began competing against each other in 1966,
taking turns as the world record holder. But when they reached 249
feet in 1970, the International Federation ruled that the depths
were too dangerous and refused to accept any further records.
   In ``Big Blue,'' Maiorca continues to dive and eventually dies
from going too deep. Mayol says a similar incident, although
non-fatal, actually occurred.
   ``In 1974, he beat me by one meter (3.3 feet) except when he
came back he was dead. At 20 meters from the surface he fainted
completely. He was blue, foam in his mouth,'' Mayol said.
   ``He was brought back to life and solemnly swore that he was
giving up the career. That man is really stubborn.''
   Mayol continued to dive, reaching 345 feet in 1983, but only for
scientific purposes.
   ``I went on because I felt a joy, a total awareness of a new
feeling _ a symbiosis with the sea,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Sept. 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
