<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The world's industrialized economies are booming
this year, and governments should be ready to hit their economic
brakes if inflation shows signs of heating up, the International
Monetary Fund says.
   The IMF outlook has been distributed to member governments but
is not to be made public until later this month. A copy was
obtained and published Tuesday by the AP-Dow Jones News Service.
   The fund's economists now anticipate inflation-adjusted growth
of 3.8 percent for 1988, compared with the 2.8 percent increase
projected in their April report.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car and truck sales fell 10.7 percent in August,
compared with the same month last year when incentives prompted
quicker buying decisions by consumers, the automakers and analysts
said.
   Foreign and domestic vehicle makers said they sold 1.25 million
cars and trucks last month, down from 1.35 million during the same
month last year. Figures exclude Japan's Toyota Motor Sales USA
Inc. and South Korea's Hyundai Motor Co.
   For the 10-day period ended Aug. 31, Chrysler Corp. said its
sales of U.S.-made cars rose 2.6 percent compared with the same
period last year. Ford Motor Co. said its car sales for the period
fell 1.4 percent and General Motors Corp. reported a 13.9 percent
drop.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have slid to a nearly
two-year low as traders continued to lose confidence in OPEC's
ability to restrain its production.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange on Tuesday, futures
contracts for October delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude, dropped 55 cents a barrel to $14.24.
   Crude prices have not closed that low on the exchange since
October 1986, when they reached $13.73 per barrel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's summer movies shattered box-office
records with roughly $1.7 billion in tickets sold, up from last
year's summer record of $1.59 billion.
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' got the headlines but it was a
pair of comedies featuring a cartoon bunny and a prince in search
of a bride that led the way.
   The biggest hits were ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' ``Coming to
America,'' ```Crocodile' Dundee II'' and ``Big.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IBM's top rivals in personal computers have
called a news conference for next Tuesday at which they are
expected to announce an alternative design for the way information
flows inside a personal computer.
   The new design would make it possible for the companies to build
personal computers that rival IBM's 1{-year-old Personal System-2
line without departing so far from the older standard, analysts
said Tuesday.
   Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston is leading the challenge, which
may eventually include as many as 30 companies that make personal
computers or related products, said Jim Weil, an analyst for
Gartner Securities Corp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Eastern Airlines' unions have learned
they will return to federal court later this month to argue their
case against the elimination of 4,000 jobs.
   The U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington told Eastern on Tuesday
to submit legal briefs on its position by Sept. 12.
   While attorneys for the Machinists and Air Line Pilots
Association unions had not fully decided on their next move,
options included seeking a temporary injunction from the U.S.
Supreme Court against the layoffs.
</TEXT>
