<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan has liberalized its financial markets by
announcing it would sell 40 percent of its 10-year government bonds
by auction and would give foreign underwriters a bigger share of
the distribution of the rest of the remaining 60 percent.
   The steps announced Tuesday were favorably received by U.S.
officials.
   The auctions will begin in April 1989 and are expected to make
it easier for foreign securities firms to get a bigger share of the
business of selling Japanese government debt.
</TEXT>
