   The Soviet Union has bought an additional
802,400 metric tons of U.S. corn for delivery during the 1988-89
marketing year which began on Sept. 1, the Agriculture Department
says.
   Counting the latest sales, more than 1.7 million tons of corn
have been sold to the Soviets in the last week, according to USDA
announcements Tuesday. All have been for delivery in 1988-89.
   Corn prices have averaged about $2.68 per bushel at the farm
level, according to USDA estimates, meaning the new sale could have
a farm value of around $84.7 million.
</TEXT>
