<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   09-07 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Car Sales Up, Rest Of Big Three Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sales of cars and trucks were off 10.7
percent last month compared with August 1987, when short-term
incentives enticed consumers to showrooms, automakers and analysts
say.
   Chrysler Corp. was the only one of the Big Three car makers
reporting sales Tuesday to show increases in late August and in
monthly car and truck sales, although one analyst said Chrysler's
incentives were hurting its profits.
   For the month, foreign and domestic vehicle makers reported they
sold 1.25 million cars and trucks last month, compared with 1.35
million during August 1987. Sales by foreign car and truck makers
fell 21.1 percent, and domestic vehicle makers reported a 6.7
percent decline.
   For the Aug. 21-31 period this year, Chrysler said it sold
32,214 U.S.-made cars, compared with 31,388 cars during the same
period last year, a 2.6 percent increase.
   General Motors Corp. reported a 13.9 percent sales decrease to
108,986 from 126,629 cars in late August 1987. Ford Motor Co. said
its sales dropped 1.4 percent to 65,500 in late August this year
from 66,515 in the same period last year.
   For the month, GM's sales were down 20.7 percent and Ford showed
a 6.2 percent decline. Chrysler posted a 5.5 percent increase in
monthly sales.
   All three carmakers reported increases in year-to-date figures,
with Chrysler leading the way at 13.2 percent this year over last
year, followed by Ford at 9.3 percent and GM at a modest 0.4
percent.
   There were nine selling days in the late August periods of 1988
and 1987, and 27 sales days last month compared with 26 days in
August 1987.
   A year ago, with just one month left in the model year,
carmakers offered buyer incentives, including cut-rate financing as
low as 1.9 percent for GM vehicles, to lure customers into
showrooms and shrink inventories. This year the incentives are
different.
   ``Chrysler has been more aggressive than the other two in using
incentives to stimulate sales,'' said Donald DeScenza, an industry
analyst with Nomura Securities Inc. of New York. ``They have the
biggest sales gain and the worst operating performance in the
second quarter. They're cutting into their profits.''
   ``There's an implication that they're buying the sales (with
incentives),'' DeScenza said. ``Those gains are maybe difficult to
hold onto without the incentives in a longer term...''
   ``Chrysler's strategy is to lock in as big a share of the market
as it can to increase its base of loyal customers,'' he said. ``But
I question whether customers gained though aggressive price-cutting
are loyal customers.''
   Toyota Motor Sales USA Inc. did not report August sales Tuesday
due to delayed computation of the monthly figures. The figures were
to be announced today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
