<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Argentina-Debt     09-07 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina-Debt,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officials Expect Argentinian Success In Seeking $4 Billion From
IMF, Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Creditors are not happy about
lending Argentina another $4 billion to help pay interest on its
foreign debt through the end of 1989, but probably will do it
anyway, officials say.
   ``I think they (Argentina) will get new funds. It will be harder
because of the circumstances, but they'll get it,'' an economist
for a U.S.-based bank said Tuesday.
   A spokesman for the Economy Ministry said the ministry also
believes that commercial banks and institutional lenders are
reluctant, but nevertheless will commit new funds.
   An International Monetary Fund mission opened talks this week
with the Economy Ministry and Central Bank about Argentina's
anti-inflation plan and suspended interest payments on its $56
billion foreign debt.
   The nation reportedly is seeking loans totaling $4.2 billion
from the IMF and commercial banks, plus a $500 million bridge loan
to cover its foreign debt interest payments until it gets the IMF
money.
   Interest payments on Argentina's foreign debt, the third-largest
in the developing world behind Brazil and Mexico, will total about
$4.6 billion this year, of which the government wants to borrow
half.
   The Economy Ministry spokesman acknowledged the government is
behind in interest payments, but would not say by how much.
   The daily newspaper Ambito Financiero reported Tuesday that
arrearages totaled about $800 million, including $450 million 90
days or more overdue.
   Argentina is seeking a standby loan of about $1.2 billion from
the IMF, to run through the end of the administration of President
Raul Alfonsin in December 1989, according to the Economy Ministry.
   ``The government doesn't want to have to negotiate anything in
1989,'' the ministry spokesman said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   National elections are set for next May, and the opposition
Peronist Party stands a good chance of ousting Alfonsin's Radical
Civic Union.
   The ministry spokesman declined to comment on how much Argentina
wants to borrow from commercial banks, citing the delicate nature
of the talks. But the U.S. bank economist and the newspaper La
Nacion, in an article published Tuesday citing unnamed commercial
bank sources, said Argentina is seeking approximately $3 billion in
new bank funds.
   Central Bank director Daniel Marx is to meet Thursday with a
steering committee of 11 U.S., Canadian, European and Japanese
banks, which represents the 250 to 300 banks holding about $39
billion in outstanding loans to Argentina.
   The commercial loans were rescheduled last year, giving
Argentina a 7-year grace period on repayment of principal and $2
billion in new funds. The IMF also agreed to contribute $1.3
billion in standby funds.
   But the IMF and the banks withheld a combined $450 million that
was to be disbursed this year, because the Alfonsin government did
not meet agreed-upon economic targets, including levels of
inflation and the budget deficit.
   Inflation in August probably will exceed July's 25.6 percent
increase, which brought the rise in the cost of living to 178
percent for the first seven months of this year.
   On Aug. 3, the Alfonsin government devalued the austral by 11.4
percent against the U.S. dollar, pledged to reduce the budget
deficit, lifted restrictions on imports, and arranged with
producers a program of voluntary price controls.
   In a separate development, Argentina is seeking $750 million
from the World Bank. That money would be used to help finance the
reform of the banking system and reorient trade policy.
   The World Bank's vice president for Latin America, Shamid
Husain, issued no statement before departing last week, nor did the
Central Bank. But the Economy Ministry spokesman said Tuesday,
``There is not the slightest doubt the loan will be approved.''
   Argentina also is seeking a $500 million bridge loan from a
consortium led by the U.S. Treasury to cover interest payments on
the foreign debt until Argentina receives new funds from the IMF.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
