<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StiffelAcquisition     09-07 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stiffel Acquisition,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kelly Proteges Follow His Footsteps With Stiffel Acquisition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They were schooled in corporate buyouts by master
dealmaker Donald P. Kelly, but two proteges of the Beatrice Co.
chairman say they also plan to actively manage their newly acquired
Stiffel Co. _ as they add to it.
   James M. Snodgrass said Tuesday he and Steven S. Lindblad are
``a little more operationally oriented and a little less dealmaking
oriented'' than Kelly.
   They plan to prove it as chairman and vice-chairman,
respectively, of Stiffel, a Chicago-based manufacturer of
brass-plated lamps formerly owned by Beatrice.
   ``We both want to grow The Stiffel Co. and do other acquisitions
but we want to be more involved in running the business,''
Snodgrass said in a telephone interview.
   Snodgrass and Lindblad did not disclose the amount their
investor group paid to buy Stiffel from American Brands Inc.
   American Brands, based in Greenwich, Conn., acquired Stiffel
earlier this year in its $2.7 billion purchase of Stiffel's parent,
E-II Holdings Inc., a Beatrice offshoot also headed at the time by
Kelly.
   Snodgrass, 51, said one reason he and Lindblad chose Stiffel as
their first acquisition was that, as former executives of Beatrice
and E-II, they already had some knowledge of the company's
operations.
   The 50-year-old Stiffel has about 500 employees, he said.
   The men said Kelly, who will resign as chairman of Chicago-based
Beatrice effective Oct. 1, played no direct role in their venture.
   But Snodgrass and Lindblad, who met while working for Kelly at
Esmark Inc. in the early 1970s, acknowledged his influence on this
new direction in their professional lives.
   ``I suppose, since I worked for the man from 1971 forward, if I
wasn't influenced by him I'd be kind of dumb,'' Snodgrass said. ``I
suppose the common tie is the entrepreneurial orientation that Don
Kelly brought to Beatrice for those of us who worked for him.''
   Lindblad, 48, said he and Snodgrass absorbed lessons in
conglomerate-building during their 15 years of working together
under Kelly.
   ``We have both done a lot of acquisitions and corporate
divestment work in that period of time and it can't help but have
some rub-off,'' he said.
   Snodgrass and Lindblad stayed with Esmark for about a year after
Beatrice acquired it for $2.8 billion in 1984, leaving Kelly on the
outside.
   In 1986, Kelly won a takeover of Beatrice, taking the company
private in a $6.2 billion deal backed by the New York buyout firm
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. Snodgrass and Lindblad came back on
board later that year.
   Snodgrass served as executive vice president of BCI Holdings
Corp. and president of Beatrice Consumer Durables Group, a non-food
division that went public as a part of E-II in 1987 with Stiffel as
one of its holdings. Kelly made Snodgrass president and chief
executive officer of E-II Consumer Products Co., E-II's major
operating subsidiary.
   Lindblad served with Snodgrass as senior vice president and
chief financial officer of E-II Consumer Products. Before that, he
held the same titles in the Beatrice Consumer Durables Group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AmericanSavings Bjt   09-07 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-American Savings, Bjt,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>California's Other Big Thrifts Stronger than American, Experts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $2 billion federally-assisted bailout of
American Savings & Loan Association will not be the last such
rescue in California, home to 13 of the nation's 20 biggest S&Ls,
but experts said most of the state's large thrifts are in far
better shape than American.
   The trouble at American, object of a bailout announced Monday,
is more an indication of poor management and lax regulation than a
sign that California thrifts overall are especially endangered,
analysts said Tuesday.
   However, as in the industry nationwide, more mergers and buyouts
are expected among the state's thrifts, particularly smaller
institutions that proliferated in the wake of deregulation in the
early 1980s.
   ``I think there's a trend toward consolidation,'' said William
Davis, chief deputy commissioner of the California Department of
Savings and Loans. ``We have what I would consider to be an
overcapacity in terms of the number of institutions to serve the
public in California.''
   Stockton-based American, the nation's biggest insolvent thrift
and second-largest overall, will be acquired by the Robert M. Bass
investment group of Fort Worth, Texas, under a rescue orchestrated
by the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   Bass will inject $550 million into American and the bank board
will put up $500 million in notes and an estimated $1.5 billion in
cash over the next 10 years. The bank board, which will own 30
percent of the new American, pumped $250 million into the company
Tuesday.
   The board also put American into a temporary receivership,
erasing the value of the 35.9 million shares of stock in
Irvine-based Financial Corp. of America, the holding company that
owned American.
   Business continued uninterrupted at American's 180 California
branches and federal insurance remained in force for all deposits.
   William Popejoy, who has headed American and FCA since 1984,
will leave FCA but remain at the helm of American, according to
announcements by the bank board and the company.
   FCA directors scheduled a meeting for today to determine the
company's future.
   American is the nation's second-biggest S&L, with more than $30
billion in assets. California boasts 13 of the country's 20 S&Ls
ranked by assets, including No. 1 Home Savings of America.
   California also is home to 14 S&Ls troubled enough to be under
direct supervision of the bank board, and others that are being
monitored for possible future action. Additionally, 12 California
thrifts have been sold or combined with stronger institutions since
1985, according to the bank board's San Francisco office.
   Most analysts emphasize that the problem institutions represent
a minority of the industry nationwide: In California, the 14
institutions under control of regulators have combined assets of
$4.6 billion, while statewide industry assets total $350 billion.
   American foundered, analysts said, largely because of too-rapid
growth and millions of dollars in loans on real estate in
California, Texas and elsewhere that other institutions would not
touch. In contrast, other big S&Ls lean far more heavily on
so-called quality mortgages, those on single family homes.
   ``By and large, the people running the major savings and loans
in the state have gone through a number of cycles and on the whole
are pretty conservative people,'' said Donald Crowley, who follows
the industry for Keefe, Bruyette and Woods Inc. in San Francisco.
   The California industry is on a stronger footing than that in
Texas and Oklahoma, where the collapse of oil-dependent economies
has been followed by wholesale S&L bailouts, analysts said.
California, they said, continues enjoying a housing boom that has
continued essentially unchecked since the 1950s and largely is
responsible for growth of the state's huge thrifts.
   ``It's sort of like the difference between standing on rock and
standing on quicksand,'' Crowley said, comparing the economies that
support S&Ls in California and the oil patch.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0751EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Sprinkel     09-07 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Sprinkel,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top U.S. Economic Aide Lauds U.S. And Japanese Economies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beryl W. Sprinkel, chairman of President Reagan's
Council of Economic Advisers, praised the U.S. and Japanese
economies Wednesday and said most trade issues had been resolved.
   Sprinkel predicted that inflation in the United States ``will
continue restrained'' and said he was ``pleased to note'' the
Japanese policy of encouraging domestic demand to lower exports and
reduce trade imbalances.
   The top U.S. economic adviser was in Japan for meetings with
economists and Japanese government officials, including Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and
Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita.
   Fielding questions at a news conference, Sprinkel declined to
comment on the dollar's recent strength in foreign exchange
markets, saying to comment would affect the market.
   When asked about the Bank of Japan's lack of participation in
recent interest rate increases by the U.S. Federal Reserve Board
and European central banks, Sprinkel cited Japan's almost-zero
inflation rate.
   ``I'm not about to second-guess the decision of the Bank of
Japan not to raise the discount rate when they have the lowest
inflation in the world,'' he said.
   Sprinkel said ``good economic relations'' between Japan and the
United States had led to resolution of major trade issues recently.
Those include disputes over U.S. beef and citrus imports to Japan
and U.S. firms having access to bid on construction projects in
Japan.
   ``We do not believe that will be the end,'' he said, adding he
hoped to see further measures to eliminate controls in Japan's
economy.
</TEXT>
