<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-OPEC-Council     09-07 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-OPEC-Council,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Ministers To Coordinate Policies Ahead Of OPEC Session</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subroto as one name is correct</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The six oil ministers of the Gulf Cooperation
Council nations, four of whom represent key Arab nations in OPEC,
will meet next month to review ways of stabilizing the world oil
market, a government news agency reported Wednesday.
   The meeting is scheduled for Oct. 16, the Kuwait News Agency
said, but GCC officials, while acknowledging the ministers would
meet, declined to confirm the date.
   Earlier reports had said the meeting would take place Sept. 17
and 18.
   KUNA said production by the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries and the restoration of quota discipline would
be key topics at the GCC talks in advance of an OPEC ministerial
session scheduled for Nov. 21 in Vienna.
   The GCC includes Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar and the United Arab
Emirates, which are OPEC members, and Bahrain and Oman, which are
not.
   KUNA said the four OPEC members would ``coordinate stands on a
number of issues of concern to OPEC ... especially with respect to
the future production level of OPEC and the necessity of member
states adhering to individual production quotas to guarantee
preservation of stability of the official price per barrel of oil
on the world market.''
   Overall OPEC production in August was estimated at 20 million
barrels a day, nearly 3.5 million barrels over its self-imposed
output ceiling. This has helped depress prices below OPEC's
benchmark of 18 dollars a barrel.
   The U.A.E. has refused to accept a quota of 948,000 barrels a
day and demanded a 1.5 million-barrel quota. That is about the
level of its current production.
   Kuwait, backed by Saudi Arabia, rejects Venezuela's wish to keep
condensate gases _ liquids condensed from natural gas during
production _ out of oil quotas.
   The GCC group, along with other OPEC members, hope to settle the
issue of production by Iraq and Iran now that their 8-year-old war
has ground to a halt.
   Tehran has reportedly rejected proposals that Iran and Iraq be
allotted equal production quotas in a bid to curb Iraq's unbridled
output of around 2.8 million barrels a day.
   Iraq has refused to accept a quota of 1.5 million barrels a day
and demanded parity with Iran's 2.3 million-barrel quota.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto recently visited Baghdad and
Tehran and indicated that the issue could be solved through a
revamped OPEC production policy aimed at pushing up oil prices to
around $18 a barrel.
   Subroto has also visited other OPEC states, including Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia, the U.A.E. and Qatar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
