<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Italy-Fiat     09-07 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Italy-Fiat,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italian Auto Giant Buys Controlling Stake In Ferrari</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TURIN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fiat SpA said Wednesday that it boosted its
stake to a controlling 90 percent in Ferrari, the prestigious
manufacturer of luxury and sports cars.
   The auto giant, which is controlled by the Agnelli family, said
it acquired an additional 40 percent stake in Ferrari ``in the past
few months'' from Enzo Ferrari, the company founder and chairman
who died in August.
   Fiat acquired a 50 percent shareholding in Ferrari in 1959 but
had options to purchase up to 90 percent in the event of Enzo
Ferrari's death.
   The remaining 10 percent was left in the hands of Piero Lardi
Ferrari, Ferrari's son.
   A Fiat spokeswoman said the purchase of the additional 40
percent stake cost Fiat about 19 billion lire, or $13.5 million.
   Ferrari, which produces nearly 4,000 luxury and sports cars a
year, posted net profit of 14.8 billion lire, or $10.5 million, in
1987 on sales of 360 billion lire, or $257 million.
   Most Ferrari cars, including the popular Testarossa model, are
exported to the United States.
</TEXT>
