<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0923EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Rolls-Royce     09-07 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rolls-Royce,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ritzy Rolls-Royce Ruled a Lemon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $130,000 Rolls-Royce Corniche convertible
turned out to be a lemon, but a federal judge ruled the British
carmaker owes the Detroit lawyer who bought it only legal fees and
court costs _ no refund.
   Rolls wasn't privy to the contract A. Robert Zeffs signed with
the dealer, Tamaroff Buick of Southfield, U.S. District Judge Anna
Diggs Taylor ruled a week ago. She ordered Rolls to pay Zeffs
$55,307.77 in court fees and costs.
   Zeffs bought the 1981 Tudor red car in March 1983. It came with
300 miles on the odometer, an English leather interior, Circassian
walnut on the dash and a paint job advertised as glowing more like
marble than metal.
   But after Zeff added the car to his classic collection, he began
to notice problems with flaking paint.
   Repairs by Tamaroff were followed with complaints about
additional problems such as a nonworking gearshift indicator light.
   Zeff took the car to Florida in December 1983 and got
Rolls-Royce and a Palm Beach dealer into the picture.
   Finally, a Rolls official commissioned a new finish for the car,
to be done in Florida. The Corniche's 14 to 20 coats of paint,
primer and filler were removed to bare metal, but without Zeff's
consent.
   When he learned of the job, he told Rolls, in effect, to keep
the car. He wanted his money back.
   Because the car was inadequate to start with and a proper
refinishing could only be completed in England, Taylor found that
Rolls had violated its limited warranty and committed fraud.
   However, Zeff could not sue Rolls alone to revoke his acceptance
of the car because he bought it from Tamaroff, Taylor ruled.
   Because the judge ordered Rolls to pay Tamaroff's legal bills,
too, the dealership feels vindicated, said Tamaroff General Manager
Tony Jerome.
   ``We weren't the problem,'' Jerome said.
   Zeff, meanwhile, said he expects Rolls to keep the case alive.
   ``I can't see them not appealing this,'' he said. ``They can't
let a judgment of fraud stand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
