<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 0955EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-HongKong-Lee     09-07 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hong Kong-Lee,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hearing Held in Hong Kong Courts on U.S. Insider Trading Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies allegedly controlled by the
Taiwanese businessman charged with insider trading in the United
States asked a judge Wednesday for release of $12 million from
their Hong Kong bank accounts.
   Standard Chartered PLC, a British bank, has refused to release
the deposits at its local branch claiming the money was paid to
U.S. authorities last month to comply with a New York court order,
attorneys for the bank said.
   Taiwanese businessman Fred C. Lee was charged by the U.S.
Securities and Exchange Commission in June with trading on inside
information allegedly provided by Stephen Wang, an analyst at the
New York investment bank Morgan Stanley & Co.
   The two men allegedly made $19 million from illegal trading.
   The court hearing was scheduled to continue Thursday.
   Lee is president of Nanus Asia Co. and Southridge International
Inc., two companies based in the British Virgin Islands, according
to solicitor Charles Wong.
   In a hearing before Hong Kong Supreme Court Justice Gordon
Cruden, a lawyer for the two companies argued that the New York
court order was not enforceable in Hong Kong and that the bank
should pay them the money in their accounts.
   ``The New York orders have no effect whatsoever on the
plaintiffs' right to have their money back,'' attorney Martin Lee
said. ``The accounts were opened in Hong Kong and Hong Kong law is
clearly the proper law.''
   Lee also argued that if the Hong Kong court failed to order
Standard Chartered to hand over the companies' funds, overseas
investors would lose confidence in the British colony's banking
system.
   Arguing for Standard Chartered, attorney Michael Thomas said the
bank couldn't turn the deposits over to Nanus and Southridge
because the charges of insider trading filed against Lee indicated
the funds may have been obtained through a breach of trust and
therefore did not legally belong to the Taiwanese businessman.
   Thomas said that if Standard Chartered had turned the money over
to the two companies instead of the U.S. court, the bank could have
become liable for claims from any victim of alleged insider trading.
   Standard Chartered ``has been caught up in a certain amount of
crossfire'' between courts in the United States and Hong Kong,
Thomas said, adding that there was a ``serious risk'' of the bank
falling victim to double jeopardy.
   Thomas said funds held in the name of Nanus and Southridge had
been treated as belonging to Lee because the companies were
``incorporated cash boxes'' serving solely as the businessman's
nominees.
   Quoting from the testimony of a Standard Chartered officer,
Thomas said that prior to opening the company accounts, Lee had
used a number of personal accounts to finance his U.S. securities
trading.
   Lee did not appear in court. One of his solicitors said the
businessman was in Taiwan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
