<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Amoco-Building     09-07 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amoco-Building,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amoco Skyscraper Skin to be Strapped in Place</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 43,000 white marble panels covering the
outside of the 80-story Amoco Corp. headquarters building will
temporarily be strapped down until tests determine if they must be
replaced because of buckling, officials say.
   After a buckling problem was revealed in March, the company
attached a pair of two-inch stainless steel straps to each panel on
the southwest corner of the skyscraper.
   That corner experiences the toughest beating from wind and
weather changes, and buckling found in some panels caused concern
they could fall off, officials have said.
   Some architects said that all building panels would have to be
replaced, but Amoco officials said they want more time to find a
solution.
   ``If the building is to be re-clad, it will be covered with a
material as close to the color of the original marble as we can
get,'' said Shelby Pierce, Amoco's manager of engineering in charge
of the project.
   Some materials the company might consider are granite, a heavier
marble or aluminum, officials said.
   ``Right now, we plan to keep all of our options open,'' said
Pierce. ``We'll strap the building, get the test results, evaluate
them, and then decide what's the best long-term solution. The
building does not pose a short-term safety problem.''
   The straps are not visible to the casual observer, Thompson said.
</TEXT>
