<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Labor     09-07 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Labor,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Organized Labor Splits Over Boycotting State Job Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOURNEMOUTH, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Overriding the wishes of their
leadership, trade union delegates Wednesday voted narrowly to
boycott a new government program to train the unemployed for other
jobs.
   The vote at the annual conference of the Trades Union Congress,
the umbrella organization of 84 trade unions, was 4.577 million to
4.042 million, a tiny margin that reflected the split in British
organized labor over the controversial government program. Union
chiefs wield huge voting blocks based on membership.
   Neil Kinnock, leader of the opposition Labor Party, had joined
the TUC leadership in appealing against a boycott, saying it would
portray the labor movement as uncaring about the jobless.
   But the pro-boycott camp claimed that the 1.5-billion-pound
($2.55 billion) Employment Training Scheme launched Monday was
designed to exploit the jobless as cheap labor.
   Persons joining the program will get a weekly bonus of 10 to 20
pounds ($17 to $34 dollars) a week on top of their unemployment
checks, plus money for books, transport and equipment, and a
tax-free 200-pound ($340-dollar) bonus if they complete the
six-month course.
   The basic weekly unemployment payment is 32.75 pounds ($55.60),
plus subsidized rent. The new program is aimed primarily at
retraining the 600,000 long-term unemployed among Britain's 2.3
million jobless.
   Supporting a boycott, Ron Todd, leader of the transport workers'
union, said: ``The government is looking for a hole to hide half a
million unemployed, to remove them from the unemployment court
before the next election.''
   Engineers' union president Bill Jordan backed the program,
saying it was imperfect but ``the only one we have got.''
   ``We have no alternative to offer the unemployed _ no training
to offer, no jobs to offer, only our help. We cannot turn round and
say that we, the trade union barons, decree that you cannot join
these schemes,'' said Jordan.
   The resolution adopted at the week-long conference in this
seaside resort called for an immediate boycott, but the TUC
leadership later said it would take effect over two years to
accommodate unions already cooperating with retraining programs.
   Some intepreted the vote as a slap to Kinnock, especially since
the pro-boycott lobby included powerful union chiefs such as Todd,
whom Kinnock is counting on to back him against a challenge to his
leadership at next month's Labor Party convention.
   But Kinnock said the two-year stay of execution would allow
unions to press for improvements.
   The vote was ``not a bad result at all,'' he told reporters.
``These two years can have a very productive outcome.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
