<DOCNO> AP880907-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1105EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitJOA     09-07 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit JOA,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Doesn't Object to Democrat Participation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal attorneys say they have no objection
to limited participation by the Arkansas Democrat in a court case
involving a proposed joint operating agreement between Detroit's
two daily newspapers.
   In a court filing Tuesday, attorneys for the civil division of
the Justice Department said the department did not object to
participation by Little Rock Newspapers Inc., the company that
publishes the Democrat, provided that participation is limited to
issues already raised.
   But the attorneys asked that an affidavit submitted by Democrat
publisher Walter E. Hussman Jr. be stricken from the record because
it goes ``beyond the scope of this case.''
   At issue in the litigation is an injunction issued Aug. 17 by
U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green that bars a joint operating
agreement between The Detroit News, owned by the Gannett Co., and
the Detroit Free Press, owned by Knight-Ridder.
   Gannett owns the Arkansas Gazette, the Democrat's competition in
Little Rock. The Democrat last week submitted a brief in the
Detroit case as a party with an indirect interest in the outcome,
arguing against the JOA.
   Attorneys for the Detroit News last week urged the federal court
to ignore the Democrat's arguments, saying the brief by Little Rock
Newspapers wasn't filed on time, raised questions outside the scope
of the case, and would involve the court in an analysis of pricing
practices by the two Little Rock newspapers.
   Hussman said the company he heads filed the brief because he
believes Gannett is trying to stifle competition in newspaper
markets through the use of JOAs.
   Hussman's affidavit contended approval by Meese of the Detroit
JOA altered the nature of such agreements ``from a vehicle for
preserving journalistic competition where it would otherwise not
exist into a vehicle to assist in eliminating competitive
newspapers even where both newspapers could otherwise survive.''
   According to the Justice Department brief, Little Rock
Newspapers' filings show the company ``seeks to address legal and
factual issues well beyond the scope of this litigation, including
matters pertaining to what it portrays as the competition between
its newspaper, the Arkansas Democrat, with the Arkansas Gazette,
owned by Gannett.''
   ``These matters have no bearing on this case and the facts which
Little Rock Newspapers seeks to introduce form no part of the
administrative record,'' the brief said.
   The Detroit JOA, approved by former Attorney General Edwin Meese
on Aug. 8, would be the largest such agreement in history. The
temporary injunction against the agreement was requested by
Michigan Citizens for an Independent Press, a group of advertisers,
readers and employees.
   The agreement would merge the production and business operations
of the News and Free Press, while keeping the newspapers' news and
editorial departments separate.
   The Newspaper Preservation Act allows such partial mergers when
one of the newspapers involved is in danger of failing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0246 </DOCNO>
