<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-OilPrices 1stLd-Writethru   09-07 0649</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices, 1st Ld-Writethru,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slide; Crude Futures Hit Two-Year Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS grafs 2-4 to UPDATE with latest futures prices, cuts in
posted prices today; picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, The market's ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Market pessimism about OPEC's ability to
restrain its production has pushed oil futures prices to nearly a
two-year low, but experts say American drivers should see little
benefit at the gas pump because of strong demand for the refined
product.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange today, the October contract
for delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of
U.S. crude, was down 9 cents a barrel at $14.15 at late morning.
The contract dropped 55 cents a barrel on Tuesday. Crude prices
have not traded that low on the exchange since October 1986, when
they reached $13.73 per barrel.
   Responding to the drop, several major U.S. oil companies
announced Tuesday and today that they were cutting the official
price they pay for West Texas Intermediate in the spot market.
   Futures contracts for refined oil products traded on the
exchange also continued Tuesday's decline. Wholesale unleaded
gasoline for October delivery had fallen 0.33 cent a gallon to
42.20 cents at late morning, while wholesale heating oil for
October was down 0.23 cent at 41.48.
   The market's skepticism about the ability of the 13-nation
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to trim its output
has deepened in recent days, after initial optimism about
cooperation within the cartel resulting from the cease-fire between
members Iran and Iraq.
   OPEC Secretary-General Subroto recently capped off a series of
meetings with oil producers by visiting officials in Iran and Iraq,
and tried to persuade Iran to allow Iraq a higher production quota.
But Subroto made little headway in his efforts to win cooperation
among OPEC members for curbing overall output.
   ``There just doesn't seem to be any hope right now,'' said Linda
Simard, an oil futures broker at the investment firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. ``Subroto didn't seem to be getting anywhere.''
   The Middle East Economic Survey, an influential weekly published
in Nicosia, Cyprus, reported last week that total OPEC production
was estimated at 20 million barrels a day, more than 3.5 million
barrels over the cartel's official ceiling.
   The cease-fire between the Persian Gulf rivals after eight years
of fighting frees Iran and Iraq to rebuild their war-damaged oil
industries, raising the prospect of a fresh surge in oil production
and a fall in crude prices.
   A key to controlling any increased production, analysts say, is
OPEC's ability to bring Iraq back under its discipline.
   Iraq during the war past ignored its OPEC daily production quota
of 1.54 million barrels, demanding a share equal to Iran's 2.37
million barrels a day. Iraq pumps an estimated 2.8 million barrels
a day, analysts say.
   ``There's too much oil right now. OPEC is showing a complete
lack of discipline,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of the
energy group at Elders Futures Inc.
   The price slide will not necessarily mean a break for drivers
filling up at the pump. While crude oil price declines often bring
price cuts in gasoline that is refined from crude, gasoline demand
now is unusually strong in the United States and supplies are
fairly tight, analysts say.
   ``We really don't expect a significant impact to be felt on
gasoline prices,'' said William Veno, director of oil market
analysis at Data Resources Inc., a consulting firm based in
Lexington, Mass.
   Several big oil refiners, meanwhile, cut the prices they are
willing to pay for West Texas Intermediate. Exxon Corp. and Chevron
Corp. reduced their posted price by 25 cents a barrel, to $14.50.
Texaco Inc., Sun Co., Phillips Petroleum Co., Marathon Petroleum
Corp., Diamond Shamrock R&M Inc., Conoco Inc. and Citgo Petroleum
Corp. lowered their postings for WTI by 50 cents a barrel, to $14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-07 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in a slight technical
correction after five straight days of rising prices, analysts said.
   Despite the early sell-off, experts said underlying fundamentals
remained bullish for the crop futures, especially for the wheat
market, which faces tightening world supplies.
   ``The floor leader is wheat,'' said Richard Feltes, director of
commodity research with Refco Inc., a large Chicago-based futures
brokerage firm.
   Wheat futures are approaching the year's highs set on July 5 and
many observers expect prices to rally through those levels.
   Soybeans and corn also may rally in the long term, but
increasing harvest pressure should keep a lid on those markets
during the next month or two, Feltes said.
   ``I think the mood of the (soybean) trade is described as
cautious near-term, bullish long-term,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $4.08 a bushel; corn was
1\ cents to 1} cents lower with September at $2.92\ a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1{ cents higher with September at $2.72{ a
bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents to 6 cents lower with September at
$8.82 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent lower with October at
70.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .30 cent lower
with September at 81.00 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent to .53
cent higher with October at 37.90 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent to 1.15 cents higher with February at 47.20
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
