<HEAD>B.A.T Industries' Profit Up 5 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: B.A.T is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   B.A.T Industries PLC said its profit after taxes
edged up 5 percent in the second quarter from a year earlier, with
its tobacco, paper and financial services divisions contributing
strong results but its retailing profits declining.
   B.A.T, a British conglomerate, last month won an eight-month
takeover battle for Farmers Group Inc., a major U.S. insurer based
in Los Angeles. The British company paid $5.2 billion for Farmers.
   B.A.T reported Wednesday that its profit for the three months
ended June 30 rose to 254 million British pounds, or about $434
million, from 241 million pounds, or $412 million, in the same
period a year earlier.
   Earnings per share edged up to 16.81 pence, or 29 cents, from
16.16 pence, or 28 cents.
   B.A.T's second-quarter sales rose 4 percent _ to 4.36 billion
pounds, or $7.5 billion, from 4.18 billion pounds, or $7.15 billion.
   The company's retail division, which includes U.S. department
store chain Saks Fifth Avenue, had a poor showing, which B.A.T
attributed to a sluggish and highly competitive market in the
United States.
   In the first six months of the year, B.A.T's net profit rose 8
percent _ to 422 million pounds, or $723 million, from 389 million
pounds, or $665 million.
   First-half earnings per share increased to 28.02 pence, or 48
cents, from 26.09 pence, or 45 cents.
   Sales for the first half grew 6 percent _ to 8.47 billion
pounds, or $14.5 billion, from 7.99 billion pounds, or $13.7
billion.
</TEXT>
