<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-ExportBoom Adv10-11   09-07 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Export Boom, Adv 10-11,0913</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 10-11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Everybody's Exporting These Days, Especially in Rochester</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What has the surge of American exports
meant to Tom Collier, who runs a small company that makes and sells
screws?
   ``I'm taking aspirins every day now,'' he said.
   But he's not complaining. His company, Cam-Tech Industries Inc.,
has doubled its sales this year, increased its employment to 15
from 12 and ``become somebody'' in the world of international trade.
   At Sentry Group, a leading maker of fire-resistant safes and
containers, the boom has made a long-overdue foray into foreign
markets a resounding success. Sales there doubled last year and are
expected to triple this year, said company vice president Doug
Brush.
   ``Our international business has become our top priority,'' he
said.
   There are many similar stories in Rochester, which has become
one of the busiest export centers in the country and the leading
exporting city in New York.
   The city is the home of Eastman Kodak Co., the nation's
ninth-largest exporter, and other large exporters like Xerox Corp.,
which has its largest plant in the area, and Bausch & Lomb Inc.
   But it's the small to medium-size companies that get the most
gain from current economic conditions.
   ``It never ceases to amaze the number of new companies getting
into exporting,'' said Martin Wilner, of Leading Forwarders of
Rochester, a company that finds overseas shipping space for
exporters.
   ``I've been in the business 28 years and we are always coming up
with new clients, especially this year,'' Wilner said.
   Commerce Secretary C. William Verity said in July that for the
first five months of this year, American exports have jumped 31
percent compared with the same period in 1987.
   In June, the most recent month for which statistics are
available, the federal government said exports totaled $26.8
billion, the third highest monthly sales figure on record.
   Last year, Rochester and the surrounding area exported a record
$6.3 billion worth of products, which is more than the overall
totals from 30 different states.
   Only 10 states had higher export sales than Rochester last year.
California led the nation with $27.5 billion, followed by Texas at
$19.7 billion and New York at $15.5 billion.
   ``Exports are more than just a good thing or a nice thing,''
said Colby Chandler, Kodak's chairman and chief executive officer.
``I think it (the export boom) means that they're an integral part
of business, a vital part.''
   He said that the current business conditions and emphasis on
exporting and foreign trade in Rochester, and beyond, will ``not
turn backwards,'' because exporting and importing have become
household terms in business planning.
   Two sure signs that the exporting boom is in full force, at
least in Rochester, according to Fritz Grasberger, director of the
Center for Governmental Research, are an increase in workers
logging overtime and in a shortage of workers for low-paying jobs.
   ``Workers are in demand because manufacturers are trying to take
advantage of new opportunities overseas,'' said Grasberger, who
heads the not-for-profit, local research firm.
   The average work week in March in the Rochester area climbed to
a record 45.4 hours _ its highest level in at least 30 years. The
national average for hours worked in a week is about 39, Grasberger
said.
   ``This is the best economic environment I've ever seen,'' said
Bill Ramage, a labor economist at the state Labor Department in
Rochester. He's been following the Rochester economy since 1978.
   He said the area's manufacturers have stopped tightening their
belts and trimming work forces, partly because of the weak dollar,
and the area's service sector continues to grow.
   Kodak, Rochester's largest employer by far, offers a good
illustration of how the value of the dollar can affect Main Street
USA.
   When the dollar began to rise in the early part of this decade,
Kodak's profits were pared by lost pennies, and then nickels, and
then dimes, on nearly every roll of film it sold overseas.
   The dollar's rise meant Kodak would have to charge more money
for its products in foreign markets in order to make the same
profit, but raising prices in yen, marks, or pounds would send
customers away from Kodak film to competitors' brands.
   So, in an effort to hang onto its customers, Kodak didn't raise
prices and hoped the dollar wouldn't keep getting stronger and keep
costing the company money.
   ``From 1981 into early '86 we estimate that we lost $4 billion
in profits,'' said Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska.
   In addition, the company was forced to lay off more than 10,000
employees, nearly half of them in Rochester, and suffer the first
quarterly financial loss in company history.
   The cutbacks were difficult for this city to cope with,
especially since Rochester's conventional wisdom included that``a
job at Kodak was a job for life.''
   But in 1986, the dollar began to fall, and Kodak began making
more money from its overseas sales. Simply converting foreign
profits into dollars at more favorable exchange rates meant $90
million in extra profits in 1986; $195 million in 1987 and a
projected $260 million this year, if the dollar remains at its
current level.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 10-11</NOTE>
