<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1400EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WPPSSTrial 1stLd-Writethru   09-07 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WPPSS Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru,0724</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giant Fraud Trial Finally Starts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with trial under way; Picks up
4th graf, `The case ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM KLAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The giant Washington Public Power Supply
System fraud trial opened today as defense attorneys argued
unsuccessfully that the judge's trial rules would favor the
plaintiffs.
   Defense attorney Kenneth Kieffer took issue with a portion of
U.S. District Judge William Browning's trial protocol that says
once the examination of a witness has begun ``it will continue
until direct and cross-examination by all parties, on all issues
has concluded.''
   Keiffer said he feared the defense would be unable to put its
case in front of the jury in a logical manner if plaintiffs have
the ability to set the order in which witnesses will appear.
   Plaintiffs' attorney Tom Barr, representing Chemical Bank of New
York, noted the judge's protocol allowed an exception if the
witness elects to appear at the trial rather than be questioned via
a direct television hookup.
   Browning has allowed the use of a satellite hookup in the case
because many witnesses are in the Northwest. The judge denied the
defense motion asking for a change in the protocol.
   Browning has ordered that 20 jurors be seated in the trial,
which could last more than a year. Because it is a civil case, only
six jurors may eventually be called upon to issue a verdict. Jury
selection is scheduled to begin Thursday.
   The case, shifted for trial from Washington state to Tucson
because of pretrial publicity, arose out of the sale of $2.25
billion in bonds to build two nuclear power plants.
   The plants, WPPSS Nos. 4 and 5, were scrapped in January 1982
after being only partially built. In 1983, WPPSS defaulted on the
bonds after the Washington Supreme Court ruled most of the 88
Northwest public utilities investing in the projects had signed
illegal contracts with the power project consortium.
   The default, with 40,000 bond buyers left holding the bag, was
the biggest in the history of the municipal bond market. Of those
bond purchasers, more than 24,000 have filed claims, including
current bondholders represented by Chemical Bank of New York and
original buyers who retain a fraud claim though they have sold
their bonds.
   In addition to the number of plaintiffs, other big figures in
the case include the more than 100 attorneys, the length of time to
trial and legal fees preparing for trial: more than $150 million.
   The case could have been even bigger.
   Dozens of defendants, originally numbering more than 100, have
dropped out during the past year, with settlements totaling about
$350 million. Much of that was paid by insurance companies.
   Left are one Oregon and 20 Washington public utilities, which
own a 67 percent share in the two nuclear plants; two engineering
firms and a financial advisory firm.
   The 21 utilities serve about 650,000 customers, who would
possibly have to bear the brunt of a jury ruling against
defendants. Utilities representing 500,000 other homes in the
Northwest have settled.
   Settlements were being made almost up to the time of trial.
Holiday or not, an agreement between plaintiff attorneys and the
Seattle engineering firm of R.W. Beck was announced Labor Day by
settlement master Junius Hoffman, a University of Arizona law
professor appointed by Browning more than 18 months ago to try to
encourage settlements.
   The case also lacks some of the big money defendants in the
original lawsuits. Wall Street bond underwriters paid $92 million
to settle their share.
   The Bonneville Power Administration, a federal power marketing
agency in the Northwest, was reluctantly dropped from the case by
Browning. He said the law was clear that BPA officials had acted
properly in encouraging construction of WPPSS plants Nos. 4 and 5.
   WPPSS attempted to build five nuclear power plants in the 1970s
to serve Northwest customers. Of those, one plant, WPPSS No. 2 at
the Hanford nuclear reservation, is operating.
   Two others, WPPSS Nos. 1 and 3, were mothballed under
construction delays five years ago.
   Bonds sold to build those three plants are paid for through BPA.
However, plants Nos. 4 and 5 never enjoyed BPA protection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1413EDT</FILEID>
