<DOCNO> AP880907-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Conflicts-Cases Adv11   09-07 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Conflicts-Cases, Adv 11,0478</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday Sept. 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>When Businesses and Their Advisers Come Into Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Corporate Conflicts</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A number of corporations have raised the conflict-of-interest
question in their dealings with bankers and attorneys.
   Among some recent confrontations between companies and the
professionals they once dealt with are:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>USG-Merrill Lynch</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   USG Corp. filed suit against Merrill Lynch & Co. in May,
charging Merrill used confidential information about USG while
representing Desert Partners in a hostile bid for the company.
Merrill had helped USG sell debt securities in its 1984 acquisition
of Masonite Corp. and served as its investment adviser in 1987,
when it acquired DAP Inc. The suit was settled in July; terms were
not disclosed. USG undertook a costly restructuring to fend off the
raiders.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>GenCorp-Shearson</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   GenCorp Inc. charged in a 1987 federal lawsuit that Shearson
Lehman Brothers improperly used confidential information in
advising Texas oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown in their
hostile bid for GenCorp. In 1986 GenCorp discussed with Shearson
the possible buyout of its General Tire Canada Ltd. and aerospace
subsidiaries. Neither deal was consummated, and Shearson did not
collect any fees. Shearson's motion to dismiss the suit is pending.
GenCorp evaded the takeover by reorganizing.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Interco-Chase Manhattan</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Interco Inc. assailed Chase Manhattan Bank in August for
agreeing to help finance a hostile bid for the company launched by
the Rales brothers of Washington, D.C. Interco said Chase was its
principal international banker and that it had relied on the bank
for other assistance over the years. Interco stopped short of
filing a lawsuit but is in the process of terminating its
relationships with Chase. The Rales' tender offer is under way.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Corning Glass Works-J.P. Morgan & Co.</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Corning Glass Works Inc. reached a definitive agreement in March
to acquire International Clinical Laboratories Inc., but SmithKline
Beckman Corp. stepped in and ultimately outbid Corning. The
situation was muddied by the fact that Corning was a long-time
Morgan client and that its chairman, James Houghton, is a Morgan
director. Nonetheless, Morgan emerged as investment adviser to
SmithKline.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Murray Ohio Manufacturing-Sullivan & Cromwell</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   In early 1987, the New York law firm Sullivan & Cromwell helped
Murray Ohio Manufacturing Co. adopt an anti-takeover strategy.
Little more than a year later, the firm represented AB Electrolux
of Sweden, which launched a hostile bid for Murray Ohio. Sullivan &
Cromwell withdrew from representing Electrolux even before a
three-judge panel acknowledged a conflict. The panel said, however,
that no transfer of confidential information had taken place. In
June Murray Ohio agreed to be acquired by Tomkins PLC of Britain.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday Sept. 11</NOTE>
