<1ST_LINE>u f PM-InsiderTrading-Wang 2ndLd-Writethru   09-07 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Insider Trading-Wang, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ex-Morgan Stanley Analyst Pleads Guilty in Insider Trading Case,
Deal Seen</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-11 UPDATE with Wang's guilty plea, picks up 10th
graf pvs, Earlier today...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former junior securities analyst pleaded
guilty today to the first criminal charges stemming from what the
government has called the second-biggest insider trading scandal in
Wall Street history.
   Stephen Sui-Kuan Wang Jr., 24, a one-time intern of the
prominent brokerage Morgan Stanley & Co., also pleaded guilty to a
single charge in connection with his role in a previously
undisclosed insider trading scheme.
   Wang, wearing a charcoal gray suit and spectacles, entered his
guilty pleas before U.S. District Judge Kevin Duffy in Manhattan,
who set sentencing for Oct. 19. If convicted of all three counts,
Wang faces a maximum sentence of 15 years in prison and $750,000 in
fines.
   ``Was there any doubt in your mind that what you were doing was
wrong?'' Duffy asked Wang, who stood during the proceeding in
Manhattan federal court. He replied, ``There was no doubt in my
mind.''
   The charges were announced earlier today by U.S. Attorney
Rudolph W. Giuliani, who said that from June 1987 to July 1988,
Wang participated in an insider trading scheme with Taiwanese-born
businessman Fred C. Lee.
   Giuliani said the scheme involved trading in the securities of
more than 14 companies involved in mergers and takeovers where
Morgan Stanley played a role.
   Lee, who has residences in Taiwan, Hong Kong and the United
States, has been said by the Securities and Exchange Commission to
have traded stocks on the tips provided by Wang and netted at least
$19 million in illicit profits. He allegedly shared at least
$200,000 of the money with Wang.
   The SEC has frozen the assets of both men and sought repayment
of the $19 million plus triple damages for a total of $76 million.
That would be the second-largest amount seized by the SEC in an
insider trading case since master speculator Ivan Boesky
surrendered $100 million nearly two years ago.
   Giuliani also said that in addition to the scheme with Lee, Wang
was charged with participating in an earlier scheme to engage in
insider trading with an individual living in the Chicago area
starting in June 1986, when Wang started working at Morgan Stanley.
   The U.S. attorney declined to further identify the individual in
the second scheme but said the person was not one of Wang's
relatives.
   Giuliani said Wang would cooperate with the government and that
the investigation is continuing, an indication that others might be
charged.
   Earlier today, Wang pleaded innocent to one count each of mail
fraud, wire fraud and securities fraud before U.S. Magistrate
Barbara Lee in Manhattan, but the move was a technical prelude to
his subsequent guilty plea.
   Under federal criminal procedure, guilty pleas cannot be entered
before U.S. magistrates, and the move is often an indication that a
defendant has negotiated a plea agreement with prosecutors.
   The U.S. magistrate set Wang's bail at $250,000.
</TEXT>
