<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed; Wheat Retreats From Summer's Highs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as profit-taking and
harvest pressure weakened markets buoyed by rumors of new export
demand, analysts said.
   Wheat finished slightly higher but below the day's highs, which
matched the year's top prices for December and March deliveries.
Rumors that the Soviet Union had purchased 2 million metric tons of
subsidized U.S. wheat supported the market, analysts said.
   ``The wheat shows excellent strength _ it's acting very well,''
said John Frazier, grain specialist with Balfour Maclaine Corp. in
Chicago.
   Soybeans ended mixed due to pressure from the advancing harvest.
Many farmers are cleaning out their bins and selling last year's
soybeans to make room for the new crop, analysts said. Soybeans for
November delivery hit $9.05 a bushel during the session but closed
below $9.
   Corn finished mostly lower in the absence of influential news,
but rumors of export sales limited losses, Frazier said.
   At the close, wheat was 1\ cents to 2{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $4.12 a bushel; corn was 3
cents lower to } cent higher with September at $2.92 a bushel; oats
were unchanged to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.69{ a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents lower to 9 cents higher with September at
$8.83 a bushel.
</TEXT>
