<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DebtReport     09-07 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debt Report,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panel Says New Loans Won't Solve Third World Debt Problem</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks and debtor nations should renegotiate
existing loans rather than seek new ones to help ease the $1
trillion Third World debt problem, a panel of top bankers,
economists and labor leaders urged in a report released Wednesday.
   The 39-page report by the Economic Policy Council of the United
Nations Association departs from the plan of former Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, which suggested pumping more money
into struggling nations to get them back on their feet and attract
foreign investments.
   The Baker Plan had helped bring more money into a number of less
developed countries over the past two years, but UNA panel said
that was mainly because interest rates were lower, making
debt-servicing costs more manageable.
   ``Large new-lending programs may be difficult to secure under
current market conditions,'' the report said.
   Many commercial banks have become reluctant to issue more loans
after some debtor countries, such as Brazil, stopped making loan
payments. Banks suffered huge losses last year after adding to
their loan-loss reserves to cover the shaky Third World debt.
   In addition, many banks are now faced with new capital adequacy
requirements, and ``a large block of problem loans to debtor
countries makes raising capital difficult and expensive,'' the
report noted.
   The report said restructuring loans so payments are reduced will
not only reduce outstanding claims against a country but aid in its
economic recovery.
   The report also urges debtor countries to undertake domestic
reforms to sustain economic growth.
   ``Economic success over a period of time also requires a level
of public confidence that grows out of efficient, uncorrupt
leadership and a political system that is reponsive to the popular
will,'' it said.
   Among its other suggestions, the UNA panel strongly urged
Congress to increase the U.S. contribution to the multinational
World Bank, which provides funding to Third World countries.
   The bank wants the United States to pledge about $70 million a
year over the next six years for a badly needed increase in its
capital. So far, about 140 of the 151 governments that own the bank
have decided to contribute.
   The UNA panel said talks should continue regularly between
multinational institutions like the World Bank, commercial banks
and debtor countries.
   ``It's been an impression ... that there is more and more debt
fatigue on the part of the key players,'' said Anthony Salomon,
former president of the New York Federal Reserve Bank and
co-chairman of the UNA panel. ``You will not see or hear one
concrete black-and-white plan.''
   Besides Salomon, others serving on the 27-member panel, which
began reviewing the international debt problem eight months ago,
included: Rodney Wagner, vice chairman of Morgan Guaranty Trust and
panel co-chairman; Tom Johnson, president of Chemical Bank; Pedro
Malan, executive director of the World Bank; Frederick Getzelman,
executive vice president of Philadelphia National Bank; Henry
Kaufman, economist and president of Henry Kaufman & Co.; and Albert
Shanker, president of the American Federation of Teacher AFL-CIO.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1731EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NYSE-ForeignBonds     09-07 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NYSE-Foreign Bonds,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NYSE To Begin Listing ADRs of Foreign Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange said Wednesday it
will be the first U.S. marketplace to offer trading in American
Depositary Receipts for foreign debt securities, beginning with
French Treasury bonds.
   American Depositary Receipts, or ADRs, are certificates issued
by U.S. banks that allow investors to buy foreign stocks with
dollars. This is the first time they have been used for debt
securities, the NYSE said.
   The Big Board said it expected the bonds to be listed by the end
of the month, pending regulatory approval, and said it expected
other foreign governments and corporations would follow suit.
   Credit Lyonnais in Paris is the custodian bank for the French
bonds, while its U.S. subsidiary CL GlobalPartners Securities Corp.
is marketing the American Depositary Receipts and Bank of New York
is the depositary bank.
   The New York Stock Exchange already offers 2,600 issues of bonds
with a par value of more than $32 billion, mostly corporate issues.
Some foreign government and corporate bonds are also traded, but
those are issues that were originally issued in the United States.
</TEXT>
