<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GoldCircleSale     09-07 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gold Circle Sale,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau To Sell 76 Gold Circle and Richway Stores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has agreed to sell all 76 of its
Gold Circle and Richway stores for more than $325 million, the
Toronto-based retailing and real estate company said Wednesday.
   The buyer, Kimco Development Corp., a privately held owner and
manager of shopping centers, said it has agreed to sell 31 of the
stores to Dayton Hudson Corp. and to lease 35 to Hills Department
Stores and two to K mart Corp.
   Buyers or operators are still being sought for the other eight
stores, according to Kimco, which is based in Roslyn, N.Y.
   The Gold Circle and Richway stores are part of Federated
Department Stores Inc., which Campeau bought in May for $8.8
billion.
   The sale does not include the warehouses and central offices,
which will be sold separately. The inventory of the stores will be
disposed of over the next 12 weeks.
   The stores being leased by Hills are in New York, Ohio and
Kentucky, while K mart is leasing a pair of stores in Ohio. The
stores being bought by Dayton Hudson are in Georgia, Florida, North
Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee and Kentucky. They are being
purchased by the Target Stores division of Dayton Hudson.
   Hills and Target said they would reopen the leased stores under
their own names by next spring.
   Campeau has been steadily selling assets to pay for the $8.8
billion purchase of Federated. It also owns Allied Stores Corp.,
which was bought in late 1986 for $3.4 billion.
   Among the units sold have been Filene's, Foley's, I. Magnin,
Bullock's-Bullock's Wilshire, Brooks Brothers and Filene's
Basement. Also on the auction block are Children's Place, Main
Street and Ann Taylor.
</TEXT>
