<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-High-DefinitionTV     09-07 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-High-Definition TV,0615</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Members Of Congress Say U.S. Should Be In Advanced Television</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress expressed concern
Wednesday that America's electronics industry could suffer
irreparably if it is left behind in the race to develop a new
high-quality television system.
   The result, they said, could cost the country in many ways _ an
even higher trade deficit and thousands of jobs lost, as well as
the loss of potential military, medical, consumer and other
applications that are expected to come with development of the
technology.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., chairman of the
telecommunications subcommittee, asked electronics industry trade
associations to submit reports to the panel by January outlining
steps the government could take to ensure American involvement in
high-definition TV.
   Suggestions have ranged from antitrust exemptions for U.S.
companies involved in research and development on high-definition
TV to appropriating Pentagon funds for research on it because of
the potential military applications of the technology, he said.
   Over the last decade, the United States has shifted from a major
supplier to a net importer of electronics products, he noted.
   ``HDTV could make a bad situation worse,'' Markey said at the
final of three hearings on high-definition TV, called HDTV.
   High-definition TV produces clearer, brighter images on a wider
TV screen with high-quality sound. The Japanese have been
developing HDTV for nearly 20 years and the Europeans have been
working on their own system for several years. Both systems are
incompatible with U.S. television broadcasting.
   The Federal Communications Commission last week set preliminary
guidelines that will allow research to proceed toward establishing
an American HDTV system. Under the FCC guidelines, a U.S. system
must be able to be received on existing TV sets so current
equipment would not become obsolete. But to receive improved
picture quality, viewers would have to buy a new TV set.
   Richard Elkus Jr., chairman of the Prometrix Corp. and
testifying for the American Electronics Association, said advanced
TV offers the U.S. electronics industry an opportunity to rebound
in a market projected to reach $20 billion in U.S. sales and $40
billion worldwide by the year 2007.
   It also will have ripple effects in other areas, he said. For
example, HDTV products will use a large supply of advanced
semiconductors and HDTV will have applications in military and
medical fields, he said in testimony submitted to the panel.
   He added, however, that regardless of what standard the United
States selects, it won't stop the Japanese from entering the U.S.
market.
   More important than selecting a standard, he said, is government
and industry coming up with a strategy to put American companies
back on the electronics manufacturing track and to develop
marketing and distribition systems that will rival the Japanese.
   About 20 advanced-TV systems are under development and competing
to be designated as the U.S. HDTV standard.
   Richard Wiley, a former FCC chairman and chairman of the FCC's
advisory committee on advanced TV technologies, said his panel's
testing of the systems could begin by the end of the year and will
take a year and a half to complete.
   ``This is not going to be something you're going to solve
overnight,'' he said referring to the selection of a standard
system, the involvement of U.S. electronics companies in the
emerging industry and the gradual replacement of TV sets by
American viewers.
   Wiley estimated that the United States had ``a year or two'' to
establish a national HDTV policy, but Markey said, ``I'm not as
optimistic as you are in the time we have before us.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880907-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1734EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TWA-Icahn     09-07 0712</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TWA-Icahn,0743</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TWA Shareholders Approve Icahn's Plan; Pilots Sue to Block
Privatization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Trans World Airlines Inc. on
Wednesday overwhelmingly approved Chairman Carl C. Icahn's proposal
to buy their shares and take the nation's seventh-largest airline
private.
   But opposition to the move mounted among TWA employees as the
3,300-member pilots union sued Icahn in New York State Supreme
Court to block the privatization.
   At a special meeting, TWA shareholders not affiliated with Icahn
voted 3,714,740 shares in favor of his privatization plan and
146,061 against. Icahn voted his shares with the majority, making a
final vote of 27,159,478 for and 146,061 against.
   The approval had been widely expected by financial analysts and
TWA employees.
   ``We've gone through quite a bit together,'' Icahn told
shareholders before the vote was taken. ``We of course were beset
by problems ... (but) I left my money in to keep the company
running.''
   Icahn, a wily takeover specialist who took the reins of TWA a
little more than two years ago, controls the airline through a
complex myriad of financial entities that own around 77 percent of
its 30.5 million common shares outstanding.
   He dropped a similar proposal to go private after last October's
stock market crash, then came back with a revised bid in April.
   Under the plan, shareholders not affiliated with Icahn would
receive for each share of common stock $20 in cash and $30 in face
amount of 12 percent notes due in 2008.
   Airline industry analysts estimate the bid puts a value of
around $40 a share, or $304.8 million, on the TWA shares that Icahn
doesn't already own. TWA stock closed at $36.75 Wednesday on the
New York Stock Exchange, up 37{ cents a share.
   Entities controlled by Icahn would receive, for each common
share, $20 in cash and a new issue of preferred stock and a
retained share of common stock.
   After completion of the transaction, expected in a month or so,
Icahn and the entities controlled by him would own about 90 percent
of TWA's stock. The remaining shares would be owned by an employee
stock ownership plan.
   TWA also has said that upon completion of the deal, it intends
to pay off at least $64.5 million of its $2.3 billion debt, and
seek the consent of holders of some preferred stock to eliminate
voting rights on that stock and to exchange other preferred issues
for 12 percent notes.
   Icahn said TWA will have about $1 billion in cash after the
deal, an unspecified portion of which will be used to purchase new
aircraft to upgrade the international carrier's fleet.
   At the start of the meeting, Capt. Thomas Ashwood, master
chairman of the TWA pilots union, attempted to serve Icahn with
legal papers related to the union's suit against the privatization.
The papers were accepted by TWA General Counsel Mark Buckstein as
some attending the meeting applauded.
   In its suit, the pilots union alleges that Icahn's plan to go
private is a breach of the agreements it made with him during his
takeover of the carrier. As part of those agreements, the pilots
accepted a 26 percent pay cut, work rule changes and other
concessions they say amount to $300 million over three years.
   The pilots are seeking an injunction blocking the privatization
and a court order enforcing their contracts.
   ``We won't stand idly by while Carl Icahn strips our airline of
assets and keeps it from growing financially stronger, from buying
airplanes and from improving service to our passengers because of
heavy debt,'' Ashwood said in a statement.
   The pilots' action intensified union opposition to Icahn's plan.
Last week, the union representing TWA flight attendants asked the
Department of Transportation to block the privatization and freeze
the airline's assets while it investigates Icahn's fitness to
continue managing the airline.
   The machinists and flight attendants at TWA also plan to file
lawsuits similar to that brought by the pilots union, Ashwood said.
   Icahn bristled at criticism leveled at him during the meeting by
a representative of the flight attendants.
   ``We will not be dictated to by employees concerning how to run
this airline,'' he said.
   After the meeting, Icahn told reporters he was disturbed by the
pilots' lawsuit.
</TEXT>
