<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 1746EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-07 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Weaker Against Yen; Traders Await New Economic Data</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precede LONDON, BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mixed against major currencies
Wednesday, losing ground against a rising Japanese yen, as
investors turned their attention to economic data due out later
this week.
   Gold prices also were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
said gold was bid at $427.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from
$426.60 late Tuesday.
   Currency analysts said activity in the foreign-exchange market
was focused on the yen after reports from Tokyo that the Japanese
economy is in danger of overheating. The yen strengthened in
overnight trading in Japan, continued in European trading and
closed near its highs of the day in New York.
   ``The market is taking it as a sign that Japan will be quick in
moving interest rates if the yen begins to weaken again,'' said
James T. McGroarty, an analyst at Discount Corp.
   Currency brokers said that Wednesday's rise in the dollar
against most other major currencies after a huge drop on Friday
reaffirmed that the summer-long rally in the U.S. currency is not
over. They said the dollar has now returned to a more realistic
trading range.
   On Friday, the dollar plunged after the government released
statistics showing unemployment rose in August. The report
suggested the economy was softening and that inflation pressures
could force the Federal Reserve to lower interest rates. Lower
interest rates make dollar-denominated securities less attractive
to foreign investors.
   Friday's selloff was followed by a further weakening of the
dollar in foreign markets Monday, while U.S. currency markets were
closed, and on Tuesday.
   ``It was a pause in the dollar's strength based on weaker
economic fundamentals,'' said Ronald Holzer, chief currency dealer
with Harris Trust & Co. ``Impressions that inflation will be stable
and therefore the economy is slowing down shouldn't hurt the
dollar, given that interest rates are still higher.''
   Analysts said investors were now awaiting new economic news due
out in the next several days. The Producer Price Index, an
important measure of inflation, is scheduled for release on Friday,
followed by the U.S. trade deficit figures due out next Wednesday.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell sharply to close at 134.30 yen, down 1.30 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.67 yen. And in New York, the
dollar fell to 133.325 yen from 134.925 late Tuesday.
   In London, it cost $1.7060 to buy one pound, more expensive than
$1.7035 late Tuesday. Later in New York, it cost $1.7080 to buy one
pound, compared with Tuesday's rate of $1.70365.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with levels late
Tuesday included: 1.84125 West German marks, up from 1.84015;
1.5530 Swiss francs, unchanged; 1.23755 Canadian dollars, up from
1.23405; 6.2760 French francs, up from 6.2695; 1,377.375 Italian
lire, down from 1,378.00.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.8435 West German marks, up from 1.8425; 1.5545
Swiss francs, up from 1.5525; 6.2795 French francs, up from 6.2715;
2.0810 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0820; 1,376.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,377.65; and 1.2392 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2340.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $426.70 a troy ounce
from $428.10 bid late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid
$427.50, compared with $428 bid late Tuesday. Earlier, in Hong
Kong, gold rose $1.04 to close at a bid $430.19.
   But on the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold closed up at
$428.10 a troy ounce, compared with $426.70 late Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.52 a troy ounce, compared
with Tuesday's $6.56.
   On the New York Comex, silver for current delivery rose to
$6.546 a troy ounce, compared with Tuesday's $6.485.
</TEXT>
