<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Earns-Gulf&Western     09-07 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Gulf & Western,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf & Western Inc. Third-Quarter Profit Up 21 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf & Western said Wednesday its third-quarter
profit rose by 20.6 percent from a year earlier, led by strong
gains in its publishing and consumer finance units.
   Gulf & Western also announced it had adopted a shareholder
rights plan aimed at making any hostile takeover prohibitively
expensive, in order to protect the rights of its shareholders.
   For the three-month period ended July 31, Gulf & Western
reported its after-tax earnings were $123.8 million, or $1.30 a
share, up from $102.6 million, or 83 cents a share, in the same
period a year ago.
   The company said its revenue rose 8.3 percent to $1.3 billion in
the third quarter, from $1.2 billion in the year-earlier period.
   Gulf & Western said healthy gains in its publishing-information
and consumer and commercial finance units contributed strongly to
the third quarter gains. Its publishing-information services
include Simon & Schuster and Prentice Hall.
   The company said its entertainment division, which includes
Paramount Pictures, contributed significant operating income in the
period.
   For the first nine months of this year, Gulf & Western's net
earnings rose 6.9 percent to $240.2 million, or $2 per share, from
$224.6 million, or $1.81 a share, in the same period of 1987. Its
revenue during the same period totaled $3.6 billion, up 12.5
percent from $3.2 billion in the year-earlier period.
   Regarding the shareholder rights plan, Gulf & Western said it
was ``not aware of any effort to acquire the company'' but believed
the plan would help prevent an acquisition of the company ``at a
price not reflective of its fair value.''
   The ``poison pill'' takeover defense essentially would allow
Gulf & Western shareholders to purchase shares of a hostile
acquirer at a deep discount price, or to purchase Gulf & Western
shares at a discount if a hostile suitor acquired 15 percent or
more of the company's outstanding shares.
</TEXT>
