<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BFI-Ruckelshaus     09-07 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BFI-Ruckelshaus,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former EPA Chief Named To Head Waste Disposal Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William D. Ruckelshaus, who served two terms as
head of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, on Wednesday was
elected chairman of the board and chief executive officer of
Browning-Ferris Industries, Inc., one of the world's largest waste
disposal companies.
   Ruckelshaus has been on the Browning-Ferris board of directors
since June 1987. He succeeds Harry J. Phillips Sr., who will become
chairman of the Houston-based company's executive committee.
   Besides stints at the EPA, Ruckleshaus has been deputy attorney
general and acting director of the FBI. He also has served in the
House of Representatives of his home state of Indiana and as chief
counsel for the Indiana attorney general's office.
   ``This country is facing serious environmental problems in the
years ahead that will demand innovative, effective and efficient
solutions,'' Ruckelshaus said.
   ``BFI is well situated to participate in helping clean up our
nation's environment, and at the same time continue its impressive
record of growth.''
   Phillips, who held the top job at the company for 11 years, said
Browning-Ferris could benefit from fresh, new leadership and a
broader perspective.
   ``Our company and our industry has become more and more involved
in the public, political and regulatory arenas,'' he said.
   ``The ideal person to lead BFI in the days ahead should, in
addition to administrative and business skills, possess strong
talents, experience and comfort in dealing with issues within these
other, diverse arenas...an individual with a widely recognized
reputation of exceptional integrity.
   ``Given these characteristics, I felt that exactly the right
person to fill this position was Bill Ruckelshaus.''
   Browning-Ferris, whose revenue rose from $300 million to
approximately $2 billion annually during Phillips' tenure, has
subsidiaries that provide collection, transfer, processing,
recovery and disposal of solid wastes and chemical wastes for
commercial, industrial and governmental customers. It also provides
solid waste collection and disposal services for residential
customers.
   It has more than 18,000 employees who work at affiliates in 225
locations in the United States, Australia, Canada, Kuwait, Puerto
Rico, Saudi Arabia, Spain, the United Kingdom and Venezuela.
</TEXT>
