<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FedIntervention     09-07 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fed Intervention,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Sold $2.9 Billion To Restrain Dollar's Rise In May-July
Period</HEAD>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. monetary authorities sold $2.9 billion in
the foreign exchange markets to restrain the dollar's rise in the
May-July period, the Federal Reserve Bank of New York said
Wednesday.
   All of dollars were sold to buy West German marks, a currency
that was under heavy selling pressure during the period.
   The New York Fed said it did all of its dollar-selling in the
final 24 business days of the period, from June 27 to July 31, when
it intervened on 16 days in coordination with other central banks.
   During the three months, the dollar rose about 12 percent
against the mark, returning the dollar to its level of about a year
ago. The dollar also rose about 6.5 percent against the Japanese
yen and 9.8 percent against the British pound, but remained below
its year-ago levels against them.
   The New York Fed buys and sells currencies on behalf of both the
Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department.
   The bank does not comment on what it has done in the currency
markets since the end of the reporting period. It also does not
comment on the activities of other central banks.
   However, during the May-July period and in a number of trading
sessions since then there has been wide speculation in the markets
that the Fed and other central banks were intervening against the
dollar.
</TEXT>
