<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TextileBill 1stLd-Writethru   09-07 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Textile Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Decides to Force Vote on Textile Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead to reflect later debate; updates in grafs 10-17
with fresh quotes; picks up 16th graf pvs, ``The textile ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate shrugged off charges it was
reverting to ``shameless'' trade protectionism Wednesday and moved
to force a vote on imposing new curbs on textile, apparel and
non-rubber footwear imports.
   ``This is about the survival of the textile industry,'' the
sponsor, Sen. Ernest F. Hollings, D-S.C., told the Senate before it
voted 68-29 to limit debate on the bill to 30 hours and thus avert
any filibuster.
   The action represented a step forward for the textile, apparel
and shoe industries. But prospects for the House-passed bill remain
clouded with a month to go before Congress adjourns to campaign
full time.
   Had the Senate not acted to invoke cloture, or limit debate,
free-trade forces seeking to prevent a vote on the bill itself
almost certainly would have staged a filibuster. Preventing that
required three-fifths support.
   The bill would freeze this year's textile and apparel imports at
1987 levels and permit growth of one percent annually in the years
ahead. It would bar increases in the level of non-rubber footwear
imports.
   The president would be authorized to negotiate tariff cuts to
compensate countries hurt by the tightened restrictions.
   President Reagan vetoed an earlier version of the legislation in
1985 to the dismay of manufacturers and a number of labor unions.
He called the measure protectionism that would raise prices, narrow
consumer choices and actually cost more jobs that it would save in
the textile, apparel and shoe industries.
   The industries were rocked by a wave of imports in the early
1980s and have been pushing ever since for congressional
restrictions.
   Critics have been complaining, however, that the textile
industry's distress is a thing of the past and that, in large
measure thanks to competition from Asian manufacturers, American
companies are more productive and competitive than ever before.
   After voting to invoke cloture, the Senate spent most of
Wednesday afternoon debating amendments designed by critics to
sidetrack the bill. Lawmakers planned to resume action on the bill
Thursday.
   In each case, lawmakers voted to table, or kill, amendments
offered by free-trade critics of the textile bill.
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, sponsored an amendment to exempt
``workers coveralls, uniforms, work shoes and work boots.'' He said
it would ``help the workingman.''
   ``This amendment is ludicrous,'' retorted Hollings. It was
tabled 62-28.
   Both sides also got onto a familiar merry-go-round over just how
much the nation's textile companies earn. The claims and
counterclaims have become a regular feature of textile debates.
   Sen. Bob Packwood, R-Ore., a critic of the proposed new curbs,
told the Senate that pre-tax earnings of U.S. textile companies
zoomed 26 percent last year. That brought Sen. Strom Thurmond,
R-S.C., an industry champion, to the floor with figures suggesting
a 12 percent drop in profits thus far this year.
   Packwood retorted that industry efforts to win new relief from
foreign competition were ``shameless.''
   Textile-state senators sat stony faced through the remarks but
retorted afterward that the textile industry's problems were a
serious matter.
   ``The textile and apparel industries will be extinct in a few
years unless the flooding of our markets is stopped,'' said
Thurmond.
   American apparel makers have not fared as well as textile
manufacturers, whose plants have undergone a broad-scale facelift
in recent years.
   Automated machinery that has drastically reduced the manpower
needs of fabric makers still has no parallel in the clothing
industry. Thus Asian apparel plants where wages are low by U.S.
standards in many cases remain able to turn out products with price
tags well below those of American products.
</TEXT>
