<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AmericanSavings     09-07 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Savings,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parent Company of S&L in Federal Bailout Filed for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial Corp. of America, said Wednesday
it would file for bankruptcy, a move widely expected after the
federal bailout of FCA's subsidiary, American Savings & Loan
Association.
   The development did not affect customers' accounts at the 186
California branches of American Savings, the nation's
second-largest savings and loan.
   FCA announced its board of directors authorized filing of a
petition for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of the
federal bankruptcy law. A filing is to be made this week.
   Also Wednesday, William Popejoy, FCA chairman and chief
executive officer, resigned his position to head a new American
Savings under control of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board.
   Both actions stem from a bank board decision Tuesday to place
American Savings into a temporary receivership _ part of a $2
billion federal bailout plan that will turn control of American
over to an investor group led by Texan Robert M. Bass.
   In effect, the receivership creates a new, federally chartered
American Savings and severs all ties between the S&L and FCA.
   Deposits at American Savings continue to be insured up to
$100,000 by the Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp.
Additionally, federal regulators several months ago took the
unusual step of guaranteeing deposits larger than $100,000 in
effort to bolster confidence in the long-troubled S&L.
   While depositors and some creditors are protected, stockholders
in FCA saw their investments wiped out by the federal action, which
does not provide for compensation from American to FCA or its
shareholders.
   The bank board agreed Monday to turn control of the new American
over to the Bass Group. Bass agreed to pump $550 million cash into
American.
   The deal, the biggest rescue of a troubled thrift, calls for the
bank board to inject an estimated $1.5 billion in cash into
American over the next 10 years, and to provide $500 million in
promissory notes. The first cash infusion _ of $250 million _ was
made Tuesday.
   Popejoy, 50, was brought in by the bank board to head American
in 1984, at the start of an extended attempt to let the S&L wok its
way out of trouble.
   American faltered after several years of rapid growth under the
former management. Its problems include billions of dollars in
loans made to shaky real estate ventures in California, Texas and
elsewhere. Many of those loans are delinquent or in foreclosure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
