<1ST_LINE>u f AM-BankofNewYork     09-07 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank of New York,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fed Gives Bank of New York More Time To Complete Irving
Acquisition Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board on Wednesday granted
Bank of New York Co. up to an additional 90 days to complete its
effort to acquire Irving Bank Corp.
   The ruling was a new blow to Irving's nearly year-long struggle
to avoid an unfriendly takeover by Bank of New York.
   Irving's hopes to fend of Bank of New York faded last week when
Banca Commerciale Italiana dropped its friendly offer of $840
million, $84 a share, for 51 percent of Irving's stock. The
Milan-based bank pulled out after an unfavorable Fed ruling on Aug.
19.
   Before Bank of New York can press on with its $1.4 billion
offer, valued at about $70 a share, it must win a ruling from a New
York appeals court affirming a lower court decision in late July
that overturned Irving's anti-takeover defense. The appeals court
has received briefs from the two sides and has scheduled a hearing
for Friday.
   The Fed, in a letter to H. Rodgin Cohen, an attorney
representing Bank of New York, gave the bank until 30 days after
the court ruling to wrap up the deal. But, it said, the extension
would expire within 90 days, whether or not the court rules.
   The Fed, on Feb. 25, originally granted Bank of New York until
May 24 to finish the deal, and has now extended the deadline three
times.
   After the court ruling, Bank of New York is required to consult
with the Fed before acquiring more than 5 percent of Irving. It
already has a 4.9 percent stake. The Fed said it would give the
case expedited consideration.
   The letter also rejected an Irving Bank contention that could
have forced Bank of New York to make a new application to the Fed
for permission to acquire Irving.
   Because of New York state law, Bank of New York may be forced to
maintain Irving as a separate subsidiary, rather than merge the two
organizations. Irving had argued that Bank of New York's
application to the Fed was for a merger only and would be invalid
if Irving remained intact as a subsidiary.
   ``We're very pleased at the extension. And ... we extend an
invitation to Irving's board to enter into substantial and
meaningful negotations with no preconditions,'' said Owen Brady, a
Bank of New York vice president.
   The two banks are both based in New York City and both have
about $23 billion in assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
