<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Resorts-Griffin     09-07 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resorts-Griffin,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resorts International Sale One Step Closer To Completion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Entertainer Merv Griffin's plan to
purchase Resorts International Inc. moved a step closer to
completion Wednesday after a shareholder lawsuit was settled.
   The Delaware Chancery Court found the $36-a-share tender offer
price offered to holders of Class A shares ``is both generous and
fair and that the settlement must be approved notwithstanding
several objections to it.''
   Griffin made the tender offer in his bid to take control of the
gaming and real estate company. Developer Donald Trump has agreed
to sell all his shares of Resorts' Class B stock, which has 100
times the voting power of Class A stock.
   As part of the deal, Griffin would pay Trump $63 million to
terminate his management contract with Resorts, and Trump would pay
$255 million for Resorts' incomplete Taj Mahal casino project next
door.
   The Atlantic City Housing Authority has already approved the
deal between Trump and Griffin, through which Griffin will assume
Resorts' housing obligations.
   However, the state Casino Control Commission must still approve
the deal and give Griffin interim authority to operate the casino.
   Gaming officials in the Bahamas must also approve the sale,
because Resorts International has a property there.
   More than 81 percent of Resorts' Class A shares already have
been tendered to Griffin, according to Trump's statement.
</TEXT>
