<1ST_LINE>u f AM-InsiderTrading-Posner     09-07 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Insider Trading-Posner,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Posner: Dropout To Takeover Artist To Working Bread Lines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. DICKERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insider trading charges leveled Wednesday against
Victor Posner are the latest in a string of legal and business
problems dogging the Miami Beach tycoon, a high-school dropout who
amassed a multimillion-dollar fortune in real estate and corporate
takeovers.
   Posner and his son Stephen were among those named in a
Securities and Exchange Commission civil insider-trading complaint
filed in New York against the investment firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., the head of its junk bond trading unit, Michael
Milken, and others.
   The complaint alleges Posner arranged for now-jailed former
speculator Ivan Boesky to buy stock in Fischbach Corp. that
secretly actually would be controlled by Milken, Drexel and the
Posners, in order to aid Posner's attempted takeover of the company.
   The Posners had not seen the complaint and had no comment, said
Renee Mottram, a spokeswoman at Posner's beachfront corporate
headquarters.
   Wednesday's charges came just two weeks after a judge rejected
prosecution complaints that a tax fraud sentence leveled on Posner
in February amounted to a slap on the wrist.
   Posner, 69, was sentenced to pay fines of $4 million, donate $3
million for a study on the homeless and perform 20 hours of
community service a week for 5 years. He pleaded no contest a year
ago to evading $1.2 million in federal income taxes by inflating
the value of 22 acres he donated to Miami Christian College.
   The crusty, white-haired mogul, whose plethora of holdings
included controlling interest in companies that owned Royal Crown
Cola and Arby's, is performing his community service by helping out
on the bread line at a shelter for the homeless in Miami.
   Posner credited his business success to an ``uncanny ability''
to churn out profits.
   At age 8, he worked at his father's Baltimore grocery stores. At
13, he quit school to run them. But it was his ``genius'' in real
estate that made him a millionaire by age 25, Posner has said.
   He turned to takeovers in 1966, first targeting DWG Corp. and
soon controlling Sharon Steel and several other publicly-held firms
as he developed a reputation as a corporate raider.
   In 1985, his empire was valued at $4 billion, and he was ranked
by Business Week magazine as the nation's highest-paid executive
with an annual salary of $12.7 million.
   But that same year, his corporate empire showed signs of
weakness when Evans Products Inc., 42.5 percent owned by Posner's
NVF Co., sought Chapter 11 protection. Sharon Steel also is
reorganizing under Chapter 11.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
