<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Campbell     09-07 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Campbell,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campbell Fourth Qtr. Profit Up 4 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. on Wednesday reported its
fourth quarter profit was up by 4 percent over the same period last
year, aided by corporate acquisitions.
   Campbell posted a profit of $72 million, or 56 cents a share, in
the three months ended July 31, compared with a profit of $70
million, or 54 cents per share, in the same period last year.
   Sales during the fourth quarter rose to $1.15 billion from $1
billion in the year-earlier period, Campbell reported.
   For the full year, Campbell had net income of $274 million, or
$2.12 per share, compared with $247 million, or $1.90 per share, in
the previous year.
   Annual sales rose to $4.87 billion from $4.49 billion in the
previous year.
   Spokesman David Hackney said Campbell's sales and earnings were
boosted by acquisitions that totaled $600 million, including the
acquisition of Britain's Freshbake Foods.
   ``We had strong volume in a number of areas, including soup,
frozen food, V-8 vegetable juice, Franco-American pasta, Campbell's
beans, Pepperidge Farms and Vlasic foods,'' said Hackney.
   Campbell President R. Gordon McGovern said restructuring,
acquisitions and a renewed concentration on the company's core
businesses contributed to profit growth.
   Last year, Campbell closed four plants in Chicago; Doylestown,
Pa.; Pottstown, Pa.; and Memphis, Mich. The company also sold three
ingredient plants and its Pietro's restaurant chain.
</TEXT>
