<FILEID>AP-NR-09-07-88 2306EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Teamsters-Hollywood     09-07 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Hollywood,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Producers Make `Final' Contract Offer to Teamsters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television and film producers made a final
contract offer Wednesday to Teamster drivers and related unions,
raising the possibility of another entertainment industry strike.
   An all-night bargaining session between the Alliance of Motion
Picture and Television Producers and representatives for five basic
crafts unions concluded early Wednesday morning without a
settlement, alliance officials said.
   In addition to 2,200 Teamster drivers, the basic crafts unions
include Hollywood electricians, plumbers, laborers and plasterers.
   Each of the five unions will vote on the producers' offer
separately. If any union rejects the terms, a strike will not begin
for at least two weeks, according to producers' spokesman Herb
Steinberg.
   The Teamsters have complained that the producers' offers include
wage cuts, unfair overtime standards, and loopholes that permit
excessive non-union film production.
   Earl Bush, secretary-treasurer for the Teamsters Local 399, did
not return phone calls immediately Wednesday.
   ``The final offers are designed to make these contracts more
competitive with the working conditions at other facilities in Los
Angeles,'' alliance president Nicholas Counter said in a prepared
statement. ``If we do not accomplish that, more jobs will be lost
at the studios. Our records show that in 1987 Teamsters lost more
than $14 million in wages and benefits as compared with employment
levels in 1985. We must reverse that trend so that we can recapture
work and jobs at studios.''
   Television and film production has only recently returned to
full speed after a five-month scriptwriters strike. Producers
contend they could hire enough replacement drivers to keep
Hollywood rolling in the event of a strike.
   The Teamsters have been working without a contract since July 30.
</TEXT>
